<FIRST>r a AM-Flight103Service     12-14 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103 Service,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syracuse University Holds Observance For Flight 103 Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Syracuse University students who died
aboard Pan Am Flight 103 last December were remembered by nearly
600 people Wednesday during an all-faith vigil marking the first
anniversary of the jetliner's bombing.
   ``They have given us a precious gift. They have given us each
other,'' said the Rev. Michael Rothermel during a 45-minute service
at the university's Hendricks Chapel.
   ``In the deaths that seemed too soon and that never should have
happened that way, they gave us a grieving vulnerability to see
each other anew, to see the preciousness in each other, to see the
infinite value and worth,'' Rothermel said.
   Rothermel and five other clergymen told those in attendance the
vigil's purpose was to keep alive the memories of the 35 students
who were among 259 who perished when the jumbo jetliner exploded
over Lockerbie, Scotland, last Dec. 21.
   Eleven residents of Lockerbie also were killed when pieces of
the jet crashed onto the village.
   The students, 25 of whom attended Syracuse, were returning to
the United States after a semester studying overseas under the
university's Division of International Programs Abroad.
   The mood of Wednesday night's vigil was not as oppressive as
that which weighed on mourners last year when the chapel opened its
doors in the immediate hours after news of the crash reached the
campus.
   Heads were bowed as a silent processional of 35 students made
its way into the chapel. Each carried a single lighted candle in
memory of their dead classmates.
   Emotions became more visible as senior Marcela Honigman read
aloud the names of those who perished in the bombing, but it was
Rothermel's words that struck the deepest passions.
   ``It still hurts, doesn't it? During the past few days, the
images have beguntumbling back in my mind,'' he said.
   Many in the gathering, made up mostly of students, began
weeping, holding hands or reaching out for one another.
   ``Tonight, we keep vigil to stay awake those memories,'' he said.
   The service was scheduled for Wednesday, eight days before the
anniversary, to allow students to attend. Final examinations begin
Thursday and conclude on Dec. 20. The chapel will be open Dec. 21
for private prayer.
</TEXT>
