<FIRST>r i PM-GlobeTheater     12-14 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Globe Theater,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains of Shakespeare's Globe Get State Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of William Shakespeare's Globe Theater
have been designated an ancient monument by the government,
guaranteeing them state protection.
   The discovery of three chalk and brick foundation walls, part of
the back of the historic Globe, was announced Oct. 12 by the
British conglomerate, Hanson PLC, which owns the site, and the
Museum of London.
   The remains on the south bank of the Thames river near Southwark
Bridge were granted the protection Wednesday by Environment
Secretary Christopher Patten as an ancient monumen, said David
Trippier, heritage minister at the Department of the Environment.
   The Globe saw the first performances of Shakespeare's great
tragedies, ``Hamlet,'' ``Othello,'' ``King Lear'' and ``Macbeth.''
   The theater was built in 1599, rebuilt after a fire 14 years
later and destroyed in 1644 by the Puritans, who detested theaters.
   It appeared in panoramic drawings of London made at the time but
its exact shape and location had been a matter of argument among
scholars for some 200 years. Most of the site was covered later by
brewery buildings.
   Hanson invited archaeologists in after acquiring the site for
development and paid for the dig.
   Patten's decision brings the Globe site into the care of the
Historic Buildings and Monuments Commission, a government body of
experts dedicated to saving hstoric structures.
   Once a monument is scheduled nothing can be done to it without
consent from the environment department, acting on the commission's
advice.
   The decision follows a national outcry earlier this year when
developers were given the go-ahead to construct an office block
over the site of another Elizabethan theater near the Globe called
the Rose.
   The environment department said: ``The remains of the Globe were
very fragile whereas the remains of the Rose are safely buried
beneath a thin layer of concrete to protect them whilst development
is in progress.''
</TEXT>
