<DOCNO> AP891214-0006 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Winter     12-14 0854</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Winter,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Winter of Food, Energy Shortages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As crews put the finishing touches on
a grandiose central palace that has swallowed billions of dollars,
the masses in Romania's capital scramble to keep warm and to feed
themselves.
   Romanians stop and gape at the exclusive stores lining the
three-mile Boulevard of the Victory of Socialism, which extends
from the base of the towering white Palace of the Republic.
   Officials, speaking on condition of anonymity for fear of
retribution, said recently the Palace of the Republic and its
surroundings have cost about eight billion lei _ $800 million at
the official rate _ annually since construction began in 1984.
   Day and night, water spouts from dozens of fountains despite the
energy shortage that keeps radiators cold for most of the day and
private cars idled for lack of gasoline.
   Luxury marble-fronted apartment buildings along the boulevard,
built after about 40,000 people were uprooted, await the arrival of
Communist Party functionaries and their families sometime next year.
   Behind them lie the narrow, muddy streets of the old town, where
shoppers crowd to present identity cards for their ration of eight
ounces of meat a week _ when meat is available.
   A woman behind the counter of a dingy bar recently measured out
glasses of bitters _ the only drink available _ and laughed
derisively when asked for coffee or tea.
   ``Interconti, Interconti,'' she said, pointing in the general
direction of the luxury hotel that is reserved for Westerners
paying in hard currency.
   A sixth winter of strict food and energy rationing looms,
despite expectations of substantial improvements following the
announcement in March that the country is debt-free for the first
time in more than four decades.
   The first winter of privation was in 1983, two years after
maverick Communist President Nicolae Ceausescu launched an all-out
drive to pay off the $11 billion borrowed to industrialize his
agrarian nation.
   As part of the campaign, Romania exported much of what it
produced for hard currency _ including food and refined petroleum
products _ and cut imports to a minimum. The results were
predictable.
   The debt shrank _ Romania managed to pay back an estimated $2.5
billion annually in recent years. But empty shelves, cold and dark
homes, and long lines at gasoline stations became commonplace.
   Romanians, cowed by decades of strict secret police
surveillance, refuse to go on the record with criticisms of the
standard of living. But several raised their eyebrows recently when
told that Ceausescu, in interviews with Western media, denies there
are shortages.
   The authoritarian Ceausescu, who has defied Moscow in the past
and continues to fight the political reforms sweeping Eastern
Europe, is commonly considered to be poorly informed about the real
situation in his country, with fearful aides scrambling to present
a picture that meets his expectations.
   But in October, in a rare move probably triggered by growing
dissatisfaction, the so-called Supreme Leader made an unexpected
tour of poorly stocked Bucharest markets and promised better food
supplies.
   Although Romanians and foreign residents say food supplies have
improved somewhat since then, few appear to expect a real
turnaround _ at least this winter.
   ``The export drive appears to have slackened, but it has bled
the country dry,'' said one Western diplomat who specializes in
economic analysis. ``It's going to take a long time to build up the
kind of surplus needed to offer a steady variety of goods.''
   In addition to meat, eggs, cheese, butter and oil are under
strict ration. Other products such as salami, sausages, flour, corn
meal, toilet paper, napkins, wine and a coffee substitute are sold
only in small quantities, although not formally rationed.
   Random surveys of several butcher shops and grocery stores
recently saw long lines for the single kind of cold cuts available:
a pink, thick-skinned salami.
   In one butcher shop, where customers waiting for deep-frozen
chunks of unidentifiable meat overflowed into the street, a
shabbily dressed older woman complained loudly when told someone
already had picked up her ration.
   Heat also remains scarce. Radiators in centrally heated
buildings were on only five hours a day in early December, and
``even then they're only lukewarm,'' said one resident. Hot water
was available for three hours daily.
   Drivers are allotted about eight gallons of gasoline a month in
some counties. And although lights are somewhat brighter than in
past winters, Bucharest remains dim compared even to other East
European capitals.
   Compounding the hardships are mammoth construction projects
decreed by Ceausescu, the last hard-line Soviet bloc leader, in a
drive to put his imprimature on what state media call the Ceausescu
Epoch.
   Western estimates put a price tag of $2 billion on a 35-mile
canal completed in 1984 linking the Danube above its estuary to the
Black Sea.
   Most of the ships plying the canal are Romanian, and revenues
from user fees have been modest as a result, Western diplomats say.
Construction on another canal of the same magnitude that is to
connect Bucharest to the Danube began in 1987.
</TEXT>
