<FIRST>r a AM-AtlantaSchools     12-14 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Schools,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide to School Superintendent Losing Job After Certificate Disclosure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City School Superintendent J. Herome Harris' top
aide is losing his job because he lacks proper qualifications, and
Harris himself must be recertified to keep his job, the school
board ruled Wednesday.
   The contract of the aide, associate superintendent Ronald H.
Lewis, will not be renewed when it expires Dec. 31, the board
decided during a six-hour meeting Wednesday night.
   State officials said Lewis, Harris' top aide for 15 months,
lacks an approved bachelor of education degree or its equivalent.
   ``He isn't certified, he's in over his head, and there's a big
question about whether we're going to keep him,'' board member Bob
Waymer said earlier.
   Lewis said he had been working to obtain a certificate since he
arrived in Atlanta, but he said he did not know until Monday that
he had been turned down.
   The board also gave Harris until Jan. 1 to get recertified to
keep his job. Harris, who allowed his temporary superintendent's
certification to lapse four months ago, said he needs one college
course to earn a new certificate.
   The course Harris needs is similar to one he taught for 14 years
at Brooklyn College. State rules require that he finish certain
courses within 12 months on the job, but Harris has said he let the
deadline pass because ``I couldn't see myself having to sit in a
class that I taught.''
   The board's resolution, passed unanimously, said Harris should
be reprimanded for not disclosing ``all significant information
concerning the appointment of Dr. Ronald Lewis as associate
superintendent, for not informing the board that his own temporary
certificate had expired on August 31, 1989, and not communicating
openly and effectively with the board of education.''
</TEXT>
