<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DetroitPoliceProbe     12-14 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Police Probe,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Questions Over Drug Fund Taints Detroit Police Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY L. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While an epidemic of drug-related crime plagues
Detroit, allegations of misuse of a secret police fund used to
fight the drug war are threatening to topple the city's
long-respected police chief.
   William Hart, a former vice cop who has a dozen meritorious
service awards in 37 years on the force, has denied misusing the
$1.4 million fund used to pay informants and finance undercover
drug buys in the nation's seventh-largest city.
   However, records show that he signed checks totaling $72,000 to
California-based companies that paid the rent on a Beverly Hills,
Calif., home occupied by his daughter and son-in-law. A report in
the Detroit Free Press on Tuesday said investigators found several
checks written to cash and signed by Hart.
   The FBI and a federal grand jury are investigating the fund and
a former civilian deputy chief whose whereabouts is unknown. No one
has been charged with a crime.
   ``I had no idea that money was used to pay for a house in
California, Michigan or Ohio, or anywhere else on earth,'' the
65-year-old Hart has said. ``With God as my witness, I swear I did
not do that.
   There have been many calls for Hart to resign or at least step
aside during the probe. A recent poll of Free Press readers found
79 percent in favor of Hart resigning.
   But Mayor Coleman Young, who is Hart's boss, said he is standing
behind the chief. As he has often before, Young blamed the media
for sensationalizing the story.
   ``The man has been tried and convicted without even a chance of
acquittal,'' Young said Monday night at a news conference.
   The City Council voted last week to subpoena 49 checks from the
fund after the Police Department barred Auditor General Roger Short
from seeing them. The department has until Dec. 19 to surrender the
records.
   Young has said he will not release the checks, signed by Hart,
which total more than $1 million. The mayor said they might hamper
confidential police operations.
   Young has assigned Deputy Police Chief James D. Bannon to take
over an internal police investigation that was begun by Hart.
   City officials say they are unsure if Hart is involved with the
alleged mismanagement of funds, but they agree that the pending
investigation could interfere with his job.
   The Police Department was an issue in the recent mayoral
election, which Young won handily. Challenger Tom Barrow said
during the campaign that he would revamp the department and fire
Hart if elected.
   The FBI's investigation focuses on whether top police officials
took money from the secret fund by diverting proceeds to dummy
corporations owned by Kenneth Weiner, a former civilian deputy
police chief.
   Hart has blamed Weiner for the misuse of the funds. He said he
made legal disbursements to Weiner, a former friend, and that
Weiner used the funds illegally.
   ``It's that simple, he stole money,'' Hart said.
   Weiner was in charge of performing sensitive security work for
the city from 1980 to 1986. He left after an investigation into his
involvement with speculative precious metals investments in which
several wealthy Detroit residents allegedly lost thousands of
dollars.
   A federal grand jury has subpoenaed records at the University of
Michigan in Ann Arbor, where Weiner worked as a part-time security
consultant. Weiner's trail has led from Michigan to California to
Georgia.
   The secret fund scandal further taints the Police Department,
which came under fire for drug use by officers.
   Nine of nearly 3,000 police officers screened for drug use
tested positive earlier this year. The Detroit Board of Police
Commissioners suspended six officers for having cocaine in their
urine. Young said three others volunteered for drug treatment
before being tested.
   Drug testing became an issue last year after an off-duty police
officer was shot to death outside a suspected crack house. Around
the same time, 14 other officers were suspended for using drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
