<FIRST>r a PM-GangBounty     12-14 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gang Bounty,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Protect Activist After Gang Allegedly Issues Bounty Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The word on the street is that Georgette Watson's
head is worth $5,000. If she's shot and doesn't die, it's $1,000.
   That's how badly street gangs want to get rid of the founder of
Drop-A-Dime, a hot line that fields tips on drug pushers. Watson is
under 24-hour police surveillance and says she can accept that _
for now. But she won't live in a fishbowl forever.
   ``I want to be free,'' she said Wednesday. ``They feel they can
kill anyone who goes against their stance. This is a fight not just
for me, but for the whole community. If we take a stand now we
won't have to pay later.''
   Deputy Superintendent William Celester said police informants
had received ``solid tips'' this week that local gang members had
set a price on Watson's life.
   ``Georgette Watson has ... been getting various threats ever
since she began to speak out about the drug dealers and everything
else,'' he said. ``From time to time, we've offered her police
protection and she's always turned those offers down. This time
we're insisting.''
   The idea of gang bounties is not particularly new. Tensions ran
high this fall when similar threats were made on police officers
patrolling this city's Dorchester, Mattapan and Roxbury
neighborhoods.
   ``Georgette has become a symbol of the little person standing
up,'' Celester said. ``She's been out there standing up for the
community and fighting back. She's become a symbol that these gangs
want to stop.''
   The 46-year-old knows she's in danger but prefers not to think
about it too much. There's something broader and more important at
stake, she said.
   ``They're violating my freedom to take a stand,'' she said. ``We
have to let them know that they will not control this community or
control people they disagree with.''
   Watson is willing temporarily to accept the constant presence of
police, the shadows of two officers parked outside her home each
night. She's willing to stay away from Drop-A-Dime hot line's
office and cancel speaking engagements.
   But the mother of three says she knows who the kids are behind
the bounty offer. She's heard it on the streets and now she's using
those same streets to put out a message of her own.
   ``I want to talk to them,'' Watson said, adding that her only
conditions for the meeting are that it take place in a daylit,
neutral location and that two or three community escorts be present.
   ``I've tried to go out there and meet with them and they refuse
to meet with me,'' she said. ``I'd like to just go up there where
they are with the whole comunity, really send them a message.''
   Since about Nov. 17, Watson said, a different message has been
clear.
   ``I'm worth $1,000 if they shoot me and $5,000 if they kill
me,'' she said. ``They also want a 14-year-old to do it so he won't
have to do any time. They're organized.''
   The bounty offer is good only through Jan. 1, she said.
   The Rev. Bruce Wall, who preaches his anti-gang message at a
local roller-skating rink, heard about the bounty early this week.
If these kids want war, he said, then that's what they'll get.
   ``After I heard, I drove right up to the gang's turf,'' Wall
said. ``I was angry and stopped the first teen-ager I saw walking.
   ``I explained that Georgette Watson was my friend and a certain
youth gang was against her. I also explained that if they attack
Georgette they'll be answering to a lot of angry people and someone
is going to get hurt''
   Community leaders said the gang picked Watson because of her
high profile and the attendant promise of attention.
   ``The word is they're just trying to make a name for themselves
and this will do it,'' Wall said.
   Watson says she is frightened, but resolved.
   ``I've lived a good life,'' she said. ``I love my job, love what
I've done for the community and if this is my time, then this is my
time.''
   It's really only in the evenings that she's frightened. It's in
the evenings, she said, that ``these people do their thing.''
</TEXT>
