<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-SantaCharlie     12-14 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Santa Charlie,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa Suit Befits Burial for `Santa Charlie'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrilling children as Santa Claus was
the delight of Charlie Cather's life, so he will be buried in a
Santa suit.
   For 20 years, Cather was known to children as ``Santa Charlie.''
On Tuesday, the 65-year-old retiree died of complications from
diabetes that confined him to a Huntsville Hospital bed as the
Christmas season approached.
   ``One of the last things he told me, maybe a month ago, was that
he had to turn things around so he could get out and be Santa Claus
again,'' longtime friend Yvonne Meigs said.
   ``Being Santa Claus was one of his greatest delights in life,
and it's so ironic that this had to happen at Christmas. ... when
he was always there for everyone else.''
   In the spring and summer, the retired shoe salesman volunteered
for telethons and other community fund-raisers, playing Santa at
``Christmas in August'' parties for young fans of the Huntsville
Stars baseball team and taking children with cerebral palsy to
ballgames.
   In the fall, Cather began touring with Reindeer Inc., a
Huntsville company that shows reindeer throughout the nation,
before returning home to sit patiently in a shopping mall,
listening to whispered requests and assuring youngsters that Santa
was watching over them as Christmas approached.
   ``Charlie believed in the spirit of love and generosity, the
kind of spirit that touches other people's lives with kindness, the
kind of spirit that is Santa Claus,'' the Rev. Carl Malm, Cather's
pastor for the last 10 years, said as he prepared for Friday's
funeral.
   Cather, who was born in Canton, Ohio, brought his family to
Huntsville about 25 years ago.
   Driving his family home from a trip to Guntersville in 1970,
Cather lost his wife and two of four sons in a fatal wreck. Friends
said he may have turned to Santa Claus to recover from the
emotional impact of the tragedy.
   As Cather's hair turned naturally frosty, he grew a white beard
and his paunch expanded until it shook when he laughed.
   ``He was Santa Claus because he never quit believing,'' Larry
Holder of Reindeer Inc. recalled. ``When you quit believing you get
old. ... and he never quit believing, he had a gleam in his eye
till the very end.''
</TEXT>
