<FIRST>r a PM-People-LovelyLips     12-14 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Lovely Lips,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush, Bo Jackson, Lech Walesa Make ``Most Beautiful Lips''
List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush invited Americans to read his
lips, but the first lady moved her lips to get more kids to read,
earning her a place on the list of the world's 12 ``Most Beautiful
Lips.''
   Bo Jackson, Lech Walesa and other lippy leviathans joined
Barbara Bush as winners of the annual tongue-in-cheek awards put
out by Blistex Inc., which knows that while loose lips sink ships,
chapped lips sell Blistex.
   Mrs. Bush captured the ``best-read lips'' honor.
   ``We felt Barbara Bush was doing more than her husband,
particularly to encourage reading literacy,'' said Richard K.
Green, the company's executive vice president.
   When it came to ships, Exxon Chairman Lawrence Rawl was named
``slickest lips'' for his public statements after the March 28
Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   Walesa, the leader of Poland's Solidarity labor movement, made
the list with the ``most solid lips,'' even though his lips are
often hidden by his walrus mustache.
   Jackson, star of the football's Los Angeles Raiders and
baseball's Kansas City Royals, took the trophy for his
``double-duty lips.''
   And Wayne Gretzky of the National Hockey League's Los Angeles
Kings scored with the ``most pointed lips.'' Gretzky, who broke
Gordie Howe's all-time NHL scoring record this year, is the only
person ever to make the list twice in its 10-year history, Green
said.
   Late night talk show host Arsenio Hall had the ``hippest lips,''
while Oprah Winfrey the ``fast-est lips'' for sharing her diet
results on her daytime talk show.
   Roseanne Barr, meanwhile, got the ``most no-holds-Barred lips''
award for her hit sitcom and best-selling autobiography, and
``Today'' show news anchor Deborah Norville made it for ``today's
lips.''
   Movie star Michelle Pfeiffer was rated ``fabulips'' for her role
in the film ``The Fabulous Baker Boys.''
   ``Whose lips?'' belonged to Peter Townshend of the rock group
The Who, which made a reunion tour, while the ``most far-sided
lips'' were those of cartoonist Gary Larson, whose ``The Far Side''
appears in more than 900 daily newspapers.
   The lips list was begun in 1980 to make people think about lip
care during the winter, Green said.
   ``We wouldn't take someone who didn't have good-lookng lips, but
it has more to do with their involvement in the news,'' he said.
</TEXT>
