<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     12-14 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sea of gleaming brass bobbed in unison for
a holiday concert that might best be described as, like, totally
tuba-ular.
   Two hundred musicians clutching the imposing instruments offered
the unusual ``Merry TubaChristmas'' program Tuesday at the elegant
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.
   Elephantine sousaphones were positioned at the top of a
staircase. Below were double-belled euphoniums, smaller orchestral
tubas, and even an ophicleide, an instrument that preceded the tuba
more than 150 years ago.
   ``I can't even hear myself, but I know I'm playing,'' said
Roland Boyer, 13.
   Santa's ho-ho-ho seems most suitable for the deep, throaty
horns. But the scores of tuba players made a joyful noise in the
program organized by Indiana University music professor Harvey
Phillips, who conceived of the idea in 1974 as a tribute to the
great tuba composers.
   The hourlong Christmas concert now plays in more than 100 cities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Grimes has been offered sex in return for
car tows and repairs. Frank Ferra had to turn down a 400-pound hog.
Seems like a tow truck in need is a friend, indeed.
   Grimes and Ferra are garage managers whose work includes
servicing vehicles on the 470-miles Pennsylvania Turnpike, where
about 30,000 vehicles broke down last year.
   Sometimes what they're offered by motorists strapped for cash
when the bill arrives is a jump start in itself.
   ``When it's late at night and they need gas or something like
that,'' there's no limit to what motorists will offer for a tow,
said Grimes, manager of Smeltz Auto Body and Towing in Monroeville.
``I never took them up on it.''
   Ferra got a wedding ring from a man who put it up as collateral
for repairs made to his car. He never returned.
   ``That ring was worth $30. His bill was $75. We ate that one,''
said Ferra, owner of Ferra Automotive Services in Sharpsburg.
   On rare occasions, the services will accept collateral from
motorists who don't have cash, credit cards or checks to pay for
towing or repairs.
   Usually motorists offer things like watches and spare tires. But
there are exceptions.
   ``I've had guys leave their wives at the shop and run to the
bank to get money,'' said Ed Reese, owner of Reese's Towing.
   ``They all came back,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa howled ``bribery!'' when Mrs. Claus
placed brightly colored gifts in front of the judge. But that
didn't stop a judgment authorizing Mrs. Claus to share gift-giving
Christmas rights with her husband.
   Judge George T. Choppelas also declared their sleigh ``community
property,'' changed Mrs. Claus' title to ``Ms.,'' and declared her
``emancipated from any household duties'' and free to accompany her
large spouse on his airborne tours of the world.
   A courtroom jammed with spectators, reporters and photographers
broke into cheers Wednesday at the conclusion of a rather unruly
and holiday-happy 60th session of San Francisco's mock Court of
Historical Review.
   The just-for-fun court is a 14-year San Francisco tradition
staged in a real City Hall courtroom, with a real judge, real
lawyers, clerks and stenographers. Only the witnesses are phony.
   Watching with interest were Municipal Court Judge Diane Wick,
dressed as a female Santa, and lawyer Robert J. McCarthy,
pillow-paunched with a tatty white beard and wig. He sat on the
lady Santa's lap.
   ``It's obvious that Santa Claus is a woman,'' claimed San
Francisco Supervisor Angela Alioto, who insisted that the Italian
female Santa Claus, ``Befana,'' leaps down chimneys to dole out
toys to good kids, and chunks of coal to the bad ones.
</TEXT>
