<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-US 1stLd-Writethru a0429 12-14 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenades Fired At U.S. Compound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs with background on U.S. evacuations during coup,
warnings that mutineers might turn to terrorism.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified assailants fired two
rifle grenades Thursday at a U.S. government residential compound,
causing minor damage and no injuries, U.S. officials said.
   There was no indication of who fired the grenades, which
exploded about noon at the Seafront compound. But the incident
occurred following threats against U.S. interests by rebel soldiers
whose coup attempt failed last week.
   A U.S. Embassy statement said the grenades were fired
``indiscriminately'' at the compound, which includes the American
club, an embassy commissary and housing areas for embassy and
military personnel.
   Embassy spokesman David Andriessen said Americans had been
warned to avoid travel to the embassy compound and other U.S.
installations in the capital for the next few hours.
   During the recent coup attempt, hundreds of American families
were evacuated to Seafront to escape fighting between mutineers and
government forces in the financial district, Makati.
   Rebels who sought to topple President Corazon Aquino expressed
anger at the United States after American F-4 Phantom jets flew air
cover for government forces on Dec.1, the first day of the coup
attempt.
   U.S. jets did not fire a shot but their presence was considered
crucial in turning the tide against mutineers, who had launched air
attacks against Malacanang Palace and military camps.
   Rebels gave up their last position Saturday when about 400
mutineers surrendered at an air base near Cebu, 350 miles south of
the capital.
   On Wednesday, Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said remnants of the
rebel force still retain the capability to launch ``terrorist
attacks, sabotage and assassination.''
   Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, chief of the Capital Command, said
there ``are indications that they are moving'' toward terrorism to
continue the struggle against Mrs. Aquino.
   ``I hope they will be reasonable enough that they will be men of
conscience,'' Aguirre said. ``They should not resort to terrorist
acts that will prejudice innocent lives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
