<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-USSIowa     12-14 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-USS Iowa,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Rushed to Judgment in Iowa Case, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a House Armed Services
investigative panel contends the Navy irresponsibly rushed to
judgment in citing gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig as likely to blame
for the USS Iowa shipboard explosion.
   Summing up two days of hearings on the blast that killed 47
sailors, Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., told Vice Adm. Joseph S.
Donnell III ``you've pointed your finger when there's that little
chance'' the blast could have been accidental.
   ``Wouldn't it have been better off to say `we don't know,'''
Mavroules asked the vice admiral.
   ``We believe we do know,'' Donnell said, alluding to the Navy's
finding that Hartwig most likely caused the blast by inserting some
type of detonator between bags of gunpowder in one of the ship's
16-inch guns.
   ``I find it quite irresponsible that the Navy would issue a
report on a probable cause rather than have the documented evidence
that they can prove,'' Mavroules said.
   Mavroules made the statement after Hartwig's onetime friend and
shipmate, Kendall Truitt, testified _ with the backing of another
sailor _ that he thought the gun-turret explosion was an accident.
   ``Clayton Michael Hartwig did not cause the explosion,'' Truitt
said. ``I do not think he committed suicide. I believe the report
is very misleaing.''
   ``It's a big coverup, in my opinion,'' he said. ``Clayton
Hartwig was not the suicidal freak they make him out to be.''
   As members of Hartwig's family looked on, Truitt and Petty
Officer John Mullahy disputed the Navy's finding, citing personal
observations about Hartwig and concerns about technical problems
aboard the Iowa.
   Mullahy said that on the night before the explosion, he and
Hartwig discussed his impending transfer to London and the seaman
even made a list of the items he needed to buy.
   In addition, Hartwig didn't learn until the morning of the blast
that he was going to be at the center gun in the No. 2 turret, ``so
there would have been not time for planning'' a suicide, Truitt
said.
   Mullahy and Truitt were part of the crew engaged in the firing
exercises that day. Both repeated the last words of Petty Officer
Eric Lawrence, who was in the center gun position with Hartwig.
   ``He (Lawrence) wouldn't have had as his last words, `I'm not
ready (to fire) yet. We've got a problem in here,''' Truitt said.
   ``He would have said, `Hey, excuse me guys, he put a bomb in
here,''' Truitt said.
   ``It tells me the situation was not dangerous, was not
life-threatening. If Clay was going to blow up the ship, Lawrence
would have stopped him. They were literally standing shoulder to
shoulder.''
   Truitt said his theory is that the blast was caused by a
defective hydraulic rammer _ the piece of equipment used to shove
the powder bags up against the projectile.
   He said he had a problem with a rammer on the left gun in No. 2
gun turret about a year earlier, describing it as behaving like a
transmission stuck between neutral and drive. He theorized that the
rammer might have ``suddenly taken off,'' putting too much pressure
on the propellant.
   Mullahy, who has served in the Navy for 19 years and was
assigned to the Iowa in December 1988, said a possible explanation
for the explosion could be found in the World War II-era gun powder
bags that were improperly stored.
   Navy officers have said that while some safety lapses were
discovered in the course of the investigation, there was no
substantial risk involving the 16-inch guns and the powder used to
fire them.
   During the course of the hearing, Mullahy said Hartwig and
Truitt did not talk to each other for several months, although
Truitt was the beneficiary on Hartwig's $101,000 life insurance
policy.
   ``They hated each other,'' Mullahy said.
   Nevertheless, Hartwig never had Truitt removed as the
beneficiary on the policy. Truitt said that in settlement of the
policy claim, he gave Hartwig's family $2,500, his lawyer $40,000,
and kept the rest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AT&amp;T-Soviets     12-14 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T-Soviets,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Seeks Permission to Boost Communication to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. wants to
make it easier for Americans to reach out and touch someone in the
Soviet Union.
   AT&amp;T said Wednesday that if the Federal Communications
Commission approves, it will start routing operator-assisted,
direct dialed, data and video services onto the Soviet Intersputnik
satellite system for the first time.
   AT&amp;T currently has the only Western phone facilities to the
Soviet Union, with other long distance companies leasing space on
AT&amp;T lines. The traffic is carried on 32 circuits by undersea cable
and land lines, as well as the Intelsat satellite consortium.
   Despite these links, which since last month has included AT&amp;T
direct dial service to Moscow, ``demand still far exceeds existing
capacity,'' the phone company said.
   AT&amp;T plans to add 24 more circuits in January, and ``the
proposal we made today could add as many as 150 additional
circuits,'' AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said.
   The plan would require construction of a new $1 million antenna
at AT&amp;T's Roaring Creek earth station near Catawissa, Pa., Linnen
said.
   It would take six months to construct the antenna, which then
would be aimed at an Intersputnik satellite located in a
geostationary orbit 22,300 miles above a point just off the coast
of Liberia.
   Intersputnik is a consortium of 15 socialist countries that
provides satellite-delivered communications among its member
nations. Currently, Cable News Network uses Intersputnik for
satellite news feeds, Linnen noted.
   In a letter to President Bush announcing its new plan, AT&amp;T
Chairman Robert Allen said, ``Expanded communications capacity will
result in direct economic benefits to the United States as we
expand world trade through commercial relationships with Eastern
Europe.''
   Linnen said presidential approval was not needed for the plan,
which he said did not involve any national security issues such as
transferring high-tech equipment to communist nations.
   He said the plan, which was negotiated over the past 12 months,
was forwarded to Bush as a ``matter of courtesy'' given Bush's
statements since the Malta summit on improving U.S.-Soviet
relations.
   An AT&amp;T-Intersputnik link would be a blow to Intelsat, the
117-nation satellite cooperative that handles the bulk of
international telephone traffic. Intelsat recently launched the
first of a series of five new satellites it plans to put aloft over
the next two years to handle increasing international
communications traffic.
   AT&amp;T said the Soviets prefer using their own satellites for
additional circuits because Moscow then incurs expenses solely
within the Soviet Union, payable in rubles rather than in Western
currencies. Rubles are not traded officially in international money
markets.
   Intelsat officials would not comment Wednesday.
   Under the proposal, AT&amp;T and the Soviets would continue to use
Intelsat for some circuits and would split future increases in
demand for circuits among undersea cables, Intelsat satellites and
Intersputnik satellites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
