<FIRST>r w PM-US-Poland     12-14 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Adds $200 Million to Loan Plan for Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is pumping $200
million into a loan package to carry Poland beyond the Christmas
season, and challenging wealthy nations to make good on promises of
aid to Warsaw and Hungary.
   Trying to bolster the process of democratic reforms in Eastern
Europe, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said, ``pledges alone
aren't enough.''
   Baker, speaking in Brussels to a gathering of two dozen foreign
ministers, joined the White House in announcing a $200 million
contribution to a multi-nation, $500 million loan for Poland as it
awaits a comprehensive aid package from the International Monetary
Fund.
   The loan ``reflects support for Poland's economic reform program
designed to restore sustained growth,'' said deputy presidential
press secretary Stephen Hart.
   Other countries contributing are Belgium, Canada, West Germany,
France, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands, Sweden, Switzerland and
Britain, the Treasury Department said.
   The loan is in addition to a previously announced $1 billion
stabilization fund for Poland. The United States is contributing a
$200 million grant for that.
   In addition, President Bush last month signed a $938 million aid
package over three years for Poland and Hungary. Most of the money
is earmarked for Warsaw.
   Referring to the fall of hardline communist governments in
Eastern Europe, Baker said, ``It is our task to support this
courageous reform effort.
   ``After the streets empty of demonstrators, after the people
select new leaders, after governments become the servants of the
people, after all this _ the economies must put food on the table
and goods on the shelves of stores,'' he said.
   The foreign ministers in Brussels committed their governments to
a coordinated assistance program valued at up to $6 billion over
the next several years.
   Most of the aid will be in the form of investment and trade
credits not to be paid out immediately.
   On Capitol Hill, Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter said
that more than money, Poland needs a Western-style legal system,
accounting system, banking system, marketing and distribution
systems and the private ownership of assets.
   ``Poland will not be able to attract foreign investment until
the institution building takes place,'' said Yeutter, who recently
led a high-level U.S. delegation to Warsaw to assess its economic
needs.
   ``As important as all of our aid programs may be, Poland really
needs people help, institutional help, more than it needs monetary
assistance,'' Yeutter said. ``Without that, it will be wasted, it
will be money lost.''
   He testified before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Speaking to reporters later, Yeutter acknowledged that ``some
assistance will be of help'' in helping Poland to deal with its
immediate problems.
   ``But it's not just a matter of throwing money at Poland,'' he
said. ``The situation in Poland and the rest of Eastern Europe is
not comparable to Western Europe immediately after World War II''
when the United States organized the Marshall Plan to spur economic
recovery.
   Contrary to Yeutter's testimony, economist John Kenneth
Galbraith told the Senate panel that a Marshall Plan is precisely
what is needed, and needed soon.
   ``There is a notion as regards Poland, as also regards to the
Soviet Union and other socialist countries, that such is the magic
of the market that a movement in that direction will produce
immediate and quite wonderful results,''
   ``This, to put it bluntly, is idiot ideology,'' he said.
</TEXT>
