<FIRST>r w PM-HHSBudget-HeadStart     12-14 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HHS Budget-Head Start,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House to Seek Funding Increase for Head Start Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House agrees to propose a funding
increase of at least 3.5 percent next year for the pre-school Head
Start program for low-income children, according to a government
source.
   The final figure for President Bush's proposed 1991 budget is
still being worked out and could go higher, but the source said the
White House has agreed to seek at least $49 million more for the
$1.39 billion program.
   The Department of Health and Human Services had proposed such an
increase in Head Start funding for the fiscal year beginning Oct.
1, 1990. The Office of Management and Budget has agreed to propose
``a minimum increase of $49 million,'' said an HHS source who spoke
Wednesday on the condition of anonymity.
   Bush is to send his proposed 1991 spending plan to Congress on
Jan. 22.
   Congress approved $1.39 billion for Head Start for the current
fiscal year, $99 million less than the administration had sought.
   Head Start _ a nutrition, health screening and education program
that helps prepare low-income children for school _ is the only
major unresolved budget issue between the department and the White
House budget office, said sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Agreement has been reached to propose trimming growth in
Medicare spending by about $9 billion. Without any changes in
payment schedules, the program is projected to cost $130 billion in
the next fiscal year, but the administration will propose cutting
that to about $121 billion, sources said.
   Secretary Louis Sullivan fared well in negotiations with OMB on
the National Institutes of Health and spending for AIDS.
   The department had proposed raising the NIH budget to $7.2
billion next year, while OMB wanted to freeze spending at this
year's level, around $6.6 billion. The final figure will be ``over
$7 billion,'' the HHS source said.
   AIDS spending will be proposed at around $1.7 billion, the
source said. Sullivan had sought $1.76 billion. OMB initially
wanted to keep spending at the $1.6 billion Congress approved for
this year, which was slightly less than the administration had
sought.
   One recommendation that Sullivan lost was to require states to
expand Medicaid coverage to cover all pregnant women and infants
with incomes up to 150 percent of the poverty line. Governors have
called for the federal government to hold the line on Medicaid
expansions.
   The reductions in projected Medicare growth would be achieved by
trimming increases in payments to hospitals and physicians, but HHS
officials say benefits under the program would not be affected.
   Hospitals would take the largest hit, sources say. The
administration's proposal would chop more than $3.5 billion from
projected payment schedules for hospitals, including about $1.5
billion less for capital equipment reimbursements and $1 billion
less in payments to teaching hospitals, which receive more money
than other hospitals to compensate for their costs in training
physicians.
   Michael Bromberg, executive director of the Federation of
American Health Systems, which represents private hospitals, said
Congress is unlikely to accept such large cutbacks in hospital
payments.
   ``They went so far in these numbers that there's going to be a
pretty quick reaction against it,'' he said.
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., said she has gotten 27 Republican
senators to sign a letter telling Bush that ``any proposal to make
significant cuts in the Medicare hospital program is likely to face
serious opposition on Capitol Hill.''
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, ranking member on the House Ways and
Means Committee, is circulating a similar letter among
representatives.
</TEXT>
