<FIRST>r a PM-MansionRape     12-14 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mansion Rape,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Prosecutor Investigates Reported Rape at S.D. Governor's
Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special prosecutor has been appointed to
investigate a report of a rape at the governor's mansion, and Gov.
George Mickelson said the investigation is causing agony for his
family.
   The special prosecutor, Craig Kennedy, said Wednesday he expects
the Pierre Police Department to complete its investigation into the
rape report within the next few days.
   ``We'll make a decision on what legal steps are appropriate
after we've received the results and completed the investigation,''
said Kennedy, who is the Yankton County state's attorney.
   Kennedy and other officials refused to discuss details of the
allegations.
   Police received a report on Nov. 30 alleging that there had been
a forcible rape at the mansion two days earlier. A statement on a
police log sheet said: ``Four boys at mansion raped her.''
   The Republican governor was in Washington at a U.S. Department
of Agriculture conference on Nov. 28. His wife, Linda, was in Texas
at the time.
   The Mickelsons' 17-year-old son, David, a senior at Riggs High
School, is the only other family member who is a permanent resident
of the mansion. The Mickelsons' two older children do not live in
Pierre.
   Asked whether David was traveling with either parent on Nov. 28,
Mickelson press secretary Gretchen Lord Anderson replied: ``We
don't feel that where David was is relevant.''
   Mickelson has not met with reporters since the rape was reported.
   In a statement Wednesday, the governor and Mrs. Mickelson said
they were pleased that the local prosecutor has said preliminary
indications are that no rape took place at the governor's residence.
   ``Our family is going through one of the most agonizing times we
have ever experienced. We have always held closely to the principle
that it is not how you fall that counts the most, but how you get
up and carry on,'' the Mickelsons said.
   ``We very much appreciate the compassion which so many people
have expressed to us during this difficult period, and we ask your
continued prayers and understanding,'' the statement said.
   Hughes County State's Attorney Mark Moreno said he appointed a
special prosecutor because he wanted to avoid the appearance of any
impropriety or conflict of interest.
   Moreno said one of his law partners, Mark Barnett, intends to
run for attorney general next year. He said another law partner has
represented the family of one of the people involved in the case.
   When Moreno acknowledged the investigation was being conducted
earlier this week, he said: ``From what Pierre police have told me,
preliminary indications are that there was not a rape at the
mansion.''
   Kennedy, who has six year's experience as a prosecutor, said he
hasn't seen any written report on the case but has talked
informally with investigating police officers.
   The special prosecutor said the fact that he's a Democrat and
the governor is a Republican won't affect his handling of the
investigation.
   ``I'm going to handle this case like I would any other, and
political affiliation has nothing to do with it,'' Kennedy said.
</TEXT>
