<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil     12-14 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil's Presidential Race Turns Ugly</HEAD>
<UNK>By TODD LEWAN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race for president is getting
seamier as it gets closer, with the former girfriend of one
candidate accusing him of hating blacks and trying to bribe her
into having an abortion.
   The latest public opinion polls say the candidate, socialist
Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, has drawn nearly even with rightist
opponent Fernando Collor de Mello in the last days before Sunday's
election.
   An estimated 250,000 Brazilians gathered in Rio for a da Silva
rally on Wednesday, the biggest political turnout of the campaign.
   ``I will unmask Collor on national TV and show Brazil that he is
the greatest political lie this country has ever seen,'' da Silva
told the crowd, referring to a nationally televised debate to be
held tonight.
   Meanwhile, Collor de Mello concluded his campaign with a
rain-shortened rally in the southeastern city of Belo Horizonte. He
told about 12,000 people he would ``save the country from the
dictatorial candidate of the Workers Party.
   ``This leftist will not turn the green and yellow colors of our
flag red,'' Collor de Mello said.
   Candidate rhetoric isn't the only blunt talk in the campaign. On
Tuesday and Wednesday, Collor de Mello's organization had
commercials broadcast showing a former da Silva girlfriend.
   ``He ruined my life,'' Miriam Cordeiro says.
   Ms. Cordeiro said da Silva ``couldn't stand blacks.'' Most of
Brazil's 150 million people are black or mixed-race.
   She also accuses him of offering her money to have an abortion.
   The candidate says his daughter, Lurian, now 15, was born after
an affair with Ms. Cordeiro following the death of his first wife
in 1969.
   ``He offered me money to get an abortion,'' Ms. Cordeiro said in
the spot. ``When she was born, I put her in his lap and said `Now
go ahead and kill her, because when she was in my belly I wouldn't
let you.'''
   Da Silva, in his own TV spot Wednesday, was shown standing
beside Lurian. ``Lurian was the product of a gesture of love,'' he
said.
   After his affair with Ms. Cordeiro, da Silva married Marisa
Leticia, the widow of a slain taxi driver.
   Ms. Cordeiro says in the spot that her testimony was voluntary,
but a former campaign worker for Collor de Mello claims the woman
was paid about $23,000.
   The Brazilian press has roundly condemned Collor de Mello's
tactics.
   Da Silva's campaign coordinator, Vladimir Pomar, called the
interview ``a low blow.''
   Analysts say Collor de Mello, a 40-year-old advocate of a free
market, has assumed a right-wing posture of late and turned the
campaign into an ideological showdown in an attempt to depict da
Silva as the radical leader of a backward party.
   The tactic is seen as a response to polls showing da Silva
gaining ground.
   A poll taken this week by the respected DataFolha Institute
showed Collor de Mello with 46 percent, da Silva with 45 percent
and 6 percent undecided.
   DataFolha interviewed 5,250 voters. The margin of error was 3
percent.
   A poll released Wednesday by the Toledo and Associates
Institute, based on interviews this week with 4,073 people, said
44.7 percent supported Collor de Mello and 44.2 favored da Silva.
The margin of error was 2 percent.
   Just 10 days ago, Collor de Mello led by 15 points.
   Sunday's election is a runoff. The two candidates were the top
vote-getters in a 21-candidate field in the first round on Nov. 15.
   Analysts say da Silva's campaign took off last week after a
strong performance during a nationally televised debate with Collor
de Mello.
   Da Silva also gained votes by airing effective television ads
and by consolidating his support among other prominent left-wing
politicians.
   The election is Brazil's first popular balloting for president
since 1960, when Janio Quadros was elected. He resigned after seven
months in office, and three years later the armed forces took power
and ruled the country until 1985.
   Civilian President Jose Sarney was chosen by an electoral
college controlled by the generals.
</TEXT>
