<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS     12-14 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: AIDS Victims' Blood Shows High Levels of Virus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS patients' blood contains hundreds of times
more virus than doctors once thought, and a single AIDS-tainted
syringe may carry enough to cause 700 infections, according to a
study published today.
   Until now, the amount of AIDS virus in victims' bodies seemed
strangely low, considering the ravages it inflicts. But new
measurements show those estimates were wrong, and the actual levels
are very high.
   In the typical AIDS patients' blood, the virus infects one in
400 of the broad class of white blood cells known as lymphocytes
and monocytes. Previously, scientists believed the virus had
penetrated just one in 100,000.
   ``The answers were quite surprising,'' said Dr. David D. Ho, who
directed the project. ``We found that the levels within the blood
cells were orders of magnitude higher.''
   The study also found that even when infected people seem well,
the virus produces new copies of itself that float freely outside
of cells in the blood plasma. This finding challenges the widely
held belief that the infection frequently lies dormant for years
after the initial infection.
   Ho's research at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles was
published in today's New England Journal of Medicine along with a
related paper by Dr. Robert W. Coombs and colleagues from the
University of Washington.
   Because the level of virus in infected people had seemed to be
so low, some researchers have questioned whether the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) really causes AIDS.
   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. David Baltimore and Mark B.
Feinberg of the Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research said
the latest data ``should dispel any lingering doubts about whether
HIV is the true culprit in AIDS.''
   Ho said the amount of virus in victims' bodies may be high
enough to account for all the damage seen in acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   ``A few years ago, we were struggling with the apparent dilemma
that we have a lot of immune destruction and yet very little virus
to account for that destruction,'' said Ho. ``Therefore people in
the field are looking for indirect mechanisms by which the immune
system is damaged. Maybe if we have this much virus present we
could think more about the direct consequences of virus infection
as a major contributor toward immune deficiency.''
   Dr. William Haseltine of the Dana Farber Cancer Institute agreed
and said the research demonstrates the importance of virus-fighting
drugs.
   ``The most important implication is that antiviral drugs are in
fact the right approach,'' he said. ``There were people who
suspected that the primary disorder was caused by auto-immunity. It
very much looks now like it's a direct effect of the virus.''
   Ho's study calculated the number of infective doses in tainted
blood. One infective dose contains perhaps 1,000 or so individual
AIDS viruses and is enough to infect a tissue culture.
   His study found that one pint of blood from an AIDS patient
contains 1.8 million infective doses, while blood from someone who
carries the AIDS virus but is free of symptoms contains 15,000
infective doses.
   ``These values clearly show why the transfusion of contaminated
blood results in an extremely high rate of HIV-1 infection among
recipients,'' the report concluded.
   Blood banks routinely screen donations for signs of infection,
and transmission of AIDS through blood transfusions is rare.
However, the virus is still being spread by dirty syringes shared
among drug addicts. The researchers estimated that a contaminated
syringe could carry between one-half and 700 infective doses,
depending on the amount of tainted blood left behind and the stage
of the infection in the previous user.
   Health workers who accidentally prick themselves with needles
also risk infection. The researchers calculate that a needle
contaminated with the infected blood of someone who is free of AIDS
symptoms would carry six-hundredths of an infective dose, while a
needle from someone with AIDS symptoms could carry seven infective
doses.
   One infective dose can cause an AIDS infection in a test tube
under ideal laboratory conditions. While this also could be enough
to cause a human infection, Ho said that exposure to 10 or 15
infective doses may be necessary to reliably spread the virus.
</TEXT>
