<FIRST>u i BC-Lebanon     12-14 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lebanon,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians, Syrians Clash Near Sidon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas of PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's
Fatah faction mounted a pre-dawn raid against Syrian troops in
south Lebanon Thursday. Police said at least 10 combatants were
killed and 15 wounded.
   The raiders, estimated at 150, stormed and ransacked the
three-story headquarters of the Syrian garrison commander in the
two-hour foray that started from Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp
at 3 a.m., police said.
   The attackers used jeep-mounted recoilless guns, shoulder-fired
rocket-propelled grenades and AK-47 assault rifles in the attack,
according to police.
   ``It is the first assault they have ever staged against the
Syrian army across the Awali river,'' said a police spokesman, who
cannot be named under standing regulations.
   ``The Syrians are moving troops and armor to the area,
apparently to counter-attack. The situation is frightening,'' the
spokesman added.
   The river on the northern edge of Sidon, provincial capital of
south Lebanon, is 40 miles north of the Israeli border and nearly
25 miles south of Beirut.
   Israel, which invaded Lebanon in 1982 to drive out Arafat's
guerrillas from his main west Beirut redoubt, made it plain when it
withdrew from Sidon in 1983 that it would not tolerate any Syrian
military presence south of the Awali river.
   Arafat has been on loggerheads with Syrian President Hafez Assad
since his army backed Palestinian dissidents in 1983 who forced
Arafat to evacuate Lebanon's northern port of Tripoli, where he had
set up command after his expulsion from Beirut.
   Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization guerrillas filtered
back in the last three years and Western military sources estimate
their strength in the Sidon region at about 5,000 hardcore fighters.
   The police spokesman said Fatah raiders punched three miles
north from their base in Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp to
attack the Syrian commander's headquarters on south Lebanon's
coastal highway.
   The fate of the commander, Col. Ziad, could not be determined,
but his top assistant, Maj. Ali, was among those killed, the
spokesman said.
   Also killed were three militiamen of the leftist Nasserite
organization, the Sunni Moslem group that has ruled Sidon since the
1975 outbreak of Lebanon's civil war. The three were manning a
checkpoint on the Awali bridge.
</TEXT>
