<HEAD>Ethics Committee Urged to Be Skeptical of D'Amato</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man whose complaint last July sparked the
ethics probe of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., has asked that the
outside counsel's investigation be widened and warned the committee
to be ``very skeptical'' about what the senator says.
   Mark Green, a Democrat who lost to D'Amato in 1986, filed a new
brief Wednesday with the Senate Select Committee on Ethics. In an
effort to back up a charge that D'Amato makes false statements,
Green said D'Amato had denied asking the Department of Housing and
Urban Development to help certain projects, then backtracked after
the media obtained letters and memos to the contrary.
   D'Amato, at a New York news conference on another issue, said he
was unaware of Green's latest move, ``but it wouldn't surprise,
whatever it is, and I'm delighted that we'll have an opportunity to
have all of Mr. Green's charges reviewed by the ethics committee.''
   The senator said he was confident he would be exonerated.
   Green asked outside counsel Henry Schuelke III to expand his
probe to include phone calls D'Amato made allegedly on behalf of
mobsters and a HUD grant he helped procure for a group led by the
Rev. Al Sharpton.
