<HEAD>FDA: Consumers Shouldn't Use Acidophilus Capsules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers should not use an over-the-counter
food supplement distributed by a Pennsylvania company because some
bottles contain capsules with potentially fatal levels of stannous
fluoride, the Food and Drug Administration says.
   Vitamin Specialities Co. of Wyncote, Pa., has asked its 22
retail stores in New York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania to recall
acidophilus capsules with lot number 069296 and has notified 140
mail-order customers, the FDA said in a statement.
   The product, which the label says will help restore and maintain
the mucous membrane that lines the stomach and intestines, is
manufactured by Vita-Pure.
   An FDA analysis found that some capsules had a 784-milligram
dose of stannous fluoride, which is used in toothpaste and is safe
in small amounts. However, a 784-milligram dose could cause
convulsions in an adult and could be lethal for a small child, the
agency said. Five capsules could kill an adult.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Artists Receive Grants to Cope With Hugo, Earthquake Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artists and arts institutions victimized by
the San Francisco earthquake and Hurricane Hugo have been awarded
$947,000 from the National Endowment for the Arts to repair damage
caused by the disasters.
   The largest grant was an emergency matching grant of $555,000
that went to the San Francisco Foundation for the Bay Area Arts
Recovery Fund, to be matched by $3 in private money for every
federal dollar.
   The arts endowment, an independent federal agency, also gave
$200,000 to Charleston, S.C., to rebuild hurricane-damaged arts
offices, studios, performance halls and rehearsal spaces and to
replace materials and equipment.
   An additional $100,000 went to the South Carolina Arts
Commission, while smaller grants went to arts agencies in Puerto
Rico and the Virgin Islands. In addition, the National Trust for
Historic Preservation will receive a $25,000 grant to collect
information from damage reports and conduct on-site investigations
of historic structures and areas affected by Hurricane Hugo.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Americans Intently Followed Earthquake, Berlin Wall News Stories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans paid close attention to news stories
about the San Francisco earthquake and the crumbling of the Berlin
Wall, but showed little interest in state and local elections,
according to a poll.
   Nearly three-quarters of the people surveyed said they
``followed closely'' the stories about the San Francisco tremor,
according to the Times Mirror News interest Index.
   The tumult surrounding the opening up of East Germany was
watched intently by half of those interviewed, the survey found.
   On the other hand, only 13 percent said they followed stories
about the resumption of hostilities in Nicaragua and state and
local election coverage.
   The index was based on a telephone survey of 1,230 adults taken
between Nov. 9-12. The margin of error was plus or minus 3
percentage points.
</TEXT>
