<FIRST>r a PM-AtlantaSchools     12-14 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Schools,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta School Board Fires Associate Superintendent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board voted to fire the associate
superintendent of schools after learning he lacked an education
degree, and warned the superintendent he would lose his job unless
he is recertified.
   The board Wednesday reprimanded Superintendent J. Jerome Harris
for not disclosing information about Dr. Ronald Lewis, his top
aide, when Lewis was hired in 1987.
   The board voted to end Lewis' contract and said it would release
Harris as well unless he obtains the certificate he needs for his
job by the end of January.
   Harris, who allowed his temporary superintendent's certification
to lapse four months ago, said he needs one college course to earn
a new certificate, a course similar to one he taught for 14 years
at Brooklyn College.
   Lewis said he had been working to obtain an education
certificate since he arrived in Atlanta. He said he did not know
until Monday that he had been turned down.
   Lewis also has come under fire over allegations that he
plagiarized much of his doctoral dissertation in 1973.
   The allegations arose in 1982 when Lewis was nominated for a top
education job in New Jersey. He eventually withdrew his name from
consideration.
   Harris has said he knew of the plagiarism allegations when he
recommended Lewis but decided not to tell the board.
