<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Consumers-Labels     12-14 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumers-Labels,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA to Increase Staff Involved in Food Labeling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration plans to
increase the number of its food inspectors by 10 percent to ensure
that food manufacturers adhere to regulations aimed at reducing
confusion over product labels.
   FDA Commissioner Frank E. Young announced the move while several
dozen consumer groups expressed their concerns over current labels
during a hearing Wednesday, the fourth and final session held by
the FDA in a two-year effort to restructure the nation's food
labeling regulations.
   ``Food manufacturers are spending $3.6 billion advertising and
some of their claims are misleading,'' said Bonnie Guiton,
President Bush's adviser for consumer affairs.
   Officials have said labels containing words such as ``light''
mislead consumers because manufacturers use the word to describe
texture or color instead of calorie content.
   FDA spokesman James Carroll said the new regulations, expected
to take effect in mid-1991, call for manufacturers to use specific
definitions of such terms. He said the regulations are aimed at
ending ``chaos that exists in the market now.''
   Allen Goldberg, a spokesman for a group which represents 130
large food manufacturers, said most companies do not object to the
new labeling requirements, but do not want states to impose even
stricter regulations.
   The new labels would put less emphasis on vitamin and nutrient
content, and focus more on cholesterol, fat and sodium in the
product, officials said.
   The form of the new labeling remains undecided, but some
consumer groups suggested that officials aim for a simple, uniform
system of labeling.
   Charles Mitchell, an attorney for the Washington-based Center
for Science in the Public Interest, suggested a system of red,
green and yellow squares on packages be used to alert consumers to
the amount of cholesterol, fiber and salt in a product.
   ``Basically you're using traffic-light colors to signal
consumers,'' he said. ``Green for high fiber, red for high salt.''
</TEXT>
