<DOCNO> AP891214-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0603EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka-Rights     12-14 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-Rights,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rights Group Says Over 1,000 Killed Monthly in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Sri Lanka ^By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government-backed forces and rebels in Sri Lanka
have murdered more than 1,000 people each month since the
government reimposed a state of emergency in June, Amnesty
International said today.
   The human rights organization said security forces and
paramilitary groups trying to quell ethnic violence in southern
regions of the Indian Ocean island have killed hundreds of unarmed
rebel suspects at random.
   Minority Tamils seeking a separate homeland as well as the
ultra-nationalist Sinhalese People's Liberation Front group also
have slain hundreds of people, many of the governing United
National Party, the report said.
   Amnesty said the rebel groups' ``tactics of criminal violence''
were being adopted increasingly by the security forces and the
allied paramilitary groups. The government, dominated by the ethnic
majority Sinhalese, claims the paramilitary groups operate as
unauthorized vigilantes.
   Amnesty also blamed Indian peacekeeping forces for a ``rising
incidence'' of unlawful killings of unarmed rebel suspects in
northeast Sri Lanka.
   The report said pro-government forces and Tamil guerrillas have
mutilated, burned and dumped bodies of their victims in public
places ``to instill terror in others.''
   On the Indians, Amnesty cited witness reports that Indian troops
killed as many as 46 civilians in an Aug. 2 reprisal attack in
Valvettiturai hours after the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
ambushed and killed six Indian soldiers.
   The Indians arrived in 1987 to enforce a peace accord and,
failing to disarm the Liberation Tigers, began fighting them. India
has promised to withdraw its remaining 22,000 troops from Sri Lanka
by Dec. 31.
   Several lawyers pursuing the fate of people who have disappeared
after being detained in the south have been killed by unidentified
assailants, the report said. Three witnesses at an inquiry into a
young man's shooting by police also were reported killed in June.
   Amnesty said an emergency regulation allowing government troops
to dispose of bodies without having autopsies or inquiries
``encourages deliberate killings by the security forces.''
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa lifted a 5-year-old state of
emergency in January, but reimposed it June 20 amid widespread
killings and strikes.
   The government said there were 1,705 political-related killings
in the first six months of 1989, including 650 politicians and
political party supporters and 740 listed as ``civilians.''
   Amnesty said ``many more killings undoubtedly remain
unrecorded.''
   The number of killings rose markedly under renewed emergency
regulations, with ``well over 1,000 people being killed each
month'' through September, the group said.
   ``The right to life can never be suspended, even in times of
national emergency,'' Amnesty said. ``The violent activities of
armed opposition groups can never provide justification for grave
human rights violations such as extra judicial executions by
governments forces or their agents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
