<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CharterRevision     12-14 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Charter Revision,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Approves Revised Charter of New York City Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department approved of changes
in the city charter approved by voters last month that probably
will give minority voters more of a say in city government.
   Acting Assistant Attorney General James P. Turner of the
department's civil rights division said in a letter made public
Wednesday that the department ``interposes no objection'' to the
revised charter.
   Frederick A.O. Schwarz Jr., chairman of the Charter Revision
Commission that drew up the changes placed on the November ballot,
said one of the commission's major goals was ``increasing minority
representation in the city government.''
   ``The foundation has been laid for a more representative, fairer
and efficient city government,'' said Schwarz.
   The revised charter abolishes the city's Board of Estimate and
transfers its fiscal and planning powers to the mayor, the City
Council and other city officials. It also increases the size of the
council from 35 to 51 members.
   The charter revision is the most sweeping change in city
government since the consolidation of the five boroughs of New York
City in 1898.
   Most of the changes will be gradually introduced during the
first nine months of 1990.
</TEXT>
