<SECOND>PM-Underage Gambler, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underaged High-Roller Arrested for Gambling</HEAD>
<HEAD>eds: SUBS 3rd graf to delete extraneous word `with'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young woman who fooled casinos
about her age and was set up as a high-rolling gambler while in her
teens was arrested for underage gambling two months shy of turning
21, authorities said.
   Debra Kim Cohen, who lost thousands of dollars in casinos at age
17, was arrested Wednesday while trying to play at a $5 blackjack
table at Trump Plaza Hotel and Casino, said Steve Smoger, the
Atlantic City prosecutor.
   Smoger said Miss Cohen was ``the most infamous underage gambler
since casino gaming here'' and a ``master of disguise'' who could
fool people about her age.
   Five casinos were penalized in March for allowing her to play
while a minor. The state Casino Control Commission required the
casinos to pay $18,000 in fines and $162,000 in donations to
compulsive gambling programs.
   The commission said the casinos treated her as a high roller,
allowing her to lose thousands of dollars playing blackjack and
offering her free rooms, drinks, shows and meals.
   The underage gambling charge carries a maximum term of six
months in prison and a $1,000 fine, Smoger said.
   Miss Cohen's father, Atlantic City police detective Leonard
Cohen, had sent letters and photographs of his daughter to casinos
to get them to keep her from playing.
   ``Compulsive gamblers have compulsive problems,'' he said. ``The
industry has been denying that for four years.''
</TEXT>
