<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-14 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arctic Cold Settling Into Central U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sub-zero temperatures and snow lingered in the northern Plains
today as an arctic front barreled into the south-central states and
the middle and upper reaches of the Mississippi Valley were blasted
by bitterly cold air.
   Wind chill readings tumbled to as low as 40 degrees below zero
in Maine, while citrus growers worked to protect their trees from
an expected freeze in Florida.
   Squalls dumped snow on the Upper Great Lakes region today, with
up to 18 inches of snow forecast for the Door Peninsula in eastern
Wisconsin. A snow advisory was in effect for the Lake Superior
snowbelt and along the Wisconsin shore of Lake Michigan.
   Temperatures around Michigan at 4 a.m. EST today ranged from
minus 4 at Sault Ste. Marie to 20 above at Detroit. Snow was
falling over most of the state. Marquette, in Michigan's Upper
Peninsula, had about 14 inches of snow on the ground.
   Parts of Wyoming were under 14 inches of snow. An advisory for
snow and blowing snow was in effect this morning for northeastern
Wyoming and northern Colorado.
   Nebraska's winter wheat outlook worsened as the deep freeze
continued without a blanket of snow to insulate the crop from the
cold and wind erosion.
   Wind chills in Nebraska Wednesday ranged from 15 to 25 below
zero.
   Iowa's low temperatures today were expected to sink to 20 below.
   Most of northern Florida was placed under a freeze warning by
the National Weather Service. Lows from the mid to upper 20s were
expected in low-lying parts of Marion County.
   Citrus growers sprayed their trees with water Wednesday to
insulate them from freezing temperatures as cold weather pushed
southward.
   Wednesday's wind chills hit 35 degrees below zero in South
Dakota and Minnesota. Greenville, Maine, reported a wind chill of
40 degrees below zero.
   Arctic air slapped upstate New York and northern New England,
where temperatures were in the single digits or below zero today.
   Temperatures above 50 degrees were mostly confined to California
and the Southwestern deserts, the southern plains and lower
Mississippi Valley, Florida and Georgia.
   Wednesday's high temperature was 77 in Fort Lauderdale.
   Other reports as of 4 a.m. EST today:
   _EAST: Albany, N.Y. 1 fair; Atlanta 30 fair; Boston 11 windy;
Buffalo 2; Charleston, S.C. 33 fair; Chattanooga 32 fair;
Cincinnati 27 snow; Cleveland 19 snow; Detroit 20 snow; Hatteras 35
fair; Jacksonville 32 fair; Key West 58 fair; Knoxville 30 partly
cloudy; Macon 29 fair; Miami 48 fair; New York 19 fair;
Philadelphia 18 fair; Pittsburgh 17 snow; Portland, Maine 2 fair;
Richmond 26 foggy; Tampa 40 fair; Washington, D.C. 21 fair.
   _CENTRAL: Birmingham 27 fair; Bismarck 25 fair; Chicago 12
foggy; Denver 25 cloudy; Des Moines 4 partly cloudy; Fort Worth 34;
Indianapolis 14 snow; Kansas City 3 cldy; Little Rock 27 fair;
Louisville 26 fair; Memphis 28 fair; Nashville 28 fair; New Orleans
31 foggy; North Platte 10 snow; Oklahoma City 26 partly cloudy;
Omaha 03 partly cloudy; Rapid City 14 snow; St. Louis 10 fair;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 9 fair; San Antonio 28 fair.
   _WEST: Albuquerque 26 fair; Anchorage 35 cloudy; Boise 31
cloudy; Casper 25 cloudy; Fairbanks 18 snow; Great Falls 33
freezing rain; Honolulu 67 fair; Las Vegas 33 fair; Los Angeles 57
partly cloudy; Medford 27; Pendleton 26 fair; Phoenix 43 fair;
Portland, Ore. 32 fair; Reno 20 fair; Salt Lake City 33 cloudy; San
Diego 50 fair; San Francisco 48 hazy; Seattle 34 fair; Spokane 23
cloudy.
   _INTERNATIONAL: Calgary 37 cloudy; Montreal 8 fair; Ottawa 10
partly cloudy; Regina 17 fair; Toronto 1 partly cloudy; Winnipeg 30
fair.
