<FIRST>r a PM-AndersonCeremony     12-14 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anderson Ceremony,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Prayer Service for Hostage Terry Anderson</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emerson College journalism students and faculty
prayed for the release of hostage Terry Anderson and sent
videotaped holiday greetings to him with ``I'm Dreaming of a White
Christmas'' playing in the background.
   ``Merry Christmas, Terry, and come home soon,'' a chorus of
students sang at the end of the videotape, which is being sent to a
Lebanese television station in hopes it will get on the air and
Anderson will hear about it.
   One of the students, Sean Armstrong, wrote a special song,
``Come Home Terry,'' that was sung during the Wednesday night
ceremony. The words brought tears to the eyes of Fifi Reed, wife of
hostage Frank Reed, who was a special guest.
   ``We'd like to see you safe at home
   ``Beneath the Christmas tree
   ``Your daughter is crying
   ``Daddy I want you next to me.''
   Anderson, 42, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been held captive for nearly five years. During that
time his father and brother died of cancer, which he probably does
not know. He has not held his daughter, born three months after he
was seized on March 16, 1985.
   Anderson was kidnapped by Islamic Jihad, a group loyal to Iran
whose name means Islamic Holy War. His abductors demand the release
of 15 men imprisoned in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French
embassies in 1983.
   The Emerson College chapter of the Society of Professional
Journalists and the student newspaper, the Berkeley Beacon,
recently started a ``Free Terry Anderson Committee.'' Students are
wearing yellow ribbons until Anderson is released.
</TEXT>
