<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-DeathSquads     12-14 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Death Squads,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Policeman Confesses To Death Squad Killing of Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former policeman pleaded
guilty today to the murder of an anti-apartheid activist, saying he
was a member of a police assassination squad and had acted on
orders from superior officers.
   After years of suspicion among activists that police death
squads existed, this was the first time anyone confessed in court
to serving on such a unit.
   The black former policeman, Butana Nofomela, first made his
allegations in an affidavit Oct. 19, the night before he was to
hang for a separate murder with no political overtones.
   Armed with the affidavit, human rights lawyers obtained a stay
of execution for Nofomala so he could assist in investigations of
death squad activity.
   Subsequently, two other former policemen named by Nofomela as
death squad members confessed in newspaper interviews that they
were involved, and the issue has become a major national
controversy.
   Last week, President F.W. de Klerk rejected requests to appoint
a judicial inquiry commission, saying the allegations could be
handled through normal legal procedures. Justice Minister Kobie
Coetsee announced that Nofomela would be prosecuted for the 1981
stabbing of Griffiths Mxenge, a black lawyer and activist from
Durban.
   In a statement read in Magistrate's Court in Pietermaritzburg,
capital of Natal Province, Nofomela, 32, said he and three other
black policemen abducted Mxenge and took him to a stadium where
they kicked, punched and stabbed him until he died.
   ``At the time of the murder I was a member of the (police)
special branch assassination squad,'' Nofomela told the court. ``I
was instructed by Brig. (Willem) Schoon and Capt. (Dirk) Coetzee to
proceed to Durban and there to kill one Griffiths Mxenge.''
   Schoon, now retired from the police, has not issued any formal
statement on allegations he ordered Mxenge's assassination.
   Coetzee, who has fled South Africa, made detailed claims about
death squad activities, including Mxenge's murder, in a lengthy
interview last month with Vyre Weekblad (Free Weekly), an
anti-apartheid Afrikaans-language newspaper.
   Police have issued a warrant for Coetzee's arrest and have said
they will try to extradite him if necessary.
   After Nofomela read his statement in court, his case was
adjourned until Feb. 28.
   In addition to the alleged police death squads, police
investigators claim to have uncovered other assassination squads
run by far-right white extremists outside the ranks of the security
forces.
   Anti-apartheid activists and human rights lawyers have suggested
that disclosures about these extremist groups have been timed to
divert attention from the alleged police hit squads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
