<FIRST>u a PM-NursingHomeFire 1stLd-Writethru a0510 12-14 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0510,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire at Roanoke Nursing Home Kills Four, Injures Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>UPDATES throughout with 10 injured, details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out this morning on the third
floor of a five-story nursing home, killing four people and
injuring at least 10 others, officials said.
   The blaze started at 2:30 a.m. at the Shenandoah Homes
Retirement Community and smoke spread to the top floors before
firefighters arrived, County Fire Chief Tommy Fuqua said. It was
brought under control 2{ hours later.
   The fire's cause was being investigated.
   Officials said 124 residents of the home were evacuated to the
nearby Star City Skating Rink.
   William R. Reid, president of Community Hospital of Roanoke
Valley, said seven elderly residents were brought to the emergency
room about 4 a.m.
   ``One has a broken arm, two are suffering some cardiac problems
and the others have smoke inhalation,'' he said. ``We received two
bodies and we're expecting two more.''
   A firefighter and County Sheriff's deputy also were brought to
the hospital for observation, but appeared not to be seriously
injured, Reid said.
   Another patient injured in the fire was sent to Lewis-Gale
Hospital, Reid said, and others may have been sent to other
hospitals.
   Reid said an emergency room physician was dispatched to the
skating rink to check on the conditions of the evacuees, but all
reportedly were in good shape.
   ``We're in the process of getting breakfast to them right now,''
Reid said.
   Fuqua said there was no sprinkler system in the building, but
the home did have smoke deterctors and fire barriers.
</TEXT>
