<FIRST>u i PM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0452,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chileans Pick Leader For First Time in Nearly Two Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with polls open, heavy turnout,
Aylwin votes. Pickup 6th graf `His main...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A centrist opposition candidate was the
favorite today as Chileans turned out in droves to elect a
president for the first time in nearly two decades of iron-fisted
rule by Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
   Authorities reported calm throughout the country as polls opened
at 8 a.m. (6 a.m. EDT). Lines formed before dawn, and by 9 a.m.
they stretched for several blocks at many precincts.
   The nation's 20,023 polling stations were to remain open until 5
p.m.
   Voting was mandatory, and most of the 7.5 million registered
voters were expected to cast ballots in a resumption of a long
democratic tradition broken by 16 years of military rule.
   Voters were to pick a new president in a three-man race as well
as fill the 38 seats in the Senate and 120 in the House of
Deputies. The first official results were expected tonight, with
final results anticipated early Friday.
   Patricio Aylwin, 71, a leader of the centrist Christian
Democratic Party and the candidate for a 17-party opposition
coalition, voted at 8:30 a.m. in a crush of photographers and
television cameramen at a school near his Santiago home. He is
favored in most pre-election surveys to win the presidency.
   His main rival was Hernan Buchi, a 40-year-old independent
technocrat who served for nearly five years as finance minister
under Pinochet. Buchi, however, badly trails Aylwin in opinion
polls.
   The third candidate, millionaire, conservative businessman
Francisco Javier Errazuriz, was expected to finish last. Buchi's
advisers hoped to keep Aylwin's vote total below a majority and
force a runoff.
   Pinochet, who seized power in a bloody 1973 coup, was obliged to
call the elections after losing a referendum last year in which
voters rejected a military proposal that he remain in power until
1997.
   The opposition coalition Aylwin heads led the effort that ousted
Pinochet from the presidency. The general says, however, that he
will remain army commander for eight more years, sheltered by a
constitutional provision that prohibits the new president from
dismissing him.
   Pinochet led the armed forces in the coup that toppled the
3-year-old elected government of President Salvador Allende, a
leftist, at a time of social, political and economic turmoil.
Pinochet said at the time the armed forces would remain in power
``only as long as as circumstances demand.''
   Interior Minister Carlos Caceres, in a news conference with
foreign reporters on the eve of the vote, said the military
government had ``kept their word'' to restore democracy once it
restablished order, straightened out the economy and created a new
legal framework for the country.
   Buchi on Wednesday said that regardless of who wins the
election, ``we should all celebrate Thursday as the day of the
victory of democracy.''
   Also Wednesday, the opposition angrily denounced a new law
barring future congressional probes into the Pinochet regime and
its officials. The law was passed Tuesday by the four-man military
junta that now acts as legislature.
   Enrique Silva, Aylwin's campaign manager, said the new law ``is,
in our judgment, manifestly unconstitutional.''
   The law is one of several being pushed by the Pinochet
administration in its final months in power, and seen by the
opposition as aimed at limiting the powers of the future government.
   Aylwin and his top aides have repeatedly said they will seek to
repeal or change those laws in the future congress.
</TEXT>
