<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople-Europe     12-14 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People-Europe,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Parliament Urges UK To Halt Repatriation of Vietnamese</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Parliament today urged
Britain to stop repatriating Vietnamese refugees from Hong Kong and
blamed Britain for not generating international support to deal
with the influx of refugees.
   The Parliament also said the United States, which fought the
Vietnam War, has a ``special'' responsibility to help settle the
refugees.
   On Tuesday, the first 51 Vietnamese were flown to Hanoi. Britain
is determined to return 44,000 of the would-be immigrants from
Communist Vietnam, arguing they are economic migrants, not
political refugees.
   The European Parliament, comprising 518 members from all 12
European Community nations, said the distinction between
``political'' and ``economic'' refugees was ``arbitrary in the
context of Vietnam.''
   ``The collapse of the (Vietnamese) economy has resulted in large
measure from the imposition of a Stalinist economic model,'' it
said in a resolution that blamed the ``continuing refusal of both
the EC (European Community) and the United States to develop
economic relations with Vietnam.''
   There are 57,000 boat people in Hong Kong living in cramped
conditions.
   The Parliament said while it recognized the ``immense
difficulties'' faced by the government and people of Hong Kong in
coping with the influx of boat people, Britain must ``abandon the
policy of forcible repatriation.''
   It blamed London for failing ``to generate international support
to deal with this refugee problem in a humanitarian manner.''
   It asked the EC executive commission and the 12 EC states to
draw up an action program to resettle the boat people.
</TEXT>
