<FIRST>u i PM-BoatPeople 2ndLd-Writethru a0515 12-14 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0515,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Day of Anti-Repatriation Protests in Camps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Europarliament reaction. Pickup
3rd, `More than...'; Subs 9th, `The government...' with 3 grafs of details.
Pickup 10th graf `There have...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 Vietnamese today marched and
chanted slogans in a second day of peaceful protests against
involuntary repatriation.
   The European Parliament today condemned Tuesday's forced return
of 51 boat people from one of five detention centers in this
British colony.
   More than 2,000 Vietnamese men, women and children _ many
wearing white protest headbands _ marched through the Sham Shui Po
detention center in urban Kowloon today under banners that read
``Forced Repatriation is Homicide'' and ``Save our Souls.''
   They shouted slogans and thrust clenched fists defiantly in the
air as they snaked around the camp's playground. A few
plainclothesmen kept watch over the demonstration.
   At one point, protesters gathered in front of a makeshift altar
that had eggs piled on top and a sign that said: ``Requiem Ceremony
for 51 Souls.'' An official said the eggs were a religious offering
in remembrance of the repatriated Vietnamese.
   Nearly 4,000 Vietnamese protested at two separate centers on Hei
Ling Chau island, a former leper colony, and 2,000 more
demonstrated at Whitehead detention center in the New Territories
this morning, according to Francis Ma, spokesman for the
Correctional Services Department that runs the camps.
   Further demonstrations were staged in two of the camps in the
afternoon.
   ``They are peaceful and orderly demonstrations,'' Ma said.
   In Strasbourg, France, the European Parliament today urged
Britain to stop the forced repatriation, saying London had not done
enough to try to resettle the refugees. It also said the United
States should help solve the problem, given that fact that it
fought the Vietnam War.
   The Parliament, comprising 518 members from all 12 European
Community nations, said the distinction between ``political'' and
``economic'' refugees was ``arbitrary in the context of Vietnam.''
   The Hong Kong government issued a statement saying a Vietnamese
man who tried to commit suicide had been found hanging inside one
of the camps today. He was taken to a hospital where his condition
was listed as fair.
   There have been fears that forced repatriation could lead some
boat people to attempt suicide, but the statement said the incident
did not appear connected to the demonstrations.
   On Wednesday, about 6,000 Vietnamese protested at three centers,
with some shouting that they would rather die than return to
Vietnam.
   The protesters are among about 44,000 Vietnamese who have sailed
into Hong Kong since June 1988 and are considered illegal
``economic migrants'' unless they can prove they fled their
Communist homeland out of fear of persecution.
   Nearly 6,800 have been denied refugee status after being
screened by immigration officials, compared with slightly more than
700 who qualified.
   The first batch to be sent home against their will were whisked
screaming and crying from their detention center by riot police and
put on a plane to Hanoi.
   British and Hong Kong officials say more repatriations are
coming and argue that returning the Vietnamese home is more humane
than keeping them indefinitely in the camps, which are overcrowded
and rife with violence and malnutrition.
   But among the signs at Sham Shui Po was one that said ``Thatcher
No Heart,'' a reference to British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, who has strongly defended involuntary repatriation.
   Another sign read: ``Vietnamese Today! Hong Kong 1997?''
recalling concerns of some Hong Kong people who believe involuntary
repatriation will hurt the territory's chances of obtaining
international protection from Communist China, which takes control
of the colony in eight years.
   Hong Kong now houses about 56,000 Vietnamese. Those who arrived
before June 1988 automatically were granted refugee status and are
eligible for resettlement.
</TEXT>
