<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Environment 1stLd-Writethru a0518 12-14 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Environment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Everglades, Wetlands Bills</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts Bush's title in 2nd graf, The wetlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North American wetlands will grow by nearly 2
million acres and the Everglades National Park in Florida will
expand by 110,000 acres under a pair of new laws intended to
reverse dwindling wildlife habitats.
   The wetlands bill will provide ``a steady source of funds for
the purchase of critical wetlands in the United States, Canada and
Mexico,'' President Bush said at a signing ceremony Wednesday. The
measure authorizes spending $15 million annually over a four-year
period.
   An additional $10 million would be generated for purchases each
year by putting excess receipts from excise taxes on hunting
equipment into interest-bearing accounts. Fines and forfeitures
collected under a migratory bird act, amounting to about $850,000 a
year, also would be used to purchase wetlands.
   ``This bill is an excellent first step in reaching our national
goal of no net loss of wetlands,'' Bush told a White House audience
of environmentalists and lawmakers.
   He said the steady decline in the duck population is largely due
to the continuing loss of wetland areas. He does not favor a ban on
development projects that destroy wetlands, but wants any
development offset with an equal amount of acreage restored as
wetlands.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, who introduced
the bill last April, said it would allow the nation to begin
rebuilding waterfowl populations by conserving nearly 2 million
acres of U.S. wetlands under a 1986 agreement with Canada.
   ``There has been relatively little progress made ... during the
past three years,'' Mitchell said in a statement. ``It's important
that no more time be lost. Less than half the original 200 million
acres of wetlands in the 48 contiguous states remain, and the
destruction continues today at a rate of half a million acres per
year.''
   The expansion of the Everglades will be undertaken in
cooperation with the state of Florida, which will donate 35,000 new
acres to the federal park. The government estimates it will cost
$40 million to acquire the rest of the new acreage, with Florida
paying 20 percent of the costs.
   The Everglades, the second largest national park in the 48
contiguous states, is home to 13 endangered species, but problems
with the flow of waters have harmed the habitat for both birds and
alligators.
   ``The woodstork, heron, ibis, egret and roseate spoonbill have
all declined dramatically over the years,'' Bush said. ``The
Florida panther, the alligator and many species of fish are
declining.''
</TEXT>
