<DOCNO> AP891214-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0426 12-14 0898</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,0923</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Says It's Talking To Soviets About Troop Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with talks on Soviet troop cuts,
party denies final agreement reached on president. Pickup 6th, `The presidency...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new government said today it
has begun talks with Moscow on the pullout of 80,000 Soviet troops
from Czechoslovakia.
   Also today, the Communist Party denied it had reached a final
agreement with the opposition on choosing a president, saying a
final decision must be made at a party congress Dec. 20-21.
   But the party did not deny the substance of an agreement with
opposition leaders that will lead to the nation's first
non-Communist president in 41 years. The agreement was reported
Wednesday by opposition sources.
   In his first news conference since becoming foreign minister
Sunday, Jiri Dienstbier said he held ``preliminary talks'' with
Soviet representatives on the pullout of 80,000 Soviet troops.
   The discussions extended those begun by Dienstbier's
predecessor, Jaromir Johanes, in Moscow following the Malta summit
between Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Bush.
   ``I believe that we shall soon be able to arrive at some
concrete conclusions, some common understanding,'' Dienstbier said.
   The bilateral talks should run parallel with disarmament talks
in Vienna between NATO and the Warsaw Pact, which already have set
the goal of agreement on troop cuts in Europe by the end of next
year.
   He noted that the Moscow Protocol and the agreement allowing the
presence of Soviet troops in Czechoslovakia ``have been rendered
invalid unter international law because these agreement were made
under pressure.''
   Alexander Dubcek, who led the reforms of the ``Prague Spring''
crushed by the Soviet invasion in 1968, signed the agreements after
he was ousted and flown to Moscow.
   The government and the opposition agreed Wednesday that
Parliament will choose Czechoslovakia's next president by the end
of January, with the stipulation that he be a Czech not affiliated
with any political party.
   No agreement was reached on who would be president, but the
accord sets the stage for the election of Vaclav Havel. The
playwright and former political prisoner has been the key figure in
the peaceful revolt that ended the Communists' monopoly on power.
   It also seemed to rule out any chance at the presidency for
Dubcek, a Slovak. A Czech is stipulated for the presidency to
balance the ethnic background of the new Communist premier, Marian
Calfa, also a Slovak.
   The presidency is largely ceremonial, but it has great symbolic
importance because of the respect the first president, Tomas
Garrigue Masaryk, enjoyed in the independent Czechoslovakia he
founded in 1918.
   A statement issued at the conclusion of the talks Wednesday
night also called for the ouster from Parliament of lawmakers ``who
do not provide guarantees of political democracy ...''
   The statement did not specify how the deputies would be replaced.
   A strong Communist majority runs the 350-member Parliament
which, under the constitution, had 14 days from the resignation of
President Gustav Husak on Sunday to choose a new president.
   It was agreed at Wednesday's talks to extend that deadline to 45
days, participants said.
   The opposition coalition Civic Forum had hoped to see Havel
voted into office during a two-day parliamentary session this week.
Last week, the coalition said there was virtual agreement with the
Communists that the president should be a Czech with no political
affiliation.
   But Communist deputies abruptly swerved in another direction,
proposing instead that the matter be put to a public referendum in
the hopes of buying more time to regroup and slow the quicksilver
reform process.
   Civic Forum objected to the referendum on the grounds it could
delay the more important task of moving swiftly to free elections
for an entirely new Parliament, expected by July.
   Political observers in Prague speculated that Communist deputies
in Parliament rebelled against the party leaders who conducted the
negotiations with the opposition last week.
   Opposition negotiators at Wednesday's talks, Petr Pithart and
Michal Kocab, and the leader of the small People's Party, Josef
Bartoncik, said it was decided at Wednesday's meeting not to scrap
Czechoslovakia's 70-year tradition of Parliament electing the
president.
   Communist negotiators did not comment as they left the talks.
   While the presidential negotiations were being held, the
government said Wednesday it was drafting laws to ensure freedom of
religion, assembly and association and provide more protection to
people who are arrested.
   The proposed legal reforms were announced to Parliament by
Deputy Premier Jan Carnogursky, a dissident lawyer released from
jail two weeks ago who on Sunday was named to the first government
in 41 years led by non-Communists.
   Changes in the penal code would strengthen the independence of
the judiciary and reduce the time a person can be held before
charges are filed, Carnogursky said.
   Carnogursky also has joined a three-man government commission
overseeing Czechoslovakia's secret police.
   His elevation and that of nine other dissidents who became part
of the 21-member Cabinet on Sunday has been the greatest of the
historic gains made by the reform movement, which since Nov. 17 has
used mass demonstrations to force the Communists to open borders,
promise free elections and surrender their monopoly on power.
   Husak, 76, resigned Wednesday from his last position of power in
the Communist Party, his seat on the party Central Committee, the
state news agency CTK reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
