<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedSchoolKids     12-14 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned School Kids,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Bus Driver Suspended, Charged With Child Neglect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bobbette in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus driver who got lost on her route dropped
off seven children at a closed school and told them, ``You're
gifted, you figure out what to do,'' authorities say.
   A man living nearby invited the children into his home to call
their parents, and the driver, Bobbette Collier, 35, was charged
Wednesday with seven counts of contributing to the neglect of
children, an offense carrying up to a year in jail and a $1,000
fine, police said.
   ``She's fortunate that the kids weren't injured or hurt by
somebody else out there after she dropped them off,'' said police
Officer Albert Augustine.
   Ms. Collier became frustrated on Monday when she got lost while
driving her route and returned to Edison Comprehensive Gifted
School. Authorities say she then drove away, leaving behind seven
pupils from kindergarten through eighth grade.
   ``We said, `There's nobody at the school. What are we supposed
to do? There's no where to go,''' said eighth-grader Amanda
Oshinski. ``And she said: `You're smart. You're gifted. You figure
out what to do.'''
   Bill Hood, president of Willett Bus Co., which employs Ms.
Collier, said the three-year employee was suspended without pay for
one month.
   ``What she did was a major infraction of company policies,''
Hood said. ``It was a serious incident. We are happy that it was
not worse than it was.''
   Ms. Collier was a substitute driver but had driven the route
before, Hood said. She blamed her becoming disoriented on the
children's misbehavior.
   ``They were running up and down the aisle, and they wouldn't
stay in their seats,'' Hood said. ``She was trying to get them in
their seats with their seatbelts buckled.''
   Hood said Ms. Collier told him she dropped the students off at
the school to see if they could get in. But he said the driver
couldn't find the students after they went around to the side of
the school to try to find an open door.
   ``The kids were just floating around out there,'' said Edward
Fraczek, the neighbor who offered the use of his phone. ``We
couldn't just leave them alone out there like that.''
</TEXT>
