<FIRST>r w PM-Brown     12-14 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Chairman Raps Bush on China, Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Chairman Ron Brown today
criticized President Bush for his overtures to the Chinese
leadership that crushed student protests last spring, saying it is
part of a disgraceful U.S. policy.
   Brown, who recently returned from a visit to Berlin, also
attacked Bush for being timid and failing to make the United States
a force for democracy amid dramatic changes in Eastern Europe.
   Brown, addressing a breakfast meeting of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, called U.S. policy toward China disgraceful and said the
administration's high-level meeting last week in Beijing
``compounded that disgrace.''
   The meeting, he said, amounted to ``embracing that regime that
was crushing students with tanks just a few months ago.''
   ``I think that sends the wrong kind of signal ... around the
world,'' Brown said.
   Bush dispatched national security adviser Brent Scowcroft and
Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger to Beijing last
weekend for the first high-level meetings with China's leaders
since the crackdown in Tiananmen Square in June.
   Brown said that as communism recedes in Eastern Europe, the
United States should take a more active role in assisting those
countries in establishment of democratic institutions.
   ``We ought to be there to help,'' he said. ``We know more about
democracy than any country in the world.''
   Brown said Eastern Europe represents a large potential market
for U.S. business. A consequence of Bush's caution in Europe, he
said, may be that American businesses will get their too late,
after West German businesses win the new markets.
   ``They're reaching out to us,'' he said. ``I'm not sure we're
reaching out to them.''
</TEXT>
