<FIRST>u i PM-Comoros 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comoros, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0517,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mercenary Negotiating Handover of Power, Some Comrades To Leave Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with South African official saying several
mercenaries likely to leave today, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORONI, Comoros Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European mercenaries who seized
control of this Indian Ocean nation in a coup last month are
planning to leave but their commander is still negotiating terms
for his departure, a South African diplomat said today.
   Thirty French and Belgian mercenaries, led by Bob Denard, have
been under pressure to leave the former French colony since the
Nov. 26 assassination of President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane.
   Denard, a veteran soldier of fortune in Africa and Asia, said
today he wanted a formal transfer of power to the French army
before leaving, said the Star newspaper of Johannesburg, South
Africa.
   Comorans, who are mainly African, believe the mercenaries who
run the 600-man Presidential Guard are responsible for killing the
president. Denard has acknowledged he was in the room at the
presidential palace when Abdallah was shot, but says he is not to
blame. He said a guard shot Abdallah ``by mistake.''
   France and South Africa, the two leading donors to the Comoros,
have suspended aid and are pressuring Denard to leave. Denard has
been negotiating with the French about his departure.
   Marco Boni, the South African trade representative on the
islands, said he expected some of the mercenaries to leave on an
Air France flight tonight, but Denard would not be among them.
   Boni said the talks were at an impasse, but he believed there
could be breakthroughs within days.
   The Star reported today that Denard and the last of his men
could leave by the weekend if there was agreement on details of the
departure.
   The newspaper's correspondent in Moroni said Denard's conditions
for leaving included:
   _ Indemnity against prosecution for any of the guards'
activities in the Comoros.
   _ Six months' salary, plus an undisclosed additional payment,
for all the ``good work'' he and his men had performed.
   _ That the press attend the formal transfer of power.
   Denard said he was prepared to return to France, where he faces
arrest in a suit brought by relatives of mercenaries killed in the
unsuccessful coup attempt Denard led in Benin in 1977.
   Several of the mercenaries have married Comoran women. Denard
has a Comoran wife and two children.
   Four French warships left Mayotte Wednesday for an unknown
destination. Officially the ships are preparing for a possible
evacuation of the 1,600 French citizens on the Comoros. France has
denied any intention to intervene militarily.
</TEXT>
