<FIRST>u a PM-EarlyChristmas 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-14 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Early Christmas, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Brain Tumor Hot Line' Brings Christmas Early to Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT that release is expected this
afternoon, sted Friday. PICKS UP 3rd graf, `We got ...'; INSERTS hometown
in 8th graf, `Curbow was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who thought an inoperable brain tumor
would make this Christmas her last has been told she can leave her
hospital bed for home with a clean bill of health.
   Kym Curbow was scheduled for release this afternoon because the
holiday came ``a little early'' this year, as her mother put it on
Wednesday.
   ``We got ours on the afternoon of December Fourth,'' Linda
Curbow said.
   That was the day doctors determined that the mass next to her
20-year-old daughter's brain stem, where vital functions take
place, was a cyst _ not a tumor _ and removed it.
   ``When I walked in and said we have the final diagnosis,
everyone held their breath,'' said her neurosurgeon, Dr. George
Dohrmann. ``I said `Kym, Christmas has come early.'''
   A national ``brain tumor hot line'' made the difference for the
nursing student, who refused to settle for the bleak prognosis she
was given in August.
   ``A few months ago, I didn't think I'd have the rest of my
life,'' Curbow said as she prepared for her release from the
University of Chicago Medical Center. ``Now I know the whole thing
is over, that it's all gone.''
   Curbow, of Conyers, Ga., was referred to an Atlanta neurosurgeon
after complaining to her internist about severe headaches. The
neurosurgon performed a biopsy in August and ``just told her it was
inoperable,'' Mrs. Curbow said.
   The family was told Kym would likely lose her sight, her memory
would be affected, and that there was very little hope for a
positive outcome.
   ``Every report we got was worse than the one before,'' Mrs.
Curbow said. ``Kym was only 19 at the time and we weren't willing
to just sit and wait for this. It was a very stressful time.''
   Using her own medical skills, Kym tracked down the Brain Tumor
Information Service, a national hot line the University of Chicago
operates for people who need information on tumors.
   Doctors who volunteer for the service talk with those who call,
frequently send additional medical information to them, and often
ask to see medical records.
   After looking at Curbow's medical report and pathology slides
from her Atlanta neurosurgeon, ``we said two things,'' Dohrmann
recalled. ``We weren't convinced it was a tumor ... and second, we
thought there would be a way to remove it safely.''
   The cyst, which shouldn't return, likely began with irregular
cell development before Kym was born and may have been the cause of
the headaches, said Dohrmann.
   Dohrmann said Curbow's Atlanta doctor was not at fault, but that
``sometimes there are known treatments that can help people like
this and (doctors) just aren't aware of them.''
   The hot line's purpose, he added, is ``making national resources
available so that people don't have to depend just on what's
available locally.''
   And although not all calls have the happy ending Curbow's has,
Dohrmann said in nearly half the cases in which hot line doctors
ask to see medical records, ``something more .. can be done.''
   Kym Curbow said she is looking forward to returning to Georgia
Baptist Hospital School of Nursing and now has a new future in
mind: ``I want to be a neuro-nurse. I think I've had all the
experience necessary.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Brain Tumor Information Service can be
reached at 312-684-1400.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
