<FIRST>u a PM-TylerCase     12-14 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tyler Case,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pardon Board Recommends Reduced Prison Term in Racial Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Louisiana Pardon Board today
recommended early release for Gary Tyler, a black man who contends
an all-white jury wrongly convicted him of murdering a fellow
teen-ager during racial violence in 1974.
   Amnesty International and other organizations have urged freedom
for Tyler, 31, who has spent much of his life on the state prison
farm at Angola for a shooting that occurred when he was 16.
   Tyler's case has produced marches and rallies, and most recently
petitions to the Pardon Board with more than 12,000 signatures. The
British reggae band UB40 recorded a song about Tyler, and he was
described by the Soviet Communist Party newspaper Pravda in 1978 as
a political prisoner.
   The Pardon Board voted 3-2 to recommend Gov. Buddy Roemer cut
Tyler's life sentence to 60 years. That would make Tyler eligible
for release in five years, once he has served a third of his
sentence.
   Roemer's spokesman said the governor was not available for
comment this morning.
   Tyler's mother, Juanita Tyler, said she was happy with the
decision,but believes Pardon Board members would have voted for an
immediate release had they interviewed him. Board members routinely
do not interview inmates unless they are facing death and Tyler's
death sentence was commuted in the 1970s.
   ``If they would have talked to Gary, I think things might have
been different. They don't know Gary,'' said Mrs. Tyler.
   Joseph Weber, the father of the 13-year-old Tyler was convicted
of killing, said he would try to influence Roemer not to commute
the sentence.
   In October 1974, Tyler was an outspoken backer of school
integration in Destrehan, a small town on the Mississippi River 25
miles north of New Orleans.
   State Police in riot gear were patrolling the streets amid
racial fights sparked by the presence of Ku Klux Klansmen led by
David Duke, now a Republican state representative.
   As whites surrounded buses of black students at Destrehan High
School, shouting and hurling bottles, cans and rocks, a shot was
fired from one of the buses. Timothy Weber, standing with his
mother across the schoolyard, fell dead.
   Witnesses said the pistol was held by a gloved hand. Tyler was
the only one on the bus wearing gloves, said police.
   Those who believe Tyler was framed say a student who testified
against him was known as a liar and that police planted a pistol
found in the stuffing of the torn seat where Tyler had sat.
   Tyler's death sentence was commuted to life imprisonment when
the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the state's death penalty law.
But the conviction has withstood appeals.
</TEXT>
