<FIRST>u w PM-StealthBomber 1stLdWritethru a0488 12-14 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Bomber, 1st Ld Writethru, a0488,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cheney Favors Full B-2 Stealth Bomber Production in 1991</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout, no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney plans to move
ahead with building five B-2 stealth bombers next fiscal year but
has not decided on the fate of the full 132-plane, $70 billion
program in later years, Pentagon officials said today.
   Cheney's decision came as he was putting the final touches on
the defense budget for fiscal 1991, which is due to be submitted to
the White House in the coming days for final review before going to
Congress in January. The year begins Oct. 1, 1990.
   ``Five (planes) is right for '91, but there's been no decision
made on the out-years,'' said one source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Amid the reforms under way in the Soviet Union and the political
changes in Eastern Europe, congressional critics of the
radar-evading bomber have ridiculed the idea that the full number
of planes would ever be built.
   But Cheney has stressed throughout the budget process that he
prefers to cut entire weapons programs, rather than stretching them
out over longer production periods _ which makes each unit more
costly.
   The advanced technology bomber is designed to replace the Air
Force's aging B-52 strategic bomber fleet.
   The Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions that Cheney
had decided to build five bombers in 1991, 10 in 1992, 21 in 1993
and 24 in 1994. The rest would be completed by fiscal year 1996,
the newspaper said.
   Officials said later, however, that no such decision has been
made.
   ``Mr. Cheney has not reached any decision on his plans for any
programs in the out-years,'' said Defense Department spokesman Pete
Williams.
   Williams refused to discuss any of Cheney's plans for the 1991
budget, but he noted that the secretary has backed the long-range
bomber program as an essential part of the nation's strategic
defense.
   The Pentagon has invested about $23 billion in the program and
had expressed hopes of purchasing 132 bombers at a cost of about
$70 billion.
   But the price of the plane produced ``sticker shock'' in
Congress when lawmakers learned the price tag could be in the range
of $530 million for a single plane.
   Cheney's decision to move ahead with the program for a single
year comes as the Air Force recommended that the production be
stretched out over a longer period of time.
   Under the 1990 budget signed by Bush last month, the Congress
appropriated $4.5 billion for the program, and provided money to
build two in that fiscal year. Plans also called for funds for
components for five more of the radar-evading, bat-winged aircraft
in 1991.
   The Pentagon has proposed spending about $24 billion over a
three-year peak period for the bomber _ $7.8 billion in fiscal
1992, $8.4 billion in fiscal 1993 and $7.7 billion in fiscal 1994.
   Air Force Secretary Donald Rice told reporters last week that he
was looking at plans to extended purchases of the planes beyond
previous deadlines to meet budgetary constraints and prevent cuts
to other Air Force programs.
   Air Force officials have begun studying conventional-weapons
roles for the B-2 as its original mission _ delivering nuclear
weapons to Soviet targets _ comes under question with warming
superpower relations.
   Bombers equipped with long-range missiles with conventional
warheads could be used to strike terrorist targets or support
limited Navy operations, the officials say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
