<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugTax-Sentence     12-14 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Tax-Sentence,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Person Charged Under Drug Tax Law Gets Fine, Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEWISTON, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former leader of a Just Say No chapter
drew 60 days in jail and a $1,000 fine for possessing cocaine and
not paying tax on it, becoming the first person prosecuted under an
Idaho law levying a tax on drugs.
   Victor H. Smith, 23, also was placed on three years' probation
Wednesday. He entered a conditional guilty plea to the charges
under which he retains the right to appeal the case and challenge
the law, which took effect July 1.
   Police said they found almost an ounce of cocaine in a car he
was driving in July.
   The drug-tax law imposes both civil and criminal penalties for
not affixing tax stamps to illegal drugs. At least 18 other states
have taxes of some kind on illegal drugs, according to the Council
of State Governments in Lexington, Ky.
   The state Tax Commission is prohibited from trying to establish
the identity of anyone who buys tax stamps.
   However, supporters say the law raises the cost of dealing in
drugs and gives prosecutors another charge to throw at a suspect
arrested on a drug offense.
   Smith was vice president of the local Just Say No anti-drug
organization until he was removed from that position in April.
   ``No one's perfect,'' defense attorney Charles Stroschein said.
``Lots of people ... have responsible positions and fall off the
bandwagon.''
   Judge Ron Schilling delayed execution of the sentences pending
Smith's appeal.
   The tax stamps are about 2 inches square and are green for
marijuana, blue for controlled substances sold by quantity and red
for those sold by dosage. They cost $3.50 per gram for marijuana
and $200 per gram for cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
