<FIRST>r w PM-US-China 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 12-14 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0521,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Blast White House for Blocking Testimony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Fitzwater comment on VOA after 7th graf,
`We welcome'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats complain that the White House
is more prepared to dispatch high-level officials across the world
to reach out to the leaders of China than to send one official to
Capitol Hill to explain the action.
   Members of a House Foreign Affairs panel had sought the
testimony of Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger who,
over the weekend, accompanied national security adviser Brent
Scowcroft to China.
   When the White House blocked Eagleburger's appearance on
Wednesday, Democrats accused the administration of ``hiding out''
to avoid embarrassment.
   ``It seems the Bush administration is willing to send Mr.
Eagleburger 6,000 miles to apologize to the Chinese leaders but it
was not willing to send him two miles to Capitol Hill to explain
this action to Congress,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.
   The U.S. officials apologized, Gejdenson asserted, ``for being
offended by the savage squelching of those who courageously sought
basic freedoms in Tiananmen Square.''
   Meanwhile, the State Department announced Wednesday that China
has approved a new Voice of America correspondent to replace the
newsman expelled after the government crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators.
   ``We welcome'' the decision to approve Stephanie Mann Nealer's
accreditation, the State Department said in a statement.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today, ``It's
difficult to assign a specific motive to why they did it, but we
think it's a good sign.''
   Asked if the administration considered it an important step,
Fitzwater said: ``Well, this is a world where signs and signals are
important, which is a lot of what all this is about as we
reconsider our diplomatic relationship.''
   Nealer is head of the VOA's East Asia and Pacific News
department. VOA correspondent Al Pessin and Associated Press
newsman John Pomfret were expelled from China after being accused
of spreading rumors and lies about the military crackdown.
   Gejdenson and other Democrats vowed to press early next year for
the imposition of punitive sanctions against the Chinese government
in retaliation for the killings of demonstrators.
   The Democrats also stepped up their verbal attack.
   ``By bowing and scraping to the butchers of Beijing, the
administration has sent China and the world a message that is not
worthy of the world's greatest democracy and one which does not
represent the views of the American people,'' Gejdenson said.
   ``This mission will not be recalled with honor but with a deep
sense of shame,'' said Rep. Peter Kostmayer, D-Pa.
   But Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, defending Bush, said the Democratic
criticism has become so shrill and partisan that it may well
backfire.
   ``I don't know of a soul who believes that the Scowcroft mission
went to Beijing to apologize to the Chinese,'' Leach said.
   ``This Congress and this administration have no intention of
kowtowing to illegitimate Chinese actions,'' Leach said, but added
that he believes the United States has an obligation to take
whatever steps it can to persuade the Chinese to lift the ``yoke of
political oppression.''
   Leach said the Scowcroft-Eagleburger mission can be seen as a
test of the administration's ability to ``help extricate a proud
nation from an embarrassing corner.''
   ``President Bush is prudentially betting that an historically
xenophobic China is more likely to temper its stridency at home and
abroad if it isn't perceived to be capitulating to the pressure of
foreign powers,'' Leach said.
   Two witnesses, Professor Merle Goldman of Boston University and
Minxin Pei, a Chinese graduate student at Harvard University, said
they believed the president made a serious error in sending the two
officials to Beijing.
   ``This visit is being trumpeted by the conservative hardliners
in China as a triumph of their reactionary policies ... and as a
seal of approval on their repressive regime,'' Pei said.
   But Doak Barnett, a veteran China scholar and professor emeritus
at Johns Hopkins University, said Bush made the right move because
``it is imperative to have a dialogue with the Chinese leaders at
the highest levels, especially at this time.''
   ``I believe Congress should allow several months to permit
President Bush's initiative to be tested,'' Barnett said, adding
that he believes there is reason for hope that the reform movement
in China will eventually be revived.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
