<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Pope 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0550,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Group Threatens To Kill Pope, Tells Papal Nuncio To Leave
Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details, background on Lebanon, RAISE
the reference to the threat against the nuncio. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known Moslem group today
threatened to kill Pope John Paul II because it said he has
supported Lebanon's rebellious Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun.
   The communique from the group, the Organization for the Defense
of the Oppressed, also told the Roman Catholic envoy living in this
country, Papal Nuncio Pablo Puente, to ``leave Lebanon soonest.''
   The statement was delivered to a Western news agency as the pope
was criticized by Lebanese leftists for failing to receive Arab
mediators seeking to end the 14-year-old civil war between Moslems
and Christians.
   ``The Organization for the Defense of the Oppressed, after
consultations with its forces fighting international arrogance,
announces that it has issued the death sentence on the pope of
Rome,'' said the handwritten, Arabic message. The 92-word statement
said the killing will be carried out ``sooner or later.'' It
charged that the pontiff ``has become the spiritual guide of the
mutinous crusaders in east Beirut,'' a reference to Aoun and his
supporters in the Christian enclave north of the capital who have
rejected a new Christian-Moslem government. Aoun wants guarantees
that Syrian forces will pull out.
   Last month, the pope said the Vatican ``cannot remain neutral''
and that ``it is time ... for sacrifices for the sake of peace.''
In what at the time appeared to be an appeal to Aoun to back down,
the message added: ``One should sometimes choose the less painful
options.''
   There was nothing to authenticate the Moslem group's statement,
which used Shiite Moslem fundamentalist language similar to that of
pro-Iranian extremist factions holding most of the 18 Western
hostages in Lebanon, including nine Americans. Those groups usually
send a phototograph of a hostage with their statements as
authentication.
   The Organization for the Defense of the Oppressed issued one
previous unauthenticated statement Aug. 28, threatening to kill the
pope if he visited Lebanon. The group has not claimed
responsibility for any terrorist acts, and its leaders, size and
overall goals are unknown.
   Aoun has rejected an Arab peace plan _ under which a new
Christian president, Elias Hrawi, was elected Nov. 24 _ because the
accord did not specify when Syria's 40,000 peacekeeping troops
would leave Lebanon.
   Hrawi fired Aoun from all his posts, but Aoun and 20,000 loyal
troops are holding out at the presidential palace in the Christian
enclave.
   Newspapers and radio stations controlled by the leftist and
Moslems in Beirut said the Saudi Arabian, Moroccan and Algerian
foreign ministers were in Rome on Wednesday during a tour of Arab
and Western countries aimed at bringing pressure on Aoun to stop
defying the Hrawi government.
   The Beirut media quoted Vatican officials as saying the pope was
unable to meet the delegation because he was preoccupied with
religious preparations for Christmas. Newspapers said the ministers
turned down a papal suggestion they meet his foreign secretary,
Cardinal Augustino Casarolli.
   There was no immediate comment available from the Vatican or the
Algerian and Moroccan embassies in Rome. An unidentified official
at the Saudi Embassy said his country's foreign minister was not in
the city.
   Newspaper and radio reports said the pope's attitude would
hamper the peace process and help cement Lebanon's de facto
partition into sectarian states.
</TEXT>
