<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Statue     12-14 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Statue,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Communist Wants to Give Lenin Statue a `Worthy' Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian Communist has begun a
fund-raising drive to buy a statue of Vladimir I. Lenin that was
removed from a public square after violent anti-Soviet
demonstrations.
   Roberto Napoleon wants to transfer the monument to Italy so that
the statue of Lenin can reside in ``a place worthy of a great
revolutionary,'' the state news agency PAP reported Thursday.
   The 30-foot-tall monument was quietly removed ``for conservation
works'' Sunday night from a square in Nowa Huta, an industrial
suburb of the southern city of Krakow.
   Demonstrators shouting ``Soviets go home!'' had tried to destroy
the statue during protests in the past two weeks and then clashed
with police, who used water cannon and tear gas to disperse the
crowds and protect the monument.
   Poland's Solidarity-led government, made up of former opposition
activists now required to maintain relations with the Soviet Union,
had said it would not tolerate more violence. Mediators called on
Krakow authorities to move quickly to remove the monument so order
could be maintained.
   Protesting the decision to take down the monument, Napoleone
called on ``all Italian citizens and Communists who believe in the
ideas of Marxism-Leninism'' to contribute to the fund-raising
drive, PAP said.
   ``Lenin was not Stalin,'' Napoleone told The Associated Press in
Rome, adding that he would stage a contest to choose a city to
receive the statue if his offer to buy it is accepted by Polish
authorities.
   In letters to the Nowa Huta muncipal council and Poland's
Communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski, Napoleone said the money
paid for the Lenin statue could be used by Poland ``to make another
monument of bronze to the glory of the Polish pope ... or another
benefactor of yours,'' PAP said.
   Napoleone, a member of the Italian Communist Party who runs his
own publishing house, said he also gave a copy of the letter to
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, the first secretary of the Polish Communist
Party, who is visiting Italy.
</TEXT>
