<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Film     12-14 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Film,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Censored Film Removed From Shelves For Showing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1982 film about Stalin-era
interrogations has been shown in Poland, clearing the censor's
shelves of all those movies that were banned for their
anti-Communist messages, a noted director said.
   Ryszard Bugajski's film ``The Interrogation,'' completed in the
spring following the imposition of martial law on Dec. 13, 1981,
was previously distributed only illegally on videocassette tapes.
   But it was shown in a Warsaw cinema on Wednesday, the eighth
anniversary of the military crackdown to crush the independent
Solidarity movement.
   The lifting of artistic censorship has been a priority of the
new Solidarity-led government of Taduesz Mazowiecki, who became the
first non-communist prime minister in the East bloc in August.
   ``I hope that never again there will be such a power in Poland
which will decide for viewers what can and what must not be
watched,'' director Andrzej Wajda told the audience at the
screening Wednesday.
   ``Therefore, I can announce tomorrow as the beginning of the
`Cinema in Free Poland,''' said Wajda, whose works also were
censored. His remarks were carried by the PAP news agency.
   Bugajski's film concerns the 1950s arrest and torture of a young
singer who refuses to give the secret police testimony against her
friends.
   Bugajski emigrated to Canada in 1983 but was in Warsaw this week
for the Polish premiere of his film.
</TEXT>
