<FIRST>r i AM-China-Computer     12-14 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Computer,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Running Smoothly Despite Pro-Democracy Involvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's largest computer company has survived
despite the involvement of its former head in the pro-democracy
movement, but it has seen a decline in business because of the
government's current economic policies, its new president said
Thursday.
   Shen Guojun, president and chairman of the board of Stone Co.,
also said his ousted predecessor and former partner, Wan Runnan,
has no legal right to any assets in the company.
   Wan and two other senior officials of Stone fled China following
the military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement, in which they
had been deeply involved.
   The government alleged the 43-year-old entrepreneur had donated
$54,000 to the student movement, although for some of that amount
Wan is believed to have acted only as a go-between for other
contributors to the students.
   Police are believed to have issued a warrant for his arrest as
an instigator of what is officially called a ``counterrevolutionary
rebellion.''
   Shen said at a news conference that Wan ``decided by himself to
take part in the turmoil against the will of the company'' and that
as a result he was fired from his posts.
   Shen insisted no employees had been punished for assisting Wan
in supporting the students. Wan's brother and father still work in
the financial section of the company, he said.
   He said the government froze company bank accounts until
September, ``for political reasons,'' apparently to keep Wan from
withdrawing money, but has not interfered with Stone's management
or independence.
   ``Stone is still getting a lot of favorable treatment from the
government,'' he said.
   But he said turnover and profits are down 20 percent this year
due to a government austerity program, which has left customers
short of funds, and the political turmoil of May and June.
   Stone, which commands 80 percent of China's word processor
market, had a turnover of $203 million in 1988, double the 1987
figure, and profits of $13.5 million.
   Shen said Stone also has had to adjust its product line as the
government, now moving to strengthen its socialist central planning
system, emphasizes heavy industry and other basic industries.
   Another company official said the company previously put too
much emphasis on electronics and office automation, and now has
shifted to marketing industrial control devices.
   Stone also has abandoned the idea of selling shares to the
public.
   ``We don't think it's a proper time right now to put Stone
shares on the market,'' said Hu Zhaoguang, president of the Beijing
Special Zone for high technology in the Haidian university area of
northwest Beijing.
   Stone was founded in 1984 by Wan, Shen and two other former
computer experts at the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
   It quickly became China's foremost computer company and a symbol
of the entrepreneurial spirit encouraged by senior leader Deng
Xiaoping's market-oriented reforms.
   The independently run collective employs nearly 700 people and
accounts for 50 percent of the business in the Haidian district,
known as Beijing's ``Silicon Valley.''
   But in May, Wan is said to have joined student leaders in
calling for Deng and Premier Li Peng to step down. Members of a
Stone research institute collected signatures for a petition
calling for a meeting of China's legislature to discuss ending
martial law imposed by Li on May 20.
   Wan fled China soon after the June 3-4 military crackdown and is
based in Paris, where he is an active participant in the overseas
Chinese pro-democracy movement.
   Shen acknowledged Wan's role in the success of Stone: ``He did
his part and contributed to the development of this company.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
