<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 12-14 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Guerrillas Attack Syrian Garrison, At Least 10 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with PLO headquarters denouncing
attack, death threat against pope. Pickup 3rd, `The attackers...' TRIMS
thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian guerrillas armed with guns and
grenades attacked a Syrian garrison in southern Lebanon before dawn
today. Police said at least 10 combatants were killed and 40
wounded.
   About 150 raiders ransacked the three-story headquarters in a
two-hour foray that started from Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee
camp, police said.
   Police and other sources said the attackers belonged to PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction, police and other
sources said.
   But the Palestine Liberation Organization, without explicitly
denying launching the attack, issued a statement at its Tunisia
headquarters condemning the raid by ``unidentified armed men,'' the
Kuwaiti News Agency said.
   Also today, a Moslem group threatened to kill Pope John Paul II,
claiming he supports the Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun. The
general has refused to surrender to a new Christian-Moslem
government trying to end the country's 14-year-old sectarian war
and has demanded that Syrian troops leave Lebanon.
   The Organization for the Defense of the Oppressed also said in a
communique that the Roman Catholic envoy in Lebanon, Papal Nuncio
Pablo Puente, must ``leave Lebanon soonest.'' There was no way of
authenticating the message.
   The little-known group, which has never claimed responsibility
for a terrorist attack, in August threatened to kill the pope if he
visited Lebanon.
   The attackers in Sidon used jeep-mounted 107mm recoilless guns,
shoulder-fired rocket-propelled grenades and AK-47 assault rifles,
police said.
   ``Some of the dozen or so Syrian guards who were caught by
surprise fought hand-to-hand to stop the attack, but they were
hopelessly outnumbered and outgunned,'' a police spokesman said.
   He said it was the first attack the Palestinians had ever staged
against the Syrian army, whose southernmost garrisons in Lebanon
are across the Awali river, which is on the northern edge of Sidon
40 miles north of the Israeli border and nearly 25 miles south of
Beirut.
   ``The Syrians are moving troops and armor to the area,
apparently to counterattack. The situation is frightening,'' said
the police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   He was evidently alluding to fears the Syrians might cross the
river to take revenge on Fatah, even at the risk of sparking a
confrontation with Israel.
   Police could not give a complete breakdown of the 10 killed.
They said they included at least two attackers. Also killed were
three militiamen of the leftist Nasserite Organization, the Sunni
Moslem group that has ruled Sidon since the 1975 outbreak of
Lebanon's civil war, who were manning a checkpoint on a nearby
bridge.
   Sidon, Lebanon's third largest city with a population of
350,000, closed down in daylong general strike called by the
Nasserites to protest the attack, which they blamed ``exclusively
on Fatah.''
   Arafat has been at loggerheads with President Hafez Assad of
Syria since Assad's army backed Palestinian dissidents in 1983 who
forced Arafat to evacuate Lebanon's northern port of Tripoli.
Arafat had set up command there after his expulsion from Beirut.
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982 to drive out Arafat's guerrillas
from his main west Beirut redoubt and made it plain when it
withdrew in 1983 that it would not tolerate any Syrian military
presence south of the Awali.
   The Syrians had withdrawn most of their 100-man garrison from
the two-mile coastal strip just across the Awali three weeks ago
when they massed on mountaintops in central Lebanon to put pressure
on Aoun.
   Fatah guerrillas filtered back into Lebanon the last three years
and Western military sources estimate their strength in the Sidon
region at about 5,000 hard-core fighters.
   The Syrians maintain 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League mandate to smother Lebanon's Moslem-Christian civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
