<DOCNO> AP891214-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-CzechFuture 1stLd-Writethru a0421 12-14 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech Future, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Over President Shows Communists Still Have Some Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `Yet the...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with party
denial. Pickup 4th pvs, `Tens of...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the big weekend party
celebrating a heady revolution, the opposition woke up to a new
battle with the Communists over whether playwright Vaclav Havel
could be president of Czechoslovakia.
   The opposition appeared to have prevailed on Wednesday, when the
Communists agreed that Parliament would choose a president not
affiliated with any party. That apparently paved the way for Havel.
   But Communist Party spokesman Josef Hora today denied an
agreement had been reached. He said the party's negotiators were
not authorized to offer a binding commitment and that only the full
party congress on Dec. 20-21 can do that.
   The battle was a reminder that the Communist Party, which in
three weeks surrendered its 41-year monopoly on power, still wields
some clout.
   Tens of thousands of Communists are rumored to have handed in
their party cards since a Nov. 17 police crackdown on peaceful
student demonstrators drove a disgusted nation into revolt.
   But those left in the party, like everybody else in
Czechoslovakia, have already started campaigning for the free
parliamentary elections next year and are using what remains of
their power as skillfully as they can against the opposition.
   Picking right up on the newest trend in East European politics,
where the largest opposition groups in Hungary, East Germany and
Czechoslovakia, all are called ``forums,'' Communist reformers
founded a ``Democratic Forum'' to give the party a new, liberal
face.
   The image makeover is expected to go further with another
leadership overhaul at the party's extraordinary congress next
week, just a month after thediscredited hard-liners who had ruled
for 21 years were ousted.
   Meanwhile, thousands of orthodox Communists remain in powerful
positions in factories, offices, villages and towns across the
country, many of them hand-picked to run Czechoslovakia after the
1968 Warsaw Pact invasion.
   ``The factual power of the party is not broken yet,'' noted
Marek Benda, son of a well-known dissident and a student leader.
   The students, lauded as national heroes for their role in
starting the revolt, were the only ones who did not join in the
general celebrations of the end of one-party Communist rule.
   Instead, displaying the same political determination that
powered the revolt, they decided to continue their strike. Two of
their reasons were that local Communists were still obstructing
opposition activists in remote regions such as east Slovakia, and
that Havel was not yet president.
   ``We knew from the beginning that the Communists would try to
make things dark, and to cheat,'' said Benda.
   The tussle over the presidency proved the students' suspicions
right.
   Civic Forum spokesman Lubos Dobrovsky says it was implicitly
agreed last week at talks between all parties and the opposition
that a non-party Czech would become president.
   The description clearly fit Havel, a former political prisoner
who symbolizes Czechoslovakia's peaceful fight for freedom.
   The Communists won't say what happened to that agreement.
   Either there was a revolt by the Communist deputies in
Parliament, a conservative group picked in the last ``elections''
in 1986, or the Communist leaders decided to play for time.
   They demanded a referendum instead of a straight parliamentary
election on the presidency. Finally, they agreed on Wednesday that
the president should be elected by Parliament before the end of
January.
   In the eyes of the opposition, Havel is the only person who can
be president because, as Cerny put it, ``his slate is clean.''
   After four years in jail and 13 years standing up to police
harassment, Havel is viewed as a guarantor of the new freedoms just
won in Czechoslovakia, someone who will make sure there is no
backsliding.
   Thus Civic Forum has mounted an enthusiastic campaign for Havel,
handing out thousands of posters at its Prague headquarters for
visitors to take back to the country, and plastering thousands more
all around the city center.
   Many opposition activists are determined to go all out to make
Havel president.
   ``Any other president would delay the cause,'' said composer
Michael Kocab, a key negotiator with the Communists.
   He believes Havel will best calm the situation in
Czechoslovakia, encouraging reform and Western investment.
   Others, who did not want to be named, want Havel as president,
but say this is less important than the victory already won over
the Communists.
   A great debating point this week has been: which posters of
Havel give the would-be president the best image?
   ``This is not America. We are not running an American
campaign,'' Cerny told a Czech visiting Civic Forum headquarters
who complained about Havel's image. ``Either he wins as he is, or
he loses. We are not afraid of that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Alison Smale, chief of the Vienna bureau of The
Associated Press, has covered East bloc affairs out of Austria,
Moscow and West Germany since 1980.
</TEXT>
