<FIRST>r i AM-Liechtenstein     12-14 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liechtenstein,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liechtenstein's Bid for U.N. Membership Approved by Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliament of the principality
of Liechtenstein voted unanimously Thursday to have their wealthy
but tiny nation bid for membership in the United Nations.
   All 25 legislators backed a government proposal to send a formal
application to U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar in
the spring.
   Hans Brunhart, the chief of government, said the vote was a
``historic step'' in Liechtenstein's foreign policy. If the U.N.
General Assembly approves the bid in its session next fall,
Liechtenstein would be the smallest member state.
   Chief advocate of a U.N. role has been Prince Hans Adam II, who
became head of state last month following the death of his father,
Franz Josef II.
   Hans Adam has said that only by joining the world body could
Liechtenstein obtain worldwide recognition as a sovereign state. He
said the principality might one day face ``locked doors'' if it
stayed outside.
   The road toward U.N. membership was cleared in March when
Liechtenstein voters narrowly rejected a proposed constitutional
amendment that would have made accession to any international body
subject to popular approval.
   In a 1986 referendum in neighboring Switzerland, a government
proposal to seek U.N. membership was defeated by a large majority.
   The export-oriented nation of 26,000 people is linked to
Switzerland in a customs and currency union, and has one of the
highest per-capita incomes in the world. After World War I, members
of the League of Nations, the forerunner of the U.N., had
successfully opposed admitting Liechtenstein, officially on the
grounds that it has no army, then a characteristic of as sovereign
nation.
   Since 1978, Liechtenstein is already a member of the Council of
Europe. In the past few decades, it also has joined several other
international organizations and is a signatory of the Helsinki Act
of the Conference for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</TEXT>
