<FIRST>r w AM-Gingrich-Ethics     12-14 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich-Ethics,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Asking Supporters To Help Pay $125,000 In Legal Fees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Durenberger-Ethics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich has run up
more than $125,000 in legal fees in preparing his defense against
ethics charges and is appealing to past campaign contributors to
help pay the bills, an aide said Thursday.
   Spokesman Rich Galen said Gingrich has had two lawyers working
to prepare a defense so he would be ready should the House ethics
committee decide to launch a formal investigation of two compliants
that have been filed against him by Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark.
   ``It's like buying insurance,'' Galen said. ``You hope you don't
have to use it.''
   Both complaints are pending before the ethics committee. The
first alleges that Gingrich violated House rules and federal
campaign finance laws by getting 21 investors to put up $5,000 each
to promote his 1984 book, ``Window of Opportunity.''
   An outside counsel hired to evaluate that complaint concluded in
October that there was no reason for the panel to investigate
Gingrich, who rose to prominence in the House after filing the
ethics complaint that led to the resignation last June of former
House Speaker Jim Wright.
   A week after the outside counsel made its recommendation,
Alexander filed another complaint, along with 670 pages of
supporting documents, accusing the Georgia congressman of ethics
and campaign finance violations in seven new areas.
   Galen said the legal work on Gingrich's defense has been done
primarily by two Washington attorneys, former Arkansas Rep. Ed
Bethune and Dan Swillinger. He said other lawyers also may have
been consulted during work on the defense.
   Because Gingrich does not have enough money in his campaign
account to pay the attorneys' bills, Galen said a fund-raising
appeal to about 12,000 past contributors was mailed out last week.
   In his most recent filing with the Federal Election Commission,
Gingrich reported that as of June 30, he had $35,847 in leftover
debts from his 1988 re-election campaign and had a cash balance in
his 1990 campaign account of $50,297.
   In the fund-raising letter, Gingrich described the ethics
complaints as a ``political witch hunt the liberals launched
against me earlier this year in the form of hundreds of baseless
charges.''
   ``This fight has severely weakened the financial condition of my
campaign committee,'' the letter continued. ``And this is precisely
the result these liberals wanted to achieve ... My campaign is very
financially vulnerable going into an election year.''
   Urging his contributors to ``show them they will have to fight
it out at the ballot box rather than through smears at the ethics
committee,'' Gingrich asked for ``a very special contribution of
$100, $75, $50 or even $25.''
   During the Wright investigation, Gingrich repeatedly used his
ethics campaign against the former speaker as a fund-raising tool
for a political action committee created to help elect Republicans
to state and local offices.
</TEXT>
