<FIRST>u a PM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0502 12-14 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truck Driver's Relatives Make a Show of Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with relatives attending court,
waiting for testimony. PICKS UP `Meredith on ...'; Lead prospects undcertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About a dozen of Larry Mahoney's
relatives went to court today in a show of support and to hear him
tell his story about the night his pickup collided head-on with a
church bus and killed 27 people.
   The 36-year-old factory worker from rural Owen County was
expected to take the stand after cross-examination today of an
accident-reconstruction expert.
   Mahoney's parents, son, brother and sisters, were among those in
the courtroom at his murder trial.
   ``I would have crawled to get here,'' said Judy O'Donovan, his
sister.
   Mahoney has been ``very emphatic'' about taking the witness
stand and giving his version of events leading up to what
authorities say is the nation's worst drunken-driving accident,
said defense attorney William Summers.
   ``He wants to tell his story. He will tell his story,'' Summers
said Wednesday. ``He obviously feels bad for all the people
involved in this tragedy.''
   On Wednesday, a defense witness disputed official
reconstructions of the accident, saying Mahoney tried to avoid a
head-on collision with the bus. Wilbur R. Meredith III also
testified that the bus had several serious design flaws and was not
being used for its intended purpose.
   Twenty-four youngsters and three adults died and a dozen
children were seriously burned in the May 14, 1988, bus crash on
Interstate 71 south of Carrollton. The prosecution contends the
tragedy was caused after an intoxicated Mahoney, driving the wrong
way, crashed into the bus.
   Mahoney faces multiple life sentences if convicted of the
charges: 27 counts of murder, 42 of wanton endangerment, 12 of
assault and one of drunken driving.
   Meredith on Wednesday confirmed the prosecution's basic finding:
Mahoney's pickup truck hit the loaded church bus.
   But Meredith's account differed from those of the National
Transportation Safety Board and the State Police.
   The prosecution had said Mahoney took no evasive action before
colliding into the right front section of the bus.
   Meredith said Mahoney may have believed he was on a two-lane
highway when he came upon the bus and a blue Cadillac.
   The sedan was passing the bus on the right side and swerved to
avoid Mahoney's truck, he said. The pickup also swerved and
sideswiped the car. The truck then struck the front-right part of
the bus and spun away, he said.
   In the prosecution version, the truck struck the bus first,
rotated and hit the rear driver's side portion of the Cadillac.
   Meredith based his version on at least 400 computer simulations
of the crash, in part by using NTSB computer programs. The jury
viewed a videotape showing a computerized diagram of the crash,
with rectangular boxes representing the three vehicles.
</TEXT>
