<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     12-14 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Flashing Warning Signs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories climbed to their highest
level in two months in October, the government said Thursday, and
some analysts said that while the backlog had not reached dangerous
heights yet, it was flashing warning signs.
   ``We have not reached the point where we need to call out the
Marines, but there are some warning signals,'' said Robert G.
Dederick, chief economist for The Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   On the other hand, economist Michael P. Niemira of Mitsubishi
Bank in New York said that while businesses need be cautious, they
have better inventory control now and should be able to correct
problems before they become too serious.
   The Commerce Department said inventories climbed 0.4 percent to
a seasonally adjusted $793.9 billion in October after remaining
flat in September. The September report was revised from a 0.2
percent increase reported earlier and followed a 0.4 percent
advance in August.
   Business sales, meanwhile, dropped 0.7 percent to a seasonally
adjusted $519.2 billion in October after falling a revised 0.7
percent in September. September sales originally were reported to
have fallen 0.3 percent after rising 3 percent in August.
   The October business activity produced a slight increase, to
1.53, in the ratio of sales, meaning it would take 1.53 months to
exhaust inventories at the October pace. The ratio was 1.51 in
September and 1.50 in August.
   If inventories were to pile up excessively, it could mean
cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs, perhaps leading to a
recession. However, neither Dederick nor Niemira found the ratio at
a dangerous level yet.
   Niemira suggested it reflected the end of the slow-growth cycle
and predicted that ``things will begin to look better in 1990.''
   In fact, things began to look better on Wednesday when the
Commerce Department reported an 0.8 percent improvement in retail
sales in November, the biggest in four months, as shoppers began
the Christmas gift-buying season.
   That and other recent economic indicators reflect the easing in
Federal Reserve interest-rate policies, analysts say. The Fed had
kept a tight rein on credit for more than a year to slow inflation,
but began loosening its grip last June, permitting short-term rates
to fall gradually.
   The October report showed retail sales slumped 1.3 percent,
while retail inventories edged down 0.3 percent. Excluding the
automobile category, inventories rose 1 percent.
   The Commerce Department reported that retail automobile
inventories fell 3.7 percent in October, but Niemira said that
represented some problems with the government's seasonal adjustment
factor since car sales have plummeted since the end of September.
   Inventories at the manufacturing level, which represent about 45
percent of the total, rose 0.3 percent. Manufacturing sales, on the
other hand, dropped 0.6 percent.
   Wholesalers' inventories jumped 1.7 percent, while their sales
were off 0.1 percent.
   Overall, inventories were 4.1 percent above those of a year ago,
while sales increased 6.9 percent over October 1988.
</TEXT>
