<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Pisa     12-14 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pisa,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Agrees to Close Leaning Tower for Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Pisa agreed Thursday to sign an order
to close the famed Leaning Tower to the public at an as yet
undisclosed date, the ANSA news agency said.
   Pisa Mayor Giacomo Granchi, who met with Minister for Public
Works Giovanni Prandini in Rome, agreed to sign the closure order
on Friday.
   Granchi agreed to sign the order after he was assured the
restoration work would begin as soon as possible, perhaps in the
next three months, ANSA said.
   Granchi, who had opposed closing the tower, said Monday he now
agrees it is necessary. However, he said the shutdown would not
begin until after the Christmas holidays.
   Prandini said the government would not reimburse Pisa for any
financial losses suffered by its tourist industry. An average 1,500
to 3,000 tourists climb the tower daily, paying a fee of $2.80 each.
   The 180-foot tower tilted almost from the time Bonnano Pisano
started building it in 1173 because the ground shifted underneath.
Experts in Pisa said it would not topple for another century if its
tilt pursued at the same rate.
</TEXT>
