<FIRST>u a PM-NurseSlayings     12-14 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nurse Slayings,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse Convicted of 2 Murders, Manslaughter, Negligent Homicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse was convicted today of killing
four patients by injecting them with a powerful drug in a scheme to
revive them and look like a hero.
   A jury deliberated eight days before finding 27-year-old Richard
Angelo guilty of murder in two deaths, manslaughter in one and
criminally negligent homicide in the fourth. All four deaths
occurred in 1987 at a Long Island hospital.
   The Lindenhurst man was also convicted of assault in connection
with the deaths and on three counts of assault for giving
injections to a patient who survived. He was acquitted of assault
in connection with two other patients whose deaths could not
conclusively be linked to injections.
   The injections of a muscle relaxant occurred at Good Samaritan
Hospital in West Islip in the fall of 1987. Angelo said he had
planned to inject the patients, then be first on the scene to
revive them and be seen as a hero.
   Angelo could receive 50 years to life in prison at sentencing
Jan. 17 on the murder charges. He was ordered held without bail at
the Suffolk County jail, where he had been since his 1987 arrest.
   Defense attorney Eric Naiburg had conceded that Angelo injected
the patients and may have caused some of their deaths. But Naiburg
argued that Angelo was not aware the injections presented a grave
risk to the patients, a condition necessary for a murder conviction.
   Prosecutor John Collins, calling Angelo ``a monster in nurse's
whites,'' contended that Angelo had to know the risks, especially
after the first victim died.
   ``I'm not saying he intentionally killed anyone,'' Collins said
in closing arguments. ``I'm saying he just didn't give a damn.''
   Angelo, who was a nurse in the intensive care unit for about six
months, was arrested after a patient complained that Angelo had
injected him with an unknown drug.
   The patient, Gerolamo Kucich, a 75-year-old Yugoslavian,
testified that a man with a beard and a white coat gave him an
injection ``to make me feel better.'' Kucich, the only victim now
alive, said how almost immediately after the injection he couldn't
breathe and his body went limp.
   Authorities exhumed 33 bodies of patients at Good Samaritan who
died suspiciously during Angelo's tenure.
   The medical examiner found traces of Pavulon in six of the
bodies. He determined that Pavulon directly caused the death of
four of the victims buit that there was insufficient evidence in
the two others to determine if Pavulon contributed to the deaths.
   The prosecution linked Angelo to the Pavulon through Angelo's
statements and a Pavulon-laced syringe found in his apartment the
day before his arrest.
</TEXT>
