<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     12-14 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Signing of IMF Agreement Expected Early Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's expected signing of a letter of
intent on a key economic adjustment program with the International
Monetary Fund probably won't occur until next week, a government
source said Thursday.
   The agreement, in which Poland commits itself to specific
economic reforms in exchange for $700 million in standby IMF loans,
is expected to open the way to even larger Western loans and debt
rescheduling from other sources.
   IMF head Michel Camdessus, in Poland on Monday, had predicted
the signing of the letter of intent as early as this week.
   But a government official, demanding anonymity, said IMF
negotiators would have to remain in Poland a few extra days to
review economic reform bills approved by the government of Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki on Wednesday.
   ``The negotiations are still going on. They have gone through
about half the text. The mission probably will prolong its stay and
the letter probably will be signed at the beginning of next week,''
the source said.
   The agreement has been the linchpin of Poland's hope for massive
aid from the West and rescheduling of its $40 billion hard-currency
debt.
   The IMF, a Washington-based consortium of 152 nations in which
the United States is the largest shareholder, has played a key role
in helping Poland plan a major restructuring of its economy.
   Under the direction of Deputy Premier Leszek Balcerowicz, the
government is putting together more than a dozen bills to fight
inflation, restructure the economy to promote private ownership and
competition and transform the Polish zloty into an internally
convertible currency.
   Among the bills appoved by the Council of Ministers on Wednesday
was one defining the concept of an unemployed worker, setting out
procedures for laying off workers and providing for unemployment
benefits.
   The legislative package, the most extensive economic reform
program ever attempted by an East bloc government, is to be
submitted Sunday to the Parliament for approval. The target date of
implementing the program is Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
