<FIRST>u a PM-NursingHomeFire 6thLd-Writethru a0574 12-14 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Fire, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0574,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire at Retirement Home Kills Four, Injures 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 23 injured, victims' ages,
other detail; SUBS last 4 grafs with 7 grafs with victims' identities,
most of building not subject to state regulation. Ottis in 8th graf is
cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a retirement home early today
killed four residents and sent people in wheelchairs and pajamas
into the freezing cold. At least 23 people were hurt in the home's
third fatal blaze in 13 years.
   TV crews dropped their cameras to help rescue people from the
burning six-story Shenandoah Homes Retirement Community, and
residents designated as floor ``fire captains'' knocked on doors
and led their neighbors to safety.
   The dead, ages 77 to 86, were found in four rooms on the third
floor, where the fire broke out about 2:30 a.m., but the blaze
spread heavy smoke to the upper floors before it was brought under
control 2{ hours later, authorities said.
   About 135 residents, some using wheelchairs and dressed only in
pajamas, were evacuated in 19-degree cold to a roller skating rink,
authorities said. Some were sent to hospitals, others picked up by
relatives.
   ``The smoke was horrible,'' said Louise Dudney, 79, a
sixth-floor resident sitting on a bench at the rink. ``I thought I
couldn't make it but told myself I'm going to make it. I ran out
and started knocking on doors.''
   Twenty-three people were taken to three hospitals, with most of
them suffering from smoke inhalation, chest pains or injuries
related to falling, authorities said. The injured included three
firefighters and a police officer.
   Seven victims remained hospitalized this afternoon, one listed
in serious condition with smoke inhalation. The rest were treated
and released.
   ``It is a sad day,'' said Roanoke County Fire Chief Tommy Fuqua.
   It was the third fatal fire at the brick building, which has no
sprinkler system but was equipped with smoke detectors and fire
barriers, authorities said. In 1976, a fire killed four residents
of the home. Three months earlier, a blaze started by a dropped
cigarette killed a woman.
   Today's blaze came two months after a fire at a nursing home in
Norfolk killed 12 residents. That home had no sprinklers, prompting
demands that the Legislature make such systems mandatory at all
nursing homes.
   The cause of the fire today was under investigation.
   ``They have all the equipment they are required to have,'' Fuqua
said. ``The alarm system worked, the smoke detectors worked.''
   The fire caused major damage to only one room, said Fire Marshal
Ken Sharp.
   R.C. Wilson, the retirement home chaplain, said able residents
had been trained as ``fire captains'' or ``fire assistants.''
   Ottis Burgher, administrator for the home, said, ``It was just a
marvel how these elderly people reacted under pressure.''
   Early reports incorrectly described the home, which has 124
apartments, as a nursing home.
   Only one floor is licensed by the state as a home for adults, a
lower level of care than a nursing home, according to Richard
Martin of the Virginia Department of Social Services and Welfare.
The rest of the building was not subject to state regulation, he
said.
   Fuqua said officers and camera crews from TV stations were the
first to arrive, and some reporters and photographers helped in the
rescue.
   ``Everybody that was out here were heroes,'' Fuqua said. ``They
evacuated people before they even tried to put out the fire.
   Killed were Rada Powell, 77; Edna S. Aliff, 77; Linard H. Mann,
86, and Marcie L. Keith, 80, the Sheriff's Department said.
</TEXT>
