<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Somalia     12-14 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Somalia,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Refugees to Begin Repatration in March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voluntary repatriation of tens
of thousands of Ethiopians who sought refuge in Somalia 12 years
ago during a war between the nations should begin in March,
officials said Thursday.
   The repatriation is dependent, however, on Somalia completing
registration of the refugees by the end of February, said officials
of Ethiopia, Somalia and the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
after a two-day meeting.
   The refugees are predominantly ethnic Somali Ethiopians who took
refuge in Somalia during the two nations' war in 1977-78 over a
piece of arid land in southeastern Ethiopia called the Ogaden,
which is principally inhabited by the nomadic ethnic Somalis.
   The number of refugees has never been certain. Somalia says
there are 700,000, the U.N. group puts the figure at 160,000, and
Ethiopia says they number about 100,000.
   Somalia has begun registering refugees in southern Somalia, but
not in the north where fighting has intensified between government
troops and Somali rebels.
   During the registration, refugees will be asked if they want to
return to Ethiopia. Those who don't will be granted limited
assistance to help them settle in Somalia.
</TEXT>
