<FIRST>u a PM-RitterInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0542 12-14 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritter Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0542,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Covenant House Founder Denies Allegations by Male Prostitute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Ritter denial at news conference.
PICKS UP 8th graf, `The shelter's...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Bruce Ritter, founder of the Covenant
House for runaways, today denied charges of financial improprieties
leveled by a former male prostitute the priest has helped.
   ``They are simply nonsense,'' Ritter said. The priest said that
news reports on the matter have been inaccurate and that a special
audit just completed by an accounting firm showed ``no misuse of
funds whatsoever.''
   A day earlier, the district attorney said an investigation of
the allegations was still at an early stage.
   ``No determination has been made as to the truth of the
allegations, nor can such a determination be made until the
investigation has been concluded,'' Manhattan District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau said in a statement Wednesday.
   The New York Post first disclosed the investigation, reporting
Tuesday that it began when a former male prostitute told
prosecutors the Roman Catholic priest provided him with an
apartment, money and gifts and took him on trips.
   A law enforcement source identified the young man for The
Associated Press as Timothy Warner, 20.
   The Post reported today that investigators had the youth wear a
recording device during a conversation with Ritter in an effort to
confirm allegations that they had a sexual relationship. It is not
clear what Warner recorded.
   Ritter, a 62-year-old Franciscan priest, had not spoken publicly
about the allegations before today. But the Post quoted him earlier
this week as denying any sexual misconduct and suggesting that
emotional problems led the young man to make ``scurrilous''
allegations.
   The shelter's chief executive officer, James Harnett, and
Ritter's lawyer, Stanley Arkin, denied any financial wrongdoing by
Ritter or Covenant House. Covenant House officials have said that
such expenditures are normal and that Warner was put in a ``safe
house'' to keep him away from his criminal past.
   ``There is no case and there never was any case,'' Arkin said.
   ``I think it was outrageous and disgusting for the district
attorney to outfit this kid with a wire to try to entrap Father
Ritter,'' Harnett said. ``I can tell you Father Ritter is a lot
calmer about this than I am.''
   Ritter founded Covenant House for homeless teen-agers in 1969
and has built it into an $85 million-a-year operation with seven
shelters in the United States, one in Toronto and four in Latin
America. More than 90 percent of its funding is private.
   Morgenthau said Covenant House is cooperating with the
investigation and subpoenas have not been necessary.
   Ritter brought Warner to New York from New Orleans in February
after the young man told the priest he wanted to escape
prostitution.
   Harnett acknowledged Ritter and Warner took trips in which they
were alone together.
   The two men attended the wedding in June of a Covenant House
staff member in Wyomissing, Pa., and shared a room. He said Ritter
`is categorical that he and the kid slept in separate beds and
nothing sexual went on, nothing.''
   In February, they spent a night at a board member's Rhinebeck,
N.Y., country home, which is used frequently for group outings. The
two stayed in a guest house, Harnett said.
   The Post reported Wednesday that an employee at Covenant House
had said Ritter might have been involved with a second youth. The
district attorney's office refused to comment.
   In a statement supporting Ritter, Cardinal John O'Connor said,
``In all my personal association with Father Ritter and those who
work with him, I have seen nothing but self-sacrifice and
commitment to the most abandoned in society.''
</TEXT>
