<FIRST>r w AM-Brady-Surgery     12-14 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brady-Surgery,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Brady Undergoes Successful Hip Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady
successfully underwent elective surgery Thursday to replace his
arthritic right hip, the department reported.
   ``Everything went fine,'' said a department official, who
declined to be identified. ``The secretary's doing great.''
   It is uncertain when Brady will be released from the hospital,
but recovery is expected to last three to six weeks, the official
said. During that time, Deputy Secretary John Robson will serve as
acting secretary.
   Despite his absence from the department, Brady will remain in
touch with Treasury officials and take part in major decisions just
as he does when traveling outside the capital, officials said.
   Among the pending decisions are the fiscal 1991 budget, which
President Bush plans to send to Congress on Jan. 22, and the
contents of Bush's State of the Union address.
   Officials said Brady chose this time for the operation because
Congress is in recess until next month.
   Officials refused to disclose where the operation occurred.
   Brady, who became treasury secretary in August 1988, has
suffered for some time from the arthritic hip, which lately has
caused him to walk with a slight limp.
   Until his hip worsened, Brady enjoyed playing tennis,
occasionally as Bush's partner, and was a low-handicap golfer.
</TEXT>
