<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Refugees     12-14 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Refugees,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Criticism of Forced Repatriations Stirs British Resentment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. criticism of Britain's forced repatriation of
Vietnamese from Hong Kong has stirred resentment in the Thatcher
government and raised new doubts about the special relationship
between the two nations.
   Britain also faces more criticism from an announcement expected
shortly that it will admit only a select minority of Hong Kong
Chinese if things go wrong when the colony reverts to China in 1997.
   Officially, Foreign Office Minister Francis Maude described as
``misguided'' a U.S. State Department statement Tuesday that the
forced repatriation of 51 Vietnamese boat people was unacceptable.
The deportations were the first of thousands expected in the coming
years.
   But the British government resentment goes deeper than the
diplomatic parlance.
   ``It is no good complaining unless they are prepared to take
more (Vietnamese refugees),'' Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was
quoted as saying in a newspaper interview Thursday, referring to
the United States and other critics.
   ``I know what their reason against taking more is. It is that
the more they take, the more will come,'' she was quoted as saying
in the London's Daily Star. ``One doesn't like having to do it, but
we have to think of our responsibility to the people of Hong Kong.''
   It is a phrase likely to be used against her when, in an
announcement scheduled before the end of the year, the government
says how many of the 6 million Hong Kong Chinese will be granted
rights of residence in Britain. They include 3.25 million people
who now have British passports without the right of abode.
   Most analysts expect Britain will give residence rights to
between 100,000-200,000 Hong Kong Chinese, mostly people who have
worked for the British administration or members of the colony's
thriving entrepreneurial class.
   The latter find it easiest to get into other Western countries,
notably Canada, the United States and Australia. They already
leaving at the rate of about 1,000 a week.
   British officials complain privately that what one called a U.S.
``hang-up'' about Vietnam has brought London and Washington into
open conflict over the forced repatriation of Vietnamese refugees
classified as economic migrants.
   The clash comes when Mrs. Thatcher is already widely portrayed
as sidelined by the United States. The 12-nation European Economic
Community as a bloc and West Germany in particular have become the
focus of U.S. attention amid the rapid changes in Eastern Europe.
   There are signs the dispute will get worse as thousands more of
the 44,000 Vietnamese whom Britain is determined to deport are
bundled out of the colony with TV cameras recording scenes of
emotion.
   ``Given the major changes in Europe, it is just an enormous
waste of political capital for Britain and the United States to
have a row about this,'' said Gerald Segal, an analyst at London's
Royal Institute of International Affairs.
   ``But it is going to get worse without any question,'' Segal
said in an interview. ``Because of the focus on West Germany, the
United States may also feel that there is little cost in having a
major argument with Britain on the repatriation issue. If it comes
to that, I think Britain will turn fairly nasty.''
   Right now, Britain sounds aggrieved at the universal criticism
from its allies as Hong Kong, the last significant remains of a
once globe-encircling empire, turns into an international
controversy.
   ``We do not look for the world's applause, but we are entitled
to ask for the world's understanding,'' said Sir David Ford, chief
secretary in the British-run Hong Kong administration.
   ``This is not a role or responsibility we have sought. It is one
that geography and circumstances have thrust upon us.''
   As well as attracting Western disapproval, Mrs. Thatcher is
under ferocious attack from British opposition parties and some
newspapers over the repatriation issue.
   The government, whose move is highly popular with the Hong Kong
Chinese and Beijing officials, retorts that no one else has offered
to take the boat people.
   More than 90 percent are peasants from north Vietnam, while the
majority of the 900,000 Vietnamese settled in the United States
since the war ended in 1975 are from the south.
   British officials said the United States is reluctant to take
the northerners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
