<FIRST>r w AM-US-Syria     12-14 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Syria,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Critical of Syria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is turning up the heat in an
effort to persuade Syria to kick out the terrorist believed
responsible for the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, a State
Department source said Thursday.
   ``It's a matter of degree, of frequency and of language,'' the
source, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said about
increased diplomatic contacts with Syria.
   The official said the increased pressure did not include direct
threats, but that there had been a measured turning up of the heat
in the most recent contacts, some of which have come through U.S.
Ambassador Edward Djerejian.
   Threats, the source said, would be counterproductive against a
tough-minded leader such as Syrian President Hafez Assad. The
source also said that U.S. relations with Syria already are cool,
leaving the United States little with which to bargain.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said the United
States is unhappy with Syria's refusal to eject Ahmed Jibril,
believed to have engineered the Pan Am attack a year ago.
   The headquarters of Jibril's organization, the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, are in Damascus, and
he has at least one training camp outside Damascus.
   ``This is a major item on our bilateral agenda with Syria,''
Boucher said in response to a question Thursday at the daily State
Department briefing. ``To date we're not satisfied with the Syrian
governmnent's responses and we think the Syrian government can do
more.''
   Boucher said the United States had had ``extensive discussions''
and has made ``repeated demarches ... on the issue of terrorism and
Syrian support for terrorism groups.''
   Syria's response has been to insist that it be shown hard
evidence linking Gibril to the explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland,
that killed 270 people. The United States has been reluctant to do
so because such a move might jeopardize the criminal investigation
or expose sensitive intelligence sources.
   ``The Syrian government, at the highest levels, has told us that
if it is presented with firm evidence that any group or individuals
within its purview are responsible for Pan Am 103, the Syrian
government will take action against them,'' Boucher said.
   However, the department source said the United States believes
the Syrians ``should bounce Jibril, just as they bounced Abu
Nidal,'' another terrorist, because of his overall record of
violence independent of the Pan Am case.
   U.S. officials are unsure whether Assad knew of the plans for
the Pan Am bombing before it occurred, but believe he now is well
aware of Jibril's involvement.
   Jibril is a former Syrian army major believed to have continuing
close ties to Syrian intelligence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
