<DOCNO> AP891214-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Journalists-Escape     12-14 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Journalists-Escape,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists' Escape From Confederate Prison To Be Commemorated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daring escape of three war
correspondents from a Confederate prison 125 years ago will be
commemorated this weekend in a ceremony organizers hope will also
focus attention on hostage Terry Anderson's plight.
   On Dec. 18, 1864, New York Daily Tribune reporters Albert
Richardson and Junius Browne and the Cincinnati Gazette's William
Davis masterminded an escape from Salisbury Prison after 19 months
in captivity.
   Contemporaries referred to their 340-mile journey to freedom
across the Blue Ridge Mountains as ``The Walk of the Journalists.''
   ``These gentlemen were not unlike Terry Anderson,'' said Mark
McDonald, the executive director of the Historic Salisbury
Foundation Inc., which is co-sponsoring the event with the Society
of Civil War Correspondents. ``They were 19th century political
prisoners. They were imprisoned not because they took up arms but
because of what they wrote.
   Anderson, the chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been held hostage since his capture in Beirut, Lebanon,
in March 1985.
   ``Wherever Terry is being held, we fervently wish he might find
some inspiration from the successful struggle of Richardson, Browne
and Davis,'' McDonald said.
   Joining the journalists in their escape 125 years ago were
Connecticut merchant marine Capt. Thomas E. Wolfe and Sgt. Charles
Thurston of the 6th New Hampshire Infantry.
   McDonald said Richardson and Browne, who were captured during
the battle of Vicksburg in May 1863, were granted special status at
the prison.
   ``Richardson was given the job of collecting usable clothing
from the dead,'' he said Wednesday. Richardson was given a pass
that allowed him to go outside the prison walls to perform his
duties.
   The reporters later used the pass to trick the guards and make
their escape.
   ``The escape itself did not feature any cloak and dagger,''
McDonald said. ``Their journey had a lot more daring associated
with it.''
   McDonald said they had a good reason to escape when they did.
   ``The current commander of the prison, Major John Ghee, was
being replaced by General Bradlee Johnson,'' a strict
disciplinarian, he said. ``They decided to get out while the
getting was good.''
   Twenty-six days later, on Jan. 13, 1865, they arrived in
Union-held Knoxville, Tenn.
   Within a day of their arrival, the Tribune, which was run by
staunch abolitionist Horace Greeley, reported their exploits under
the headline ``Out of the Jaws of Death.''
   Salisbury Prison, which was constructed around an abandoned
cotton mill, held more than 10,000 prisoners in October 1864.
Between that date and February 1865, 3,419 of its prisoners died.
   The prison was destroyed by Union cavalry in April 1865.
   Beginning on Friday, the escape will be commemorated in downtown
Salisbury with lectures, a walking tour, living history portrayals,
a banquet and a re-creation.
   The escape will be re-created Saturday at 3:30 p.m., the hour of
the flight.
   Gerald A. Regan, a copy editor with USA Today, and U.S. Naval
Academy English professor Robert Madison will portray Richardson
and Browne. They will also give readings from books the Tribune
reporters wrote about their Civil War exploits.
   ``This is not a story of North vs. South, but of men caught up
in a war who refuse to accept captivity,'' said Regan. ``They would
be free because they would accept nothing less, no matter what the
odds or dangers.
   ``Journalists don't set out to be heroes, but heroic efforts are
sometimes required in the pursuit of the news,'' he said.
   Among the weekend's speakers will be Allen Ellis, an assistant
professor at Northern Kentucky University and a descendant of Dan
Ellis, who helped guide the journalists over the mountains to
freedom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-Larson     12-14 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Larson,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cartoonist Back At Work After 14-Month Sabbatical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Larson, who took a 14-month
sabbatical from producing his popular cartoon ``The Far Side,'' is
back at the drawing table.
   The first of his new panels will be for release starting Jan. 1,
John P. McMeel, president of Universal Press Syndicate, said
Wednesday. More than 900 newspapers _ more than before the
sabattical began _ will carry the cartoon.
   Larson, known for a bizarre outlook expressed primarily through
animal characters and nerdy people, took a break from active
cartoon production starting in October 1988. During the interim,
newspapers buying the service received ``classic'' selections from
his earlier work.
   Larson said he took the sabbatical because he needed a break
``after nine years of deadlines.'' He Larson and his wife visited
Africa and the Amazon in South America during the break and spent
four months in New York, where he studied jazz guitar. Their home
is in Seattle.
   His only drawing, he said in a statement released by the
syndicate, was a cover for an album by guitarist Herb Ellis, ``and
the few ideas I wrote down were things that seeped in unavoidably.''
   He admitted to mixed feelings about being back at work.
   ``I currently feel fresh and recharged, and a reduced workload
I'm sure will play a big role in maintaining that feeling,'' he
said. ``But, as I'm sure anyone who has had an opportunity to take
a full year off will agree, that first Monday morning back to work
is quite a sobering experience.''
   Under his new schedule, Larson will produce five original panels
a week, with reissues of old cartoons supplied to newspapers to use
during the rest of the week.
</TEXT>
