<DOCNO> AP891214-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     12-14 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 6-year-old Sean McQuillan dialed 911, he
thought he had an emergency on his hands. His brother had taken one
of his toys.
   When police arrived at his home after Sean left the phone off
the hook he got a lesson on what the emergency number is for.
   Instead of writing Santa Claus this week, Sean was writing an
apology to ``Mr. Policeman.''
   ``I know you need to catch burglars and help kids who are hurt
or lost or robbed,'' Sean wrote. ``You can't do that if you are at
my house when I don't need you. I am sorry I called you when I did
not need you.''
   A clown had visited Sean's school to introduce children to the
911 emergency system. And the boy figured he'd get to talk to the
clown if he called 911. There was no clown on the line, so he hung
up.
   ``I chewed him out and thought it was the end of it,'' Debbie
McQuillan said Wednesday of her son's first call six months ago.
But last month Sean was at it again while his mother was busy
taking care of her grandmother.
   ``He wanted the policeman to (make his brother) give it back,''
Mrs. McQuillan said of the toy.
   Because Sean left the phone off the hook, police couldn't call
back to check on the situation and an officer was sent to the
McQuillan home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Froelich and Evelyn Kaufman both
have the distinction of having headed the Board of Governors of
State Colleges and Universities _ and they both got their college
degrees this week.
   The women, who had been away from the classroom for a
generation, earned credit for professional experience and added
campus coursework to earn their bachelor of arts degrees from
Eastern Illinois University. They joined more than 500 other EIU
students receiving degrees during fall commencement.
   The women are among 11,500 adult learners in the special Board
of Governors bachelor of arts degree program.
   Mrs. Froelich is chairwoman and Mrs. Kaufman is a member and
former chairwoman of the board, which sets policies for five state
universities in Illinois. But until Sunday, neither had degrees.
   ``I was a little frightened. You think maybe you're not as smart
as you thought you were,'' said Mrs. Kaufman, a 73-year-old civic
leader and former secretary from Chicago with no college
experience. ``But, I did it. I saw a dream fulfilled.''
   Mrs. Froelich, 59, who lives north of Bloomington in McLean
County, said she quit college in 1950 to marry.
   ``One of the things that has always bothered me is that I didn't
finish,'' she said. As for going back to school, she said, ``The
best part was finding out I could really compete in today's
academic world.''
</TEXT>
