<FIRST>r a AM-KlanMarch     12-14 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Klan March,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Klan Protest Organizers Predict 500 Marchers, Police Far Fewer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY KINNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members and supporters of the Ku Klux Klan
will rally in a quiet college town in support of two high school
students disciplined for wearing Klan robes to school, police said
Thursday.
   But citizens groups are urging residents to ignore Saturday's
march, 10 times the normal number of police will be on duty and,
based on previous Klan attempts to hold rallies in southwestern
Ohio, officials say the event probably will be a big to-do about
nothing.
   ``Frankly, I think they have gotten far too much publicity over
this,'' City Manager Dennis Stuckey said. ``There is a group in the
community that is actively promoting the shunning of the march. It
may well be that there are more media than there are marchers and
spectators.''
   Klansman Ernie Edwards of Morrow received a city permit for the
gathering, telling police 500 people would participate.
   Saturday's rally follows an incident in which two students
showed up at Oxford's Talawanda High School on Halloween in Klan
robes and shouted racial epithets. Blacks held an
anti-discrimination march the following week.
   Edwards, who told police he represented a group called U.S.
Knights, has not been available for comment; a woman who answered
his phone hung up on a reporter.
   The Klan march will start and end at the high school, where
about 50 of the 1,100 students are black.
   But Edwards was told his group would have to march on sidewalks
unless enough marchers show up to make it worthwhile to close city
streets.
   ``We don't want to inconvenience a lot of people for a few
(marchers),'' said Lt. Dick McVey, acting chief of police in the
town northwest of Cincinnati.
   ``I don't know what to expect, whether curiosity-seekers will
come out to look at these individuals, and that's one of our
concerns. Our plan is tobe prepared for the worst.''
   McVey will have 35 officers in the two-block-square march area,
including several county and township officers. Three or four
officers patrol Oxford on a typical Saturday.
   ``They say they'll have 500 people,'' McVey said. ``I warned
them that if not the expected number show up, I might encourage the
city attorney to seek payment for all these officers.''
   Oxford, home of Miami University, has a population of about
20,000 people, McVey said; 94.2 percent are white.
   ``I have personal feelings and official opinions about this,''
Stuckey said. ``My official position is that they have as much
right to congregate as anyone does. We work with all kinds of
groups because of the nature of the community. I guess it's more
routine for us ... to have activities of this nature.''
   Police departments say there probably are no more than 25 KKK
members in the area, but that it doesn't take many to stir things
up.
   The Green Ribbon Committee of Oxford was formed in response to
Saturday's march. It adopted green ribbons as a symbol of anti-Klan
sentiment and has been tying ribbons to trees and utility poles in
town to protest the march, which it wants residents to boycott.
</TEXT>
