<FIRST>u w AM-AirFares     12-14 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Fares,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Investigating Air Fare Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is investigating
whether some airlines violated antitrust laws when they increased
fares earlier this year, department and industry officials said
Thursday.
   The department's antitrust division has asked several airlines
to submit information about how they determine fares, including an
correspondence between carriers about an increase that took effect
Sept. 29, airline officials said.
   Several airlines increased fares on some routes between $10 and
$80, depending on how many days before departure tickets are
purchased.
   An antitrust expert who spoke on condition on anonymity said the
government was probably examining the industry's practice of
reporting fare increases before they take effect.
   Under this theory of antitrust violation, the pre-publication of
fare increases to travel agents and an industry clearinghouse
called the Airline Tariff Publishers Inc. would be viewed as a
``facilitating device'' for price fixing, the expert said.
   While ``it would be difficult to prove an agreement'' among
airlines to raise fares, the Justice Department might try to show
that the pre-publication of fares is way to signal price increases,
this expert said.
   An airline would ``run a price up the flagpole. If everybody
salutes it, it goes into effect,'' the expert said. If no one
follows suit, the airline is free to cancel the planned increase.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said civil
investigative demands were sent to ``a number of carriers within a
short period of time after the Sept. 29 effective date.''
   She declined to say which airlines received the orders or to
give details of the inquiry.
   ``We have complied with requests for information, but we really
don't see any basis for the investigation,'' said David Messing,
spokesman for Continental Airlines.
   Delta, Northwest and American, which was the first to indicate
it was raising fares, also acknowledged receiving requests for
information.
   Three other airlines that the Wall Street Journal reported were
subject to investigation _ USAir, United and Trans World _ declined
comment.
   The public affairs department at Pan American, also cited in the
Journal report, said no spokesman was immediately available.
   Jim Lundy of Delta said the Justice Department asked for any
correspondence between Delta and other airlines over fares.
   ``There was none,'' he said.
   The order also asked for information about the airline's
ticket-pricing operations and the way it makes decisions on fares,
along with the process used in determining the Sept. 29 increase.
   When an airline files a fare increase, it appears in a
ticket-pricing database available to all carriers, and in the
computer reservations systems used by travel agents.
   ``No one can really afford to be at a competitive disadvantage
for more than a few hours,'' Lundy said. ``You have to move very
quickly.''
   Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons said the company ran an analysis
of its Sept. 29 fare increase after the government inquiry and
determined that ``we followed standard procedures.''
   He said once a fare increase is filed electronically, each
carrier has to decide whether to reduce, increase or maintain its
fare on each competitive route.
   Airlines say that pre-publication of fares is necessary to
enable the public to plan in advance.
   If the government can prove its case, it might be able to obtain
an injunction either to stop the pre-publication of air fares or
some change in procedures to prevent airlines from signaling their
increases.
</TEXT>
