<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Famine     12-14 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Famine,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 300,000 Could Starve Because of New Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300,000 southern Sudanese face
starvation because renewed fighting between government and rebels
has suspended relief operations in the region, a Western official
said Thursday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said food
stocks at the southern capital of Juba were expected to run out in
a week.
   He said a new international operation to send about 90,000
metric tons of relief food to southern Sudan in January is
paralyzed until the government allows resumption of flights
carrying aid to the south.
   The U.N. representative to Sudan, Michael Bristly, left Khartoum
on Wednesday for a meeting with U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez
de Cuellar to ``see what he can do to get things moving,'' the
official said.
   ``Some 300,000 persons in the south will face famine because
both the rebel SPLA (Sudan People's Liberation Army) and the
Sudanese government are reluctant to allow the safe passage of
relief to the needy people in the south of Sudan,'' the official
told The Associated Press.
   ``If people are to be saved and a repetition of the 1988 plague
is to be avoided, food has to be taken to these people as urgently
as possible,'' he said.
   Some Western relief officials believe more than 560,000 people
died in 1988 from starvation or fighting in the south. The United
Nations believes the figure is closer to 250,000. The entire
country has a population of about 25 million.
   The relief official interviewed Thursday said the 90,000
additional tons of food must be in place in the south before March,
when heavy rains make many roads and airstrips unusable.
   The southerners are victims of a manmade famine. Fighting in the
southern countryside of this East African country has driven more
than 2 million people from farms and homes since the rebels began
their battle for more autonomy in 1983. The refugees fled either
toward a handful of government-held southern towns and became
dependent of relief, or they trekked north to Khartoum.
   In April, a cease-fire allowed the U.N.-coordinated operation
``Lifeline Sudan'' to send about 70,000 tons of food into southern
Sudan. The relief prevented a repeat of the 1988 disaster,
officials say.
   But relief flights into the south have been suspended by the
government since October after the renewed fighting. The government
said the suspension of flights was ``for the safety and security of
the relief personnel.''
   The Western relief official said Juba, capital of the southern
Eqatoria region 775 miles south of Khartoum, already faces a food
shortage.
   ``Maize has become as precious as gold, and there will be no
(relief) grain or wheat or sorghum in Juba at the end of this
month'' the official said.
   There are about 300,000 people in the city. More than half are
southern refugees.
   Western doners have asked the government to hold a conference
with them on Jan. 25 to discuss the food needs of the south.
   On Wednesday, the Sudan News Agency quoted Social Welfare
Undersecretary Ibrahim Abu-Ouf as saying the government was
considering the idea.
</TEXT>
