<DOCNO> AP891214-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0607 12-14 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Abolish Secret Police Agency Amid Mounting Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 7 grafs SUB for grafs 4-5, Also Thursday ... UPDATING with meeting
on keeping peace, Erfurt demonstration, details. Picks up 6th, `The Interior
... with minor editing to trim and conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reform activists scored another victory for
democracy Thursday by pressuring the government into abolishing the
hated secret police agency that tried to suppress their peaceful
revolt.
   The decision to shut down the Office for National Security came
out of negotiations between Communist leaders and opposition
groups, and amid increasing threats against secret police officials
by citizens angry about previous excesses.
   The Interior Ministry said threats and attacks against secret
police have increased at an ``alarming rate,'' and warned East
Germans against trying to take the law into their own hands.
   The official East German news agency ADN said government
officials, police and reform activists met late Thursday to discuss
how to keep the peace in East Berlin. ADN said the ``discussion
partners'' asked citizens to act responsibly.
   The capital appeared calm and the rain-soaked central streets
were nearly deserted after businesses closed. But violent incidents
have been reported in other major cities.
   More than 10,000 demonstrators braved bad weather in Erfurt to
push for reforms and warn against selling out to West Germany. But
ADN said banners supporting reunification were ``unmissable.''
   Also Thursday, West German Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann
met with Communist Premier Hans Modrow and the two sides agreed to
set up a joint economic commission and broaden cooperation.
   Haussmann said more than 40 percent of West Germany's booming
industries have expressed interest in expanding their businesses
into a reformed East German economy.
   The Soviet Union's chief ideologist, Politburo member Alexander
Yakovlev, came to East Berlin late Thursday for a meeting with
Communist Party chief Gregor Gysi before this weekend's important
party congress.
   The East German party is trying to restructure itself into a
movement for ``democratic socialism,'' to win public trust and a
chance at a role in government after next spring's free elections.
   The Interior Ministry said posters have appeared on factory
walls calling Communist Party and secret police officials
``traitors who deserve the death penalty.''
   In Dresden, about 50 people dragged one man out of his car and
tied a towing cable around his neck, shouting: ``Communist swine,
we'll hang you!'' the ministry reported in a statement carried by
ADN.
   A lynching was prevented by a man who managed to bring the crowd
under control, the report said.
   Elke Guenther of New Forum, the largest of East Germany's
pro-democracy groups, praised the dissolution of the ``Stasi''
secret police as a concession that may ease tension.
   Ms. Guenther said the secret police harassed leaders of the
reform movement until weeks ago, when the swelling force for change
forced the ouster of Erich Honecker's 18-year, hard-line leadership
and burst open the door to the West.
   The State Security Ministry already had been downgraded to the
National Security Agency and about 10,000 agents had been sent to
work in industry.
   Dozens of soldiers stood guard around secret police headquarters
in East Berlin after the decision to shut down the service was
disclosed.
   A spokesman in the press office of the security agency said the
government would divide the agency's responsibilites among other
ministries.
   ``This decision is another consequence of the round-table
talks,'' government spokesman Wolfgang Meyer said at a news
conference.
   Communist Party officials last week opened talks with
representatives of rival political parties and fledgling pro-reform
movements to discuss the nation's future. The first session agreed
on a May 6, 1990, date for the nation's first free elections.
   The secret police apparatus was a major target of opposition
criticism. Angry citizens took over secret police headquarters in
Leipzig, Gera and other cities to prevent destruction of evidence
against officials accused of corruption.
   Honecker is among those accused of having misused their offices
and indulged in high living as the national economy stagnated.
   Meyer said the Wandlitz settlement where former leaders have
been under house arrest will be converted to a rehabilitation
center for handicapped children by February.
   At talks on making Western investment in East Germany more
secure and attractive, Haussmann laid out a plan that calls for
measures to protect the assets of foreign investors and ease
restrictions that discourage joint ventures.
   Haussmann said after his meetings with Modrow and East Germany's
economics minister, Christa Luft, that he considered an agreement
on Western investment protection to be essential by February.
   Ms. Luft said seven major industrial complexes will be operating
on a self-financing and independent basis as an experiment in
broadening the rights and responsibilities of East German
enterprises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
