<DOCNO> AP891214-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-14 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Guerrillas Attack Syrian Military Base, 13 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian guerrillas attacked a Syrian
base in south Lebanon Thursday and freed 15 detained comrades in a
two-hour foray in which at least 13 people were killed, police
reported.
   Syrians troops and armor massed along the Awali River, on the
northern edge of Sidon, apparently preparing for a retaliatory
strike across the line beyond which Israel has said it will not
tolerate Syrian military presence.
   A group calling itself the Organization for the Defense of the
Oppressed threatened to kill Pope John Paul II, claiming he
supports the Lebanese Christian military leader, Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Aoun refuses to bow to a new Christian-Moslem government trying
to end the 14-year-old sectarian war, and has pledged to drive the
Syrians out of Lebanon.
   Thursday's statement was the second threat by the group against
the pope. The first, in August, said he would be killed if he
visited Lebanon.
   Police said about 150 fighters from Fatah, the mainstream
guerrilla faction led by Yasser Arafat, chairman of Palestine
Liberation Organization, stormed and ransacked the Syrian military
intelligence headquarters for south Lebanon.
   Bullet scars and smoke-blackened shell pocks dotted the
three-story headquarters. The blown-off tin roof of a fruit stall
lay next to the building and hundreds of oranges, apparently
spilled during the attack, covered the alleyway.
   The fighters, based in the Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp in Sidon,
traveled 3 miles north and crossed the Awali River to raid the base
on the coastal highway. The river is 40 miles north of the Israeli
border and 25 south of Beirut.
   The guerrillas used jeep-mounted 107mm recoilless guns,
shoulder-fired rocket-propelled grenades and AK-47 assault rifles,
said police and Palestinian sources in Sidon.
   A statement from PLO headquarters in Tunis, Tunisia, did not
deny Fatah's involvement, but condemned the attack.
   ``It is incumbent on the Palestinian leadership to reaffirm that
it condemns totally such acts and that it immediately gave
instructions for the opening of an investigation in collaboration
with the forces present in Sidon ... to identify the authors and
commanders of this attack,'' it said.
   A police source said privately the raid might have been planned
and executed, without Arafat's prior consent, by local Fatah
commanders seeking the release of their comrades.
   ``We can't rule out this possibility, since the Fatah commanders
had blamed the chain of assassinations and assassination attempts
against them in Sidon this year on Syria's military intelligence,''
the source said.
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982 with the stated purpose of
driving out Arafat's guerrillas, and warned Syria when it withdrew
in 1985 not to venture south of the Awali.
   Arafat has been at loggerheads with Syrian President Hafez Assad
since a Syrian-backed mutiny in PLO ranks in 1983.
   More than 2,000 Palestinian guerrillas remain in Syrian jails.
They were arrested in 1983 during an offensive by militias allied
with Syria that forced Arafat loyalists to evacuate Tripoli, a port
in north Lebanon. Arafat had set up his command there after the
Israelis captured Beirut.
   The police spokesman said 15 Palestinians, all from Fatah, were
set free during the raid and taken back to Ein el-Hilweh. They were
among 43 people wounded in the attack, police said.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. It never discloses casualties, but Lebanese
police said the dead included four Syrians, including a major, and
five attackers.
   Also killed were a Communist Party fighter and three militiamen
of the leftist Nasserite Organization, the Sunni Moslem group that
has controlled Sidon since the civil war began in 1975, who manned
a checkpoint on the Awali bridge.
</TEXT>
