<FIRST>r a AM-RitterInvestigation     12-14 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritter Investigation,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Denies Allegations by Male Prostitute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest accused of sexual and
financial misconduct by a male prostitute who once stayed at the
priest's home for runaways denied the charges Thursday and called
them ``deeply offensive.''
   ``I categorically deny these allegations,'' the Rev. Bruce
Ritter said at a crowded news conference in the Covenent House
cafeteria. He said the charges were ``deeply offensive to me'' and
had seriously harmed the image of the 20-year-old, nationally
recognized organization that runs shelters in seven North American
cities and four Central American nations.
   The Manhattan district attorney is investigating charges of
financial improprieties by Ritter, charges made by a 20-year-old
man who also reportedly claimed he had a sexual relationship with
the 62-year-old Franciscan priest.
   Ritter firmly disputed the charges. He said he served as a
special mentor to the man, who nonetheless later lapsed into his
previous life of prostitution.
   Ritter's Covenant House opened in 1969 after six teens showed up
at his apartment looking for a place to stay. The organization now
has more than 1,500 beds and serves about 25,000 children annually.
More than 90 percent of its funding is private.
   Ritter's group was one of 18 honored by President Bush in April
as winners of Ronald Reagan Awards for Volunteer Excellence.
   Ritter said the young man at the center of the dispute was one
of a group of runaway prostitutes who say they are being pursued by
organized crime members who run prostitution rings. They are given
special attention and a personal mentor.
   ``I chose to become his mentor because, frankly, I had more
experience than anyone else,'' Ritter said.
   ``We tried so very hard, and we failed,'' he said. ``It is
probably better to say that I failed. ... I thought I knew more
than I did.''
   Asked why the man would have accused him of such transgressions,
Ritter replied, ``I honestly, simply do not know.''
   He said he last spoke with the man in early November and that he
had chastised him for falling back into prostitution. There was
``definitely a cooling-off of the relationship.''
   Ritter and the authorities have not identified the man, but a
law enforcement source identified him for The Associated Press as
Timothy Warner.
   Ritter produced a memo that he said detailed all the money
Covenant House spent on the man _ $9,800, not $25,000 as reported.
The organization, which has an annual budget of $85 million for its
various shelters, spends an average of $15,000 per person, he said.
   An audit, he said, ``found our books in perfect order. Every
penny is accounted for.''
   The man was treated like other runaways who claim their lives
are in danger from organized crime, he said.
   He stayed at Covenant House's crisis unit, then was set up in an
apartment staffed by Covenant House personnel. Staff members took
him to their homes on special occasions, and Ritter acknowledged
traveling with him a few times, but said there were no sexual
relations.
   ``We provide for these kids a new identity and education
necessary for survival. Their needs are enormous,'' he said. ``They
are almost always boys. They are bereft of family and friends. They
are terrified. They are incapable of trust.''
   The New York Post reported Wednesday that investigators had the
youth wear a recording device during a conversation with Ritter to
try to confirm allegations that they had a sexual relationship.
   Ritter said he was unaware of any taping, though he acknowledged
the conversation ``got a little weird, a little inconsistent.''
   The Post reported that during the taped conversation, Ritter
said, ``I decided a long time ago that if God doesn't like me the
way I am, then that's his problem.''
   Ritter said Thursday that he remembered telling the man, who was
distressed about sliding back into prostitution, that sometimes
``we are what we are.''
</TEXT>
