<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Czechoslovakia     12-14 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Czechoslovakia,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Reportedly Considering Renewal of Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's foreign minister says his
country plans to review relations with Israel, indicating a renewal
of diplomatic ties is near, Israel Television reported Thursday.
   The television also quoted Jiri Dienstbier as telling reporters
in Prague the Middle East conflict should be solved by dialogue.
The television saw that comment as another indication of
Czechoslovakia's plans to revive its ties with the Jewish state.
   All the Eastern bloc countries except Romania cut diplomatic
relations with Israel following the 1967 Middle East war. Hungary,
which is also in the grip of democratic changes, was the first to
renew full diplomatic relations in September.
   The Soviet Union and Poland have renewed low-level diplomatic
relations with Israel in the last three years.
   Israel's representative in Poland, Mordechai Paltzur, returned
to Warsaw this week after a visit to Czechoslovakia.
   He said that ``foreign ministry professionals there have long
thought that some ties with Israel should be reestablished, maybe
not full relations, but some type of ties.''
   ``But the politicians were stony _ Stalinist _ and these
suggestions were not accepted,'' he said in a telephone interview
with Israel Television.
   Czechoslovakia, which is undergoing a wave of democratic reform,
this week installed a government with a non-Communist majority.
   Paltzur said that during the visit to Prague, he discussed such
issues as tourism, cultural and economic ties, and possible air
links between the two countries.
   ``When ties are renewed, they would want to sign agreements on
these subjects,'' he said.
</TEXT>
