<FIRST>r a AM-ToyotaLawsuit     12-14 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toyota Lawsuit,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Awarded $43.2 Million for Car Fire That Killed Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose family burned to death in a 1982
car fire has won a $43.2 million judgment against Toyota, the
largest award ever entered against the company.
   Jurors in a state district court awarded $18.2 million in actual
damages and $25 million in exemplary damages Wednesday to Nike
Adegbite, 36, who watched while her husband and two daughters died
in the burning car six years ago. Two other people also died in the
fire.
   Ms. Adegbite escaped serious injury in the accident involving a
1973 Toyota Corona station wagon, which caught fire after being
rear-ended on a Houston highway.
   Lawyers on both sides expressed surprise at the size of the
judgment against Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. and its parent
company, Toyota Motor Corp.
   ``We were of course surprised at the verdict _ not only by the
extraordinary amount, but that the jury decided against us,'' said
Douglas West, vice president and general counsel for Toyota Motor
Sales in Torrance, Calif.
   Ms. Adegbite was surprised, too, said her lawyer, Stan Pfeiffer.
   ``I think everybody was (shocked). It was an emotional moment,''
he added.
   West said the verdict ``is the highest award against Toyota by a
very wide margin.'' Previously, the largest award against Toyota
was about $5 million, he said.
   West said Toyota will ask the judge to set aside the verdict. If
he doesn't, the company plans to appeal.
   Neither West nor Pfeiffer believed the award was the largest
ever entered against an automobile sales company or manufacturer.
   Pfeiffer said the Sept. 26, 1982, accident happened when the
driver of the car, Boyo Adetoye, tried to steer off a roadway
because he had a flat tire, and his car was struck by a van.
   The impact pushed the station wagon's fuel tank forward,
Pfeiffer said, and the tank was punctured by an empty spare tire
carrier and a valve on the rear axle.
   ``Upon impact, the Toyota burst into flames when the gasoline
tank was punctured. Nike escaped to watch her husband and her two
girls burn to death,'' he said.
   Adetoye suffered minor injuries, but his wife and child also
died. He reached a settlement with Toyota; the amount has not been
disclosed.
   Pfeiffer claimed that if the spare tire had been in place, it
would have acted as a cushion for the fuel tank and prevented the
fire. He argued that Toyota had an obligation to tell buyers that
the tire must be in place as protection against rear-end impacts.
   But West said the missing spare tire played no part in the fire.
   Pfeiffer said the jury found that the design was defective and
that Toyota negligently designed the vehicle and failed to recall
it.
   Toyota denies any defects or negligence in the vehicle's design,
West said.
   Sam Cole, a researcher with the Center for Auto Safety, a
non-profit consumer group in Washington, said Thursday that there
were problems with the design of gas tanks on 1966-73 Corona models.
   He said the tanks were too close to the rear and had no
significant structure to absorb the impact of a crash.
   ``You're driving a time bomb if someone hits you from behind,''
he said.
   At least 17 people have died in fiery accidents involving the
1966-73 Corona models, Cole added. He did not have any specific
information concerning problems with the tanks when the spare isn't
in place in 1973 station wagons.
   Toyota improved Corona gas tanks after 1973, he said. The model
eventually was phased out.
</TEXT>
