<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Flu 1stLd-Writethru a0649 12-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Flu, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flu Outbreak Has 1 Million Britons Suffering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th `Infection levels...' to ADD details
on victims; pickup 5th pvs, `Symptoms of...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1 million Britons are wheezing, running
fevers and nursing headaches during the nation's worst outbreak of
flu in 15 years, doctors said Thursday. Five flu-related deaths
have been reported.
   Among those who are suffering from what doctors call the English
flu is Queen Elizabeth II. This strain, physicians say, is a
variant of the Hong Kong flu that swept Britain in the winter of
1974-75.
   The Royal Society of General Practitioners said Thursday that
infection levels have reached epidemic levels and it expects
400,000 more cases to develop in the next four weeks.
   It said 109 people in every 100,000 had influenza last week and
a further 154 in every 100,000 had influenza-like illness. When the
sickness rate tops 100 per 100,000, the outbreak is considered an
epidemic.
   Infection levels in 1974-75 rose to an average weekly rate of
350 per 100,000 people, the society said.
   The dead are a 16-month-old child, a 7-year-old, two elderly
people and a 35-year-old woman who was six months pregnant. Her
baby could not be saved.
   Symptoms of the disease include fatigue, aching muscles,
headaches, coughing and prolonged fever lasting four or five days.
   Three million doses of flu vaccine have been administered, and
new stock has been flown in from France, West Germany and the
Netherlands.
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke said on British Broadcasting
Corp. television that the health services were unprepared for the
epidemic.
   ``We do try to predict epidemics, but, frankly, it's rather like
trying to predict the weather,'' Clarke said. ``A lot of these
fairly basic diseases like flu do defeat sometimes the best
forecasts that the experts can produce.''
   Nearly 100 hospitals have canceled routine operations and turned
away all non-emergency cases because of a shortage of doctors and
nurses.
   The queen has canceled engagements since Dec. 6. Her sister,
Princess Margaret, was confined to bed this week.
   It's a bonanza though for the medicine industry.
   While many factories have been forced to slow their assembly
lines because of reduced staff, workers at Beecham Pharmaceuticals'
northern England plant are working overtime producing Hot Lemon and
Night Nurse cold treatments.
   ``Demand for our products has risen dramatically in the last few
weeks. We are rushed off our feet trying to keep up,'' said
Beecham's factory manager David Howarth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
