<DOCNO> AP891214-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Court-Drinking     12-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Court-Drinking,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Reinstates Charges Against Parents in Drinking Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother and stepfather of a 15-year-old
boy who died after being allowed to drink more than 25 ounces of
brandy at home must face homicide charges, a state appeals court
ruled Thursday.
   Stephen and Jeanne Garbarino will have to stand trial in the
death of Jeanne's son, Justin Russell, who choked on his own vomit
following the Jan. 18, 1988, drinking bout, said the Appellate
Division of the state Supreme Court.
   The court overturned a Rensselaer County Court decision throwing
out charges of criminally negligent homicide, reckless endangerment
and endangering the welfare of a child against the two adults.
   The court said the family began drinking together around the
kitchen table of their suburban East Greenbush home in response to
an unspecified ``family crisis.'' It soon escalated into a contest
between Russell and his stepfather over who could hold their liquor
better, the court said.
   The boy began vomiting and eventually died. He had a
blood-alcohol level of .41 when he died, the court said. A person
is legally intoxicated in New York state with a blood alcohol level
of .10.
   ``These people placed him in a very precarious position,
endangering his life and welfare by giving him this amount of
alcohol,'' said James Canfield, Rensselaer County district attorney.
   The county court threw out the homicide case, arguing it was
similar to another case where a court said a man could not be
convicted of criminally negligent homicide for giving heroin to a
person who later died of an overdose.
   But the Appellate Division said that shouldn't apply in the
Russell case, noting that the risk of death is ``greatly
increased'' by the amount of alcohol consumed by the boy.
   Lawyers representing both Garbarinos said they intended to
appeal the decision to the state's highest court. They said it
dangerously broadened the legal definition of criminal negligence.
   Peter Moschetti Jr., lawyer for Jeanne Garbarino, and Donald
Shanley, lawyer for Stephen Garbarino, said if the Appellate
Division decision is upheld it could place bartenders and party
hosts in danger of criminal prosecution in cases when they've given
guests too much to drink.
   ``Were they negligent? Yes,'' Moschetti said of the Garbarinos.
``But were they criminally negligent? There's a big difference
between criminal negligence and regular negligence.''
   The lower court found that the Garbarinos couldn't stand trial
for endangering the welfare of a child because of a state law that
says a parent can't be prosecuted for giving alcohol to a minor in
the home.
   But the Appellate Division said that provision only applied to
guardians who give a minimal amount of alcohol to children. The
court said experts testified that even a ``seasoned alcoholic''
would be endangered by drinking as much as Russell did that night.
   ``What purpose is it going to serve to have them (the
Garbarinos) sit in front of a jury and have to look at autopsy
photos of their son?'' Moschetti said.
   ``There is no way they intended to have their child die,''
Moschetti said. ``It's obviously a tragedy ... It's the worse thing
that can happen to a parent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0135 </DOCNO>
