<HEAD>Parents, Teachers Plan Petition Drive to Save TV Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents and teachers in an area with a large
black population say they will petition ABC to save ``Homeroom,'' a
comedy series they say helps keep their kids in school.
   The half-hour program, which debuted in the fall, is being
canceled because of poor ratings, said ABC spokesman Jim Brochu.
   ``All we're saying is give the show a chance,'' said Jim Goins,
who counsels school dropouts in the Watts district. He and other
parents and teachers decided to petition the network after a
meeting Wednesday.
   ``There's not that many shows of color that deal with
educational issues, and we're in a dilemma right now as far as
having black male role models,'' Goins said. ``Not everyone can be
a Bill Cosby.''
   ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's top-rated comedy, stars Bill Cosby as
a doctor whose wife is a lawyer. ``Homeroom'' also has a black
star, Darryl Sivad, who plays a man who gave up a lucrative job in
advertising to teach fourth-graders at an inner-city public school.
   ``The theme of the show allows our children to witness constant
involvement of students in a classroom setting,'' said Goins.
