<HEAD>Morial Won't Seek Return To New Orleans Mayor's Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city's first black mayor announced
Thursday that he won't seek the job he held for eight years.
   Speculation had been high for months that Dutch Morial, who was
mayor from 1978 to 1986 but was prohibited from seeking a third
consecutive term, would run against incumbent Sidney Barthelemy and
challenger Donald Mintz.
   At a news conference Thursday, Morial, 60, said he could have
won the race, but has decided that the demands on his family during
a campaign would be too much.
   ``It's a difficult decision, but the circumstances and the
balancing, the ups and downs and all of the other things that one
has to weigh have dictated it's in perhaps a mutual best interest
that I not seek the office of mayor in 1990,'' Morial said.
``However, that does not preclude other possibilities.''
   He didn't name those possibilities, but he's been mentioned as a
possible candidate for Congress, among other offices.
   Qualifying for the Feb. 3 mayor's race ends Friday afternoon. So
barring a last-minute candidcil member who was a thorn in
the Morial administration's side, and Mintz, an attorney who has
supported Morial in the past.
   Barthelemy succeeded Morial after Morial supporters failed to
persuade voters to change the city charter so the mayor could serve
more than two consecutive terms.
