<FIRST>r w AM-US-Loans     12-14 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Loans,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accord Reached on $15.2 Billion in Loans for Poorest Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agreement was reached Thursday by the United
States and 31 other governments on $15.2 billion worth of easy
loans for more than 50 of the world's poorest countries over a
three-year period.
   ``Ninety percent of the money will go to countries where the
average annual income is $400 a year or less,'' said World Bank
President Barber B. Conable.
   The money will come from the 32 countries with the United States
furnishing the largest share. The total U.S. contribution was put
at $3.18 billion by George A. Folsum, deputy assistant secretary of
the treasury for developing nations.
   Conable said he expects President Bush to ask Congress for the
first $1.08 billion in his next budget, early in the new year. The
overall package of loan money will be available starting next July
1.
   ``We are very pleased with the size of this contribution because
it maintains the size of the U.S. contribution in real terms,''
Folsum said.
   For the previous three years, the United States made the same
contribution, $3.18 billion.
   The new money will be lent out by the bank's International
Development Association for as long as 40 years, at only nominal
interest. With repayments made on loans from earlier years, the
bank expects to have to have about $5.5 billion a year for this
type of loan, Conable said.
   Japan's contribution will be a close second: $3.05 billion at
the exchange rate Folsum used, up from $2.76 billion for the
previous three years.
   The announcement said that $302 million of Japan's contribution
was critical to reaching the final agreement. The accord had been
held back by U.S. delay in agreeing to its share.
   Conable said that China and India are expected to be the biggest
borrowers, taking about $2.3 billion each over the three years.
After China's suppression last June of the movement for democracy,
Conable cut off new loans though continuing to disburse loans
granted earlier.
   ``We hope to resume lending in the not-too-distant future, but
there is no specific date,'' he said.
   He added that the bank is analyzing Chinese financial programs
and other data. ``We're not a political institution,'' he said.
``We talk about economic performance,'' he said.
   Bush nevertheless asked that loans to China be suspended, as
part of his measures against the Chinese government. Last month he
signed into law a bill that requires him to hold back $115 million
of an earlier U.S. contribution unless he certifies that the World
Bank's loans to China will promote individual freedoms and human
rights there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
