<DOCNO> AP891214-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     12-14 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Both Sides Make Proposals at Conventional Arms Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the Warsaw Pact and NATO presented
proposals Thursday designed to reduce six categories of
conventional weapons in Europe and produce an agreement that can be
signed next year.
   After the Warsaw Pact presentation, Polish delegate Wlodzimierz
Konarski told reporters on behalf of the alliance:
   ``The introduction of the East European project is an important
step forward in the negotiations but it is not sufficient. We need
a similar presentation of the Western side ... to have a good basis
for cooperative drafting.''
   NATO presented a proposal several hours later under which the
superpowers would be limited to 275,000 soldiers each and the
numbers of tanks, artillery and other non-nuclear weapons would be
reduced sharply.
   The Western draft ``will strongly spur the negotiations,'' West
German negotiator Ruediger Hartmann said after Spain introduced the
proposal.
   In Geneva, U.S.-Soviet talks aimed at speeding work on a global
ban of chemical weapons adjourned Thursday with the chief U.S.
representative expressing optimism.
   ``I believe a chemical weapons convention, particularly with the
emphasis President Bush has put on it, is highly possible within
the next year or two,'' Max Friedersdorf said in the U.S. Mission's
official Daily Bulletin.
   Since the Vienna talks on conventional weapons began in March,
both sides have praised the spirit of cooperation and expressed
hope for speedy agreement. Their positions are close on ceilings
for some weapons categories.
   In the Warsaw Pact draft presented Thursday, Moscow and its
allies proposed a limit of 4,700 combat airplanes each for each
alliance.
   They also suggested limits of 20,000 battle tanks and 1,900
combat helicopters in an area extending from the Atlantic Ocean to
the Ural Mountains.
   NATO proposed ceilings of 5,700 combat airplanes and the same
numbers as the Warsaw Pact for tanks and helicopters, according to
reports from within the meeting.
   Like the NATO draft, the 40-page Warsaw presentation contained
suggestions for limiting call-ups of reservists and the scope of
military exercises.
   This round of negotiations runs through next week. Still to be
resolved when the talks resume Jan. 11 is the problem of
definitions _ the descriptions of some arms categories.
   The Soviet Union insists, for instance, that more than 1,000
``air defense interceptors'' protecting defenses around Moscow and
the Urals be excluded from reductions in combat airplanes.
   It says the jets are not suitable for either ground attack or
surprise air attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
