<DOCNO> AP891214-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BondRatings     12-14 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bond Ratings,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>State's Bond Ratings Blamed on Political Paralysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bonds issued by Massachusetts have plunged to the
bottom of the nation's ratings as the state's budget deficit has
ballooned above $800 million and lawmakers have failed to come up
with spending cuts or taxes.
   ``The rating problem is really a political one, not an economic
one,'' Wayne Ayers, senior economist at Bank of Boston, said
Thursday.
   This week, Standard &amp; Poor's dropped the state's bond rating
from A to BBB, the lowest in the nation. In November, Moody's
Investors Service dropped Massachusetts from A to Baa 1, tying it
with Louisiana for the bottom ranking.
   ``I'm not aware of a state general obligation rating that has
dropped so quickly,'' Robert Swerdling, assistant vice president of
municipal finance at Standard &amp; Poor's, said Thursday. ``What we're
looking at is a situation that has gone on too long.''
   Economists note that the state government reaped benefits from
the boom years of the mid-1980s while failing to prepare for
cyclical changes. Some also say the presidential campaign of Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis diverted attention from the impending trouble.
   ``It's clear that the signs of the budget problem emerged early
in 1988 and could have been addressed sooner,'' said Sara Johnson,
managing economist at DRI-McGraw Hill in Lexington.
   The deficit has its roots in the state's economic downturn, as a
depressed real estate market and a slump in high-tech manufacturing
have led to lower state revenues. But economists say government
officials should have foreseen the trouble and should have saved
money to avoid a fiscal crisis.
   ``The deficit and the bond rating suggest a lack of foresight in
the good years,'' Johnson said.
   When the Massachusetts economy was booming in the middle 1980s,
Johnson said, state officials sharply increased government
spending, ``rather than use the revenues to build up a surplus to
protect the state in a downturn.''
   ``This has been building for a couple of years. It might have
been submerged because of the presidential campaign,'' said Peter
Kozel, chief economist at Shawmut Bank in Boston. ``It's just that
the issue wasn't discussed very much.''
   George Leung, vice president for state ratings at Moody's, said
he has not previously witnessed such a lack of resolve in the
Massachusetts government.
   ``I think it's been the lack of any real consensus in the
government to address the problems, both in the executive branch
and in the legislative branch,'' he said.
   Leung said while Massachusetts and Louisiana sit at the bottom
of the rankings, the two states have different situations. ``In
Louisiana, it's more fundamental economic issues,'' he said.
``Here, it's much different.''
   In Massachusetts, ``the growth in the deficit is related to a
weakening economy, but more importantly the lack of timely action
to deal with it led us to lower the rating,'' he said.
   Other states have had fiscal troubles, but they have done a
better job keeping their books balanced and maintaining their bond
ratings.
   ``There are many states with weaker economies than Massachusetts
that have higher bond ratings,'' Swerdling said.
   Bond rating officials said, however, that eliminating the debt
will not simply return Massachusetts to its lofty level. Forecasts
call for continued softness in the state economy, and this could
lead to more fiscal strains in the future, Leung said.
   Also, the lower bond ratings mean higher borrowing costs for the
state, ``which makes a bad situation worse,'' Ayers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
