<FIRST>u a AM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0668 12-14 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With 27 Deaths in Bus Accident Apologizes on Stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more testimony from Mahoney. Edits to
tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man charged with 27 counts of murder
in the nation's worst drunken-driving accident took the stand
Thursday and apologized to family members of some of the dead.
   ``I really am sorry and I mean this,'' Larry Mahoney said in a
tight voice at the conclusion of one hour and 10 minutes of
testimony. Both members of the victims' families and Mahoney's
family broke into tears.
   ``I would probably feel the same way that you feel about this,''
the 36-year-old factory worker said. ``I wanted to let you know I
really am sorry. I mean it. ... I know it's not going to make you
feel any different toward me.''
   Behind Mahoney on the witness stand was a large seating chart of
the church bus, with color photographs and names of the 67
passengers. The names of the 24 children and three adults killed in
the fiery crash were designated with a black letter ``D.''
   Mahoney faces multiple life sentences if convicted of the
charges: 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of wanton endangerment, 12
counts of assault and a count of drunken driving.
   Mahoney said he had no recollection of leaving a small drinking
party and colliding with a crowded church bus on Interstate 71 on
May 14, 1988. Mahoney, who was testifying for the first time in the
trial, also said he had no intention of getting drunk that day.
   ``It's a fact I was involved in an accident, but I don't
remember seeing the bus,'' Mahoney said. ``I remember waking up in
the hospital. ''
   Mahoney said he ``hates'' hard alcohol because it irritates his
ulcer. At the party, he remembered asking for a beer. None was
available, a man he had just met offered him a mixed drink. A clear
liquid Mahoney couldn't identify was poured into a glass.
   ``I took a big drink of it and I coughed and choked on it,'' he
said. Some of the men laughed at him, he recalled.
   Asked if he drank any more of the clear liquid, Mahoney said,
``There's no way I could drink two glasses of something like that.''
   He then recalled drinking what he believed to be Pepsi from a
glass to get the taste of the alcohol out of his mouth.
   In previous testimony, witnesses had said the soda was mixed
with vodka, but Mahoney said he couldn't taste anything in the
drink. He said he never remembered getting the keys to his truck
and driving away.
   The prosecution contends an intoxicated Mahoney, driving the
wrong way on the interstate, crashed into the bus. The defense
contends that the design of the bus, built before federal safety
standards were tightened, contributed to the deaths, which
examiners said resulted from the fire, not the original crash.
   In earlier testimony, the defense's accident reconstruction
expert, Wilbur R. Meredith III, was cross-examined about his
conclusion that Mahoney's truck first hit a Cadillac beside the bus
and then struck the bus.
   A previous reconstruction by Kentucky State Police, relying on
eyewitness accounts, investigation of accident scene evidence and
other information, found that Mahoney's truck first hit the bus and
then collided with the Cadillac.
   Mahoney's attorney, William Summers, said the defense's
reconstruction provides the jury with a more complete picture of
what authorities say is the nation's worst drunken-driving accident.
   ``I'm a lawyer, not Houdini. I'm not going to try to put him on
the other side of the road,'' Summers said. ``And I'm damned sure
I'm not going to be able to sober him up.''
   During cross-examination by Assistant Attorney General Paul
Richwalsky Jr., Meredith said his reconstruction does not
contradict eyewitness accounts of Mahoney's truck colliding first
with the bus. Meredith said the eyewitnesses couldn't see the
collision with a Cadillac from their viewing angle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
