<FIRST>u i AM-Vietnam-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0620 12-14 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boat People Attacked Government Officer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with attack on government officer, details,
minor editing to trim and conform. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KHARK SINGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 Vietnamese boat people attacked a
guard with iron bars after two days of peaceful demonstrations
against the new policy of forced repatriation, officials said
Friday.
   About 8,000 refugees demonstrated without incident Thursday
against forced return to their Communist homeland and protests
spread to more detention camps before the violent incident, the
officials reported.
   An officer of the Correctional Services Department was attacked
late Thursday when he saw about 100 refugees in the Chimawan
detention center trying to tear something down, the Government
Information Service reported. Whether it was an escape attempt was
not clear.
   After the attack, the refugees ran back to their barracks and
the officer was treated for minor injuries, according to the
report. It said an investigation revealed that some window bars and
iron bars for hanging clothes were missing.
   Protests Wednesday and Thursday were prompted by the
repatriation of 51 Vietnamese against their will Tuesday. They were
pulled screaming and crying from their detention center and put on
a plane to Hanoi.
   About 56,000 Vietnamese refugees are housed in squalid camps in
Hong Kong.
   Under the new program, those who arrived before June 1988 remain
eligible for resettlement overseas, but the approximately 44,000
who arrived later are to be sent back if they are classified as
illegal immigrants.
   About 6,800 already have been given that designation, compared
with slightly more than 700 accorded refugee status.
   The government said Thursday a Vietnamese man was found hanging
inside one of the camps. In a hospital, his condition was described
as fair.
   There have been fears that forced repatriation would cause
suicide attempts. The Information Service report said the man was
under investigation in connection with a robbery and his attempt to
kill himself was not believed linked to repatriation.
   More than 2,000 Vietnamese men, women and children _ many
wearing white headbands symbolizing protest _ marched through the
Sham Shui Po detention center in urban Kowloon under banners that
read ``Forced repatriation is homicide'' and ``Save our souls.''
   They thrust their fists into the air as they marched around the
camp's playground. A few plainclothesmen kept watch.
   At one point, protesters gathered in front of a makeshift altar
that had eggs piled on it and a sign that said: ``Requiem ceremony
for 51 souls.'' An official said the eggs were a religious offering
for the repatriated Vietnamese.
   About 4,000 Vietnamese protested at two separate centers on Hei
Ling Chau Island, a former leper colony, and 2,000 more
demonstrated at Whitehead detention center in the New Territories,
said Francis Ma, spokesman for the Correctional Services Department
which runs the camps.
   On Wednesday, about 6,000 Vietnamese protested at three centers,
with some shouting they would rather die than return to Vietnam.
   British and Hong Kong officials say involuntarily repatriation
will continue despite international criticism. They say returning
the Vietnamese is more humane than keeping them indefintely in
crowded camps where violence is rife.
   The United States has criticized the repatriation policy,
provoking anger in Britain.
   Foreign Office Minister Francis Maude described as ``misguided''
a State Department statement Tuesday that the repatriations were
unacceptable.
</TEXT>
