<HEAD>Zhivkov Ignored Burning Plane Wreck to Take Off, Paper Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper published
an account Thursday of how Todor Zhivkov, the undisputed leader for
35 years, ignored an airplane disaster that occurred as his craft
was preparing for takeoff.
   Rumors had circulated here that the Jan. 2, 1988, crash took
place as the Zhivkov plane was about to leave Sofia for the port of
Varna. Only in the last few weeks, however, have details begun to
emerge in the news media of bad deeds by the toppled Zhivkov.
Zhivkov was forced out of office Nov. 10.
   A Jak-42 plane rolled off a runway into a field and burst into
flames, killing 27 people. Many children were said to have been
among the victims.
   The daily Rabotnichesko Delo said ``the fact was concealed''
from the start that Zhivkov was preparing to take off, according to
the state BTA news agency.
   Maj. Petar Zinoviev, the military chief of the flight center,
was quoted as saying in a first-hand account that Zhivkov was
informed of the accident before takeoff, but left as planned,
flying only 650 feet over the burning wreck.
   The Jak crashed at 5:32 p.m. and Zhivkov's plane took off at
6:22 p.m., the paper said.
