<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-US     12-14 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama's Lawmakers Consider New Power for Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president Thursday told lawmakers
convened to consider naming Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega chief of
government that the United States had ``declared war on all
Panamanians.''
   Provisional President Francisco Rodriguez spoke at the
inauguration of the new People's Assembly, a legislature that
Noriega has been named to coordinate.
   The assembly, whose membership is entirely pro-Noriega, was
formed from 510 mayors and county chairmen nationwide to replace
the legitimate National Assembly, whose mandate expired Sept. 1.
   Among the issues of the two-day meeting is naming Noriega as
Panama's chief of government with powers greater than those of
Rodriguez.
   Noriega, wanted in the United States on federal drug trafficking
and money laundering charges, is already the Defense Forces chief
and the nation's de facto ruler.
   The general annulled May 7 national elections when returns
showed the opposition was winning by a landslide, blocking
selection of a new National Assembly and president.
   Afterward, Noriega named Rodriguez, a 51-year-old economist and
Noriega associate, as provisional president.
   If the People's Assembly approves new powers for Noriega,
Rodriguez's post would largely be reduced to a ceremonial one.
   However, military and other sources speaking on condition of
anonymity said they were advising Noriega against accepting such an
appointment for public relations reasons.
   Since the U.S. indictments, Washington has been exerting
diplomatic and economic pressure, including trade and other
sanctions, to force Noriga out of power.
   But so far, the strongman has remained in place, weathering coup
attempt by senior officers in March 1988 and October 1989.
   Talking to journalists before delivering his speech to
lawmakers, Rodriguez praised Noriega as a man who ``had all the
qualities for becoming chief of government.''
   ``It is evident now that the true intention of the U.S. in its
campaigning in favor of a supposed democracy ... is a war against
all Panamanians, against the government and against the opposition,
and against those who are not aligned with a political group,''
Rodriguez said in his speech.
   ``The United States does not care even about the political
groups that have repesented its political and economic interests
here. It is not Noriega they want to do away with, but our national
ability to be independent,'' he said.
   In another development Thursday, the Foreign Ministry said it
agreed to a request by European Economic Community ambassadors for
the release of a group of civilian political prisoners.
   Acting Foreign Minister Abelardo Carles said the Panamanian
government will have a ``a positive answer.''
   French ambassador Jacques Rummelhardt said the request was made
``in the spirit of the Christmas season.''
   The government did not say how many or who would be freed.
</TEXT>
