<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Christmas     12-14 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Christmas,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Cancels Christmas Celebrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Municipal officials in the biblical town of
Bethlehem announced Thursday they had canceled community Christmas
celebrations for the third year in a row to support the Palestinian
uprising.
   The town in the occupied West Bank is revered as the birthplace
of Christ.
   Municipal officials in Beit Sahour, to the east, also said they
would call off their Christmas celebrations to back the uprising.
   Beit Sahour is surrounded by fields where Christians believe the
birth of Christ was announced to shepherds.
   It will be the third consecutive Christmas that the towns, both
homes to Christian Arabs, will forgo putting up decorations,
lighting municipal trees or holding receptions.
   However, several holiday events sponsored by the Israeli
military government or by Christian groups will go ahead in both
communities, Israeli officials said. Included is a
government-sponsored choir program near the Church of the Nativity
in Bethlehem.
   Municipal officials cited both the uprising and six weeks of tax
raids carried out by soldiers and Israeli revenue agents in Beit
Sahour as reasons for canceling Christmas celebrations.
   ``How can we celebrate when our people are suffering?'' said
Bethlehem Municipal Secretary Jamal Salman. ``We must respect the
martyrs, the people in prison and to protest against unfair
taxation and what is happening in Beit Sahour.''
   Salman said there will be no decorations or receptions in
Bethlehem, but he said traditional religious ceremonies will be
held in the town of 35,000 Palestinians, who include 10,000
Christians.
   Six people from Bethlehem and Beit Sahour were among the 631
Palestinians killed by Israelis in the 2-year-old uprising. At
least 155 other Palestinians have been slain by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators with Israel. Forty-three Israelis have died
in the violence.
   The uprising leaders are demanding an end to Israeli rule in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In Beit Sahour, a Christian Arab town of about 10,000, the tax
raids carried out in September and October were aimed at ending a
tax boycott called by the underground leaders of the uprising.
</TEXT>
