<FIRST>r a AM-American-CBS     12-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American-CBS,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airline In-Flight News to Lack Air Crash Video</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because CBS refused to cut stories about air
crashes and other airline problems from the daily in-flight news
shows it provides American Airlines, it is losing American's
business on Feb. 28, a CBS official says.
   So in March, taped CNN newscasts _ without pictures of airline
crash stories _ will continue on the airline, thanks to an unusual
contract Turner Home Entertainment says it expects to sign next
week with American.
   American's rationale may be to avoid alarming passengers, but
``it's like passing out newspapers with holes cut in them,'' says
David Berman, a vice-president of CBS Broadcast International.
   ``The agreement is limited to (stories about) air crashes,''
says Steve Chamberlain, vice-president of Turner Home
Entertainment, which merchandises programs of Cable News Network,
part of Ted Turner's cable empire.
   ``There will not be any other wholesale editing of our
product,'' he adds. ``Above all, we have to preserve the
journalistic integrity of our network.''
   Although he said air crash stories would be edited from CNN's
in-flight news packages for American, Mary O'Neill, a spokeswoman
for the airline, said Thursday that this doesn't mean a complete
blackout of such stories.
   ``What the contract with CNN calls for is that CNN will not show
the video,'' she said by phone from American headquarters in
Dallas. ``They will talk, in the audio portion, about these kinds
of incidents. But they will not show the video.''
   She called this an arrangement worked out after American's
surveys showed that its passengers complained that pictures of
airline crash scenes deeply disturbed them.
   She also said that American's decision to drop CBS was financial
and wasn't based on an editorial dispute. ``We didn't feel we were
earning enough profit from our agreement with CBS,'' she said.
   Acording to a source who asked not to be identified, CBS had
netted about $200,000 annually from its in-flight newscasts on
American.
   CBS for the past six years has provided American with daily
tapes of the ``CBS Morning News'' for daytime flights, said Berman,
whose division merchandises CBS News programs.
   Under American's guidelines, he said, CBS has pulled from
flights _ sometimes after consultation with American officials _
programs with reports of airline crashes or ``virtually anything
detrimental to the airlines.''
   CBS finally was told its contract wouldn't be renewed after it
balked at American's request to simply delete adverse airline news
``and deliver the remainder of the show,'' he said. ``We said no,
absolutely not.''
   Chamberlain characterized as a compromise the CNN agreement with
American, the nation's largest air carrier.
   There is no similar agreement, he said, with 11 other airlines,
including Delta and Quantas, that show CNN newscasts during their
flights.
   CBS serves Trans World Airlines, Continental Airlines and Japan
Air Lines with weekly summaries of the ``CBS Evening News,'' Berman
said, and none ever has asked CBS to edit out reports of airline
crashes.
   ``We deliver that show to them and they're responsible for
duplicating it and putting it on the airplanes,'' he says. It's up
to them, he adds, to decide whether to show any programs containing
airline crash reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
