<FIRST>u i AM-France-Comoros     12-14 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Comoros,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Said Ready to Land in Comoros</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France has struck an agreement with European
mercenaries controlling the Comoros Islands for the soldiers of
fortune to leave and be replaced with French troops, the French
news agency reported Thursday.
   The French government had no comment on the reports.
   A South African diplomat said earlier Thursday the mercenaries
planned to leave but their commander was still negotiating terms
for his departure.
   The French and Belgian mercenaries, led by Frenchman Bob Denard,
took over the island nation off southeastern Africa after the Nov.
26 assassination of President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane. Denard
was widely believed to have killed the president but says he was
accidentally shot by his own bodyguard.
   Agence France-Presse quoted unidentified sources in the Comoros
as saying six French and Belgian mercenaries left Thursday night on
an Air France flight for Paris. Accompanying them were some wives
and children, the agency said.
   The 24 remaining mercenaries, including Denard, were to leave
Friday on a South African military transport plane for an unknown
destination, AFP said.
   The mercenaries controlled the islands through command of the
600-member presidential guard. However, some opponents took to the
streets to protest in Moroni, the capital.
   Denard said Thursday he wanted a formal transfer of power to the
French army before leaving, according to the Star newspaper of
Johannesburg.
   The South African paper said Denard demanded assurance there
would be no prosecution for the guards' activities; six months'
salary and an undisclosed additional payment, and press attendance
at a formal transfer of power.
   Denard said he was prepared to return to France, where he faces
arrest in a suit brought by relatives of mercenaries killed in an
unsuccessful coup Denard led in the West African country of Benin
in 1977.
   The French and South Africans, the Comoros' two largest aid
donors, have been negotiating for departure of the mercenaries.
   Four French naval vessels with 90 commandos are stationed just
outside Comoros territorial waters.
   On the French island of Mayotte about 170 miles to the
southwest, 300 marine parachute troops and seven military transport
planes await orders.
   Officially, the French military force is there to evacuate 1,600
French citizens who live on the islands. President Francois
Mitterrand says France has no intention of a military intervention.
   The Comoros gained independence from France in 1975.
   Denard helped engineer a 1975 coup that ousted Abdallah, then
led a 1978 coup that restored him to power. Denard and the
mercenaries have remained a leading force on the islands ever since.
</TEXT>
