<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Christmas 3rdLd-Writethru   12-14 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Christmas, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0715-a0710,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lights Tree, Declares That The `Bells of Freedom' Are Ringing</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 12th graf: ``The White,'' with 12,000 crowd estimate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, lighting the National
Christmas Tree, said Thursday night the ``bells of freedom''
ringing across Eastern Europe have made this ``the Christmas that
we've awaited for 50 years.''
   Bush lifted his 3-year-old granddaughter Marshall Bush and held
her finger to the switch to illuminate the 35-foot blue spruce on
the frigid Ellipse behind the White House, decorated to represent
his theme of volunteerism, the ``thousand points of light.''
   At this Christmas season, Bush said:
   ``We've worked hard this year, all of us, all of you, to help
build a better America, to help make this a kinder and gentler
nation.''
   But, he added, ``there remains a world at need all around us.''
   ``From now on in America, `there's no room at the inn,' that's
simply not an acceptable answer,'' said the president. ``From now
on in America, any definition of a successful life must include
serving others.''
   ``This is the Christmas that we've awaited for 50 years. And
across Europe, east and west, 1989 is ending bright with the
prospect of a far better Christmastime than Europe has ever known;
a far better future the world dared to imagine,'' said Bush.
   ``Fifty winters have come and gone since darkness closed over
Europe in 1939,'' said Bush, but now the wall in Berlin has come
``tumbling down,'' and ``spring returned to Prague.''
   ``The glad sound you hear is not only the bells of Christmas,
but also the bells of freedom,'' Bush told the crowd from behind a
bullet-proof enclosure.
   In lighting the National Christmas Tree, Bush was continuing a
presidential tradition begun by Calvin Coolidge in 1923.
   Unlike his predecessor, Ronald Reagan, who used to throw the
switch from the White House, Bush and his wife, Barbara, attended
the ceremonies lighting the 35-foot tall Colorado blue spruce tree.
   The White House said later 12,000 people gathered in the
near-freezing temperatures to watch the ceremony.
   Bush took part in the tree lighting a few hours after he went on
a quick shopping trip.
   To the delight of holiday shoppers, Bush made a surprise visit
to a Sears, Roebuck store in Washington to buy gifts for his
grandchildren. Working with a gift list, he spent 30 minutes in the
store's children's clothing section, paying in cash.
   The National Christmas Tree is a living tree transplanted to its
permanent spot on the Ellipse in 1978. This year, it is hung with a
thousand white stars for Bush's ``thousand points of light.''
   The tree is also decorated with 4,000 red and blue lights that
fade out to show the white stars.
   The tree is surrounded by 57 smaller trees representing each
state and territory. They are the center of the Christmas Pageant
of Peace put on annually by a non-profit sponsor in cooperation
with the National Park Service.
   ``Today'' show weatherman Willard Scott, dressed as Santa,
presided over the ceremonies, and entertainers Loretta Lynn,
Marilyn McCoo, Billy Davis Jr. and Tommy Tune sang carols _
frequently into a dead microphone on a star-crossed sound system.
   The mike under Scott's Santa beard was the only one that worked
reliably, and Bush, before he headed back to the White House with
his wife Barbara, daughter-in-law Margaret Bush and granddaughter
Marshall, Bush leaned over to intone into Scott's beard, ``Santa,
you did a fine job.''
</TEXT>
