<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Cyprus 1stLd-Writethru a0735 12-14 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cyprus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Extends Cypriot Peacekeeping Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with details, background. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 15-nation Security Council voted
unanimously Thursday to extend the mandate of the U.N. Peacekeeping
Force in Cyprus for six more months, as it has done twice a year
since dispatching the force in 1964.
   Peace talks between the Greek and Turkish sectors of the
Mediterranean island are stalemated. U.N. peacekeepers separate the
feuding communities.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's latest report on
Cyprus said no progress on reuniting the island was made in the
last year.
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus and Rauf Denktash, leader
of the breakaway Turkish sector in northern Cyprus, met separately
with Perez de Cuellar for talks this month but gave no sign of
budging.
   Denktash insists Cyprus must renounce any claim to governing the
Turkish Cypriots and recognize his government as legitimate.
Vassiliou reiterates his government's claim to authority over the
whole island.
   Turkey is the only country that recognizes Denktash's Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus.
   Vassiliou says Greek Cypriots must have the right to travel,
live and own property anywhere on the island. Denktash says the
minority Turkish community would lose its identity if it does not
have a protected enclave.
   ``For the Turkish Cypriots, the border stands for liberation and
security,'' the Turkish Cypriot envoy, Ozer Koray, told the council.
   Koray complained that the Vassiliou administration spent
``enormous sums'' to buy weapons and no mention was made of this in
Perez de Cuellar's report.
   Cyprus has been divided since the Turkish army invaded in 1974
following a short-lived, Greek-backed coup by supporters of union
with Greece.
   The Turks seized the northern one-third of the island. The
Turkish Cypriot minority proclaimed a breakaway republic there in
1983.
</TEXT>
