<HEAD>McMartin Jury Returns 24 Additional Verdicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors returned 24 additional sealed verdicts
in the McMartin preschool molestation trial Thursday, bringing the
total of counts they have decided to 26 out of 65 charges.
   The jurors, who are scheduled to take a two-week vacation after
Friday's session, submitted 18 sealed envelopes to the court clerk
shortly after they began their day's deliberations.
   About an hour later, they sent out six more verdicts sealed in
envelopes, the court clerk said.
   The jury returned the first two verdicts on Nov. 28 and Dec. 5.
   The panel has been talking for a month and a half, debating
allegations that Raymond Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin
Buckey, 63, molested children at their family-owned nursery school
in Manhattan Beach. The Buckeys have steadfastly maintained their
innocence through five years of court proceedings including a
2{-year trial.
   Their case has become the longest and most costly criminal trial
in U.S. history.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders earlier yielded to juror
requests that he not announce any of their verdicts before they
leave for their Christmas vacation.
   They were worried that those who might disagree with their
initial decisions would pressure them regarding their remaining
verdicts during their vacation.
