<FIRST>r i AM-India-Violence     12-14 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Violence,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Boys Killed, 50 Injured in Kashmir Police Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers were killed Thursday when
security forces fired on rampaging Moslems separatists who were
celebrating the release of five jailed militants in a ransom deal,
police said.
   Shoaib Ali, deputy police inspector general of Jammu-Kashmir
state, said police fired in Sopore town when Moslems mobs attacked
a police station and freed some prisoners, and a 16-year-old boy,
Parvez Ahmed, was wounded fatally. Ali, contacted by telephone in
Srinagar, said hours later trouble spread to neighboring
Baramullah. Mobs attacked an army motor convoy and Mohammad Yusuf,
18, was killed when soldiers fired on the crowd in self-defense, he
said.
   At least 50 people, including eight police officers, were
injured in the two towns, Ali reported. He said curfews were
imposed and army patrols were on the streets in both towns to keep
order.
   Ali said the police fired in Sopore after baton charges and
teargas failed. Baramullah and Sopore are about 25 miles northwest
of Srinagar, where five Moslem militants of the separatist Kashmir
Liberation Front were released on Wednesday. The five were arrested
the past year for suspected subversion and secessionist activities,
but had not as yet been charged.
   In exchange, the front freed its hostage, Rubaiya Sayeed, a
medical intern and the youngest daughter of Home Minister Mufti
Mohammad Sayeed, a Kashmiri.
   Ms. Sayeed, 22, was kidnapped last Friday at gunpoint as she was
returning home from work at a Sringar hospital. Her abductors twice
threatened to kill her if their demands were not met.
   Sayeed is the first Moslem named as home minister, a post that
oversees police and internal security. The Dec. 5 appointment was
seen as part of new Prime Minister V.P. Singh's efforts to appease
India's Moslem minority, which bore the brunt of Hindu-Moslem riots
this fall that killed 300 people.
</TEXT>
