<FIRST>u a AM-Casolo 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 12-14 1113</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Casolo, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,1143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed From Salvadoran Prison, Casolo Arrives In New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `She was ..., to CORRECT prison name to Ilopango,
sted Ilo Pongo; SUBS final seven grafs, 21-28, `Sen. Christopher ..., to
recast, UPDATE with hometown welcome, quotes, details; no pickup. ^LaserPhoto
NY69</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut woman imprisoned on terrorism
charges in El Salvador for 18 days denied Thursday that she hid
munitions in her yard, and said her ordeal has not diminished her
love for the Salvadoran people.
   ``I wish you all could know the Salvadoran people,'' Jennifer J.
Casolo, 28, said at a news conference at LaGuardia Airport, where
she arrived around 5 p.m. after a night in Miami.
   ``They are a people of so much faith and love and what they have
been through makes what I have been through seem this big,'' she
said, making a small fist.
   ``They deserve a country where they can eat, where their
children can go to school, where they don't have to worry about
being dragged away in the middle of the night,'' Casolo said.
   A church worker who moved to El Salvador in 1985, Casolo was
arrested Nov. 25 after authorities stormed her rented house in San
Salvador and unearthed dynamite, grenades and more than 20,000
rounds of ammunition from the back yard.
   A Salvadoran military judge dropped terrorism charges against
Casolo for lack of evidence, but Salvadoran President Alfredo
Cristiani said he remained convinced of her guilt. Salvadoran
officials said a rebel had told them where the arms were buried.
   Casolo maintains she was framed.
   ``Maybe those weapons were there. Maybe a Salvadoran guerrilla
tipped them off ... but there's just as much possibility that they
beat the hell out of someone to get them to say it _ and excuse my
language,'' Casolo said.
   She said that during her imprisonment she underwent several
interrogations, including one in which she was blindfolded and
forced to stand for a long period.
   She said that at night she couldn't sleep because of the sounds
of others being beaten.
   She said her female interrogator told her: ``Here you have no
rights.''
   ``Then she tells me she has permission to do with me what she
wants and she doesn't want to be dishonest _ (that) she has treated
people badly before,'' Casolo recalled.
   She was held in Ilopango for eight days of her 18-day detention.
She said the prison was surrounded by military headquarters and she
was afraid of being taken out by the soldiers.
   She said that when soldiers stormed her house, she shouted,
``Who could hate me this much?''
   She added, ``Maybe it's because if you could discredit me, you
could discredit the work of the church. ... I wanted to stay there
and be part of the construction of peace. The deportation broke my
heart because it means I can't go back.''
   She blasted Bush administration officials who earlier had
indicated they believed she might be guilty. She said she told the
Salvadorans she was ``innocent until proven guilty, but I didn't
know my own government representatives don't care about that same
right.''
   Casolo urged an end to U.S. military aid to El Salvador and
expressed concern for what she said are more than 1,000 political
prisoners still held in El Salvador.
   On Thursday, Salvadoran police raided the home of the lawyer who
had defended her, Salvador Ibarra, and arrested his sister, Vilma,
and two others. In New York, Casolo asked that the same sort of
support shown for her be shown for Ms. Ibarra.
   Casolo, who is fluent in Spanish, worked for Christian Education
Seminars, a San Antonio-based ecumenical group that organizes
visits to El Salvador for Americans, including members of Congress.
   The Rev. Dan Long of Christian Education Seminars, accompanied
Casolo on the flights from San Salvador to New York.
   Greeting Casolo at the airport were five classmates from her
alma mater, Brandeis University, class of 1983. Also on hand were
two Baptist ministers and one Methodist minister.
   At her hometown of Thomaston, Conn., where her parents awaited
her return. Her mother, Audrey, called her release an early
Christmas present. ``Today is like the day before the wedding,''
said Mrs. Casolo said. ``You're happy and hoping for everything.''
   Church activists often have been harassed by the Salvadoran
government, which accuses them of aiding left-wing guerillas in the
country's decade-long civil war. Government troops are widely
blamed for the slaughter of six Jesuit priests last month, when
guerrillas began a major new offensive against the government.
   She said the soldiers who stormed her house did not let her see
what they were doing in the backyard.
   Asked how the weapons came to be in her yard, she said, ``I
don't know if it was there, if they put it there or if someone else
put it there and I don't think I'll ever know.''
   Casolo flew from San Salvador to Miami Wednesday night and then
from Miami to New York City on Thursday.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who had lobbied for Casolo's
release, sent a car to LaGuardia and accompanied her back to her
hometown of Thomaston, where about 500 people braved freezing
weather to give her a warm homecoming.
   ``Thanks for coming out,'' she told the crowd, her voice choked
with emotion. ``The New York press did not overwhelm me, but you
guys are overwhelming me.''
   Her father also tearfully thanked the townspeople for their
prayers and letters. ``You've really made this the merriest
Christmas we've ever had. I hope you will have the same,'' John
Casolo said, overcome with emotion.
   Ms. Casolo planned a private reunion with her mother, Audrey
Casolo, after the official greeting on the Town Green.
   ``It was something that was something that was just kind of
personal to her,'' said Susan Abbott, one of Jennifer's closest
friends. ``She didn't want it to be all over the TVs and newspapers
when she woke up in the morning.''
   A plywood sign erected on the green read ``Welcome Home
Jennifer. We Love You,'' and at the entrance to her mother's house,
two ``Welcome Home'' banners flew, one in English and the other in
Spanish.
   A large purple bow, bearing Jennifer's name in gold letters,
hung on the front door of the Thomaston Congregational Church,
where hundreds of town residents gathered Dec. 1 to pray for her
release.
   ``Our prayers here in Thomaston have been answered,'' said First
Selectman Eugene McMahon. ``This crisis has served to unite all the
people of this community in a common purpose. Indeed, we all can
enjoy a merry Christmas and a happy New Year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
