<DOCNO> AP891214-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 2227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Uprising     12-14 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Uprising,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Collaborator Axed to Death in Occupied West Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Palestinians shot and axed to death a
suspected collaborator Thursday in the crowded Casbah, or old
market, in the West Bank city of Nablus, Arab reporters said.
   An army official confirmed the death and said it was being
investigated by police.
   The slaying was the first of an alleged collaborator in Nablus
since Dec. 1 when army troops shot and killed four members of a
radical group called the Black Panthers, which had been blamed for
killing 16 people on suspicion they cooperated with Israel.
   Following those deaths, the army announced through loudspeakers
that citizens no longer need fear attacks from the Black Panthers.
However, masked youths have appeared on the streets since, chanting
that the group's members would still punish collaborators.
   Thursday's death raised to 156 the number of Palestinians slain
by fellow Arabs as alleged collaborators during the two-year-old
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   At least 631 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis during
the revolt, and 43 Israelis also have died.
   In Nablus, Palestinian witnesses said several masked
Palestinians led the victim, with his hands tied behind his back,
through the narrow streets of the Casbah.
   One of the masked men struck the victim in the head with an ax
and another fired six or seven shots into his head, chest and
stomach, the witnesses told reporters.
   The victim was identified only as a 30-year-old man believed to
be from the nearby town of Tulkarem. Arab reporters said he was
kidnapped Wednesday along with two other men who are still missing.
   In the Gaza Strip, meanwhile, seven Palestinians were shot and
wounded in clashes between soldiers and stone-throwing youths in
the Bureij and Shati refugee camps and the town of Rafah, Arab
reporters said.
   In the Golan Heights, police fired tear gas to break up several
small pro-Syrian demonstrations on the eighth anniversary of
Israel's annexation of the heights following the area's capture
from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Schools and some businesses were closed by a general strike
ordered by activists of the Druse sect, an offshoot of Islam. A
Syrian flag was seen flying in Majdal Shams, the area's largest
town, and Druse on the Syrian side of the border held up signs
supporting the Palestinian uprising.
   Police said 11 Druse were arrested in Majdal Shams during the
protests.
</TEXT>
