<FIRST>r a AM-MickensSentenced     12-14 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mickens Sentenced,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flamboyant Drug Dealer Gets 35 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old man who federal prosecutors say
made millions in the drug trade and spent it lavishly on cars, a
yacht and real estate was sentenced Thursday to 35 years in prison.
   Thomas Mickens, who liked to call himself Tony Montana after the
mobster in the movie ``Scarface,'' was convicted in federal court
June 28 of conspiracy to distribute narcotics, money laundering and
tax evasion.
   At the time of his conviction, U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney
called him one of the largest drug distributors in Queens,
personally netting $2.5 million from January 1984 through May 1988.
   Sentence was handed down by U.S. District Judge Thomas C. Platt.
   Among his assets seized by the authorities were a customized
Rolls-Royce worth $100,000, a 38-foot yacht worth $48,000 and a
$750,000 home. He owned 17 cars and 18 pieces of real estate, the
prosecution said.
   In 1987 alone, the prosecution said, he spent more than $1
million on cars and property, not counting living expenses.
   His drug operation was headquarterd in Queens, and he garnered
favor in the neighborhood by sponsoring local basketball teams, the
prosecution said.
