<FIRST>u i AM-Chile 7thLd-Writethru a0732 12-14 1008</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0732,1037</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition's Aylwin Trounces Buchi in Vote for Civilian Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs with 93 percent of returns in, Aylwin victory
speech, street celebrations, details. Picks up 12th pvs, `Voters also ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SCL1,6,7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition candidate Patricio Aylwin
trounced Gen. Augusto Pinochet's former finance minister Thursday
in elections to end the right-wing military president's 16-year
rule.
   Official election results from 93 percent of the country's 7.5
million registered voters showed Aylwin with 3.58 million votes, or
55.2 percent, enough for an absolute majority.
   Interior Ministry returns had Hernan Buchi, the former finance
minister credited with designing a policy of economic growth and
low inflation from 1985 until May, finishing a distant second with
1.9 million votes, or 29.4 percent.
   At midnight, Interior Minister Carlos Caceres formally
recognized Aylwin's victory and pledged the government will abide
by the result.
   Under Chilean law, Aylwin is to take office for four years
beginning March 11.
   Earlier Thursday evening, Buchi conceded defeat, declaring, ``We
have returned to democracy. Mr. Patricio Aylwin has been elected
president of the republic by the people of Chile.''
   Motorists honked their horns in celebration and supporters of
the 71-year-old Aylwin, a moderate Christian Democrat, rushed into
the streets of this capital to hail the victory. Fireworks dotted
the sky and lines of flag-waving citizens crammed the main
thoroughfares early Friday.
   On one large white banner was painted a portrait of ex-President
Salvador Allende, a Marxist whose elected 3-year-old government was
toppled by Pinochet in a 1973 coup. The banner quoted one of the
final statements of Allende, who died during the coup: ``I have
faith in Chile and its future.''
   In a victory speech delivered shortly after midnight (10 p.m.
EST Thursday) from a downtown hotel balcony, Aylwin declared: ``The
people of Chile have taken their future destiny back into their own
hands.''
   He then asked the crowd to return peacefully to their homes and
prepare for an official street celebrations Friday afternoon.
   A long-shot third candidate, populist businessman Francisco
Errazuriz, also conceded defeat, saying, ``Mr. Aylwin has won an
absolute majority.'' Errazuriz had 998,000 votes or 15 percent,
according to the count. There were 114,000 null and blank ballots,
the Ministry said late Thursday.
   In his first public reaction, Pinochet applauded the
peacefulness and normality of the voting, and attributed the margin
of victory to a better organized opposition.
   One serious voting day incident was reported in this nation of
12 million people: police said a gunman fled after killing a
23-year-old officer guarding a polling station in a working-class
district in southern Santiago. No details were given.
   Voters also elected 38 Senators and 120 House of Deputies
members, but results were not immediately available. Scattered
returns reported by local radio and television networks showed the
opposition coalition leading in most of the races.
   The Senate also will include up to 10 members appointed by,
among others, the president, Supreme Court and National Security
Council.
   While a funereal atmosphere was evident at Buchi campaign
headquarters, across town Aylwin campaign official Enrique Krauss
said with a smile, ``The results show the unquestionable victory of
Patricio Aylwin.''
   Aylwin, who represented an alliance of 17 centrist and leftist
parties, had been heavily favored in most pre-election surveys.
   The presidential count included returns from all of Chile's 12
official regions. In only one, the southern 11th region, did Aylwin
win less than in absolute majority _ 46 percent.
   With an absolute majority, Aylwin avoided a two-candidate
runoff, which the constitution required if no nominee won more than
50 percent of the total.
   Buchi, 40, was backed by pro-government parties. Errazuriz, a
47-year-old millionaire, had been expected to run a distant third.
   Pinochet and other top military officials claimed responsibility
Thursday for leading Chile back to democracy. It was a model in
Latin America before 1973, and economically has done well in recent
years exporting wine, copper, fish, fruit and lumber.
   Aylwin, surrounded by bodyguards supplied by the government,
voted early at a school near his home in Santiago, and was cheered
by bystanders as he pushed through a crush of journalists.
   When Buchi voted, he was greeted by Aylwin backers who taunted
him with chants of ``Aylwin, president!'' He did not respond.
   Voting is mandatory in Chile and people failing to vote can be
fined $95. For nearly half of the 7.5 million registered voters,
this was their first real election.
   Some people arrived before dawn at the polling places and waited
in lines that stretched for blocks to receive their three paper
ballots: one each for president, Senate and House of Deputies.
   The peaceful atmosphere mirrored that of October 1988, when
Chileans rejected a referendum proposal that Pinochet lead the
country until 1997, forcing him to schedule elections.
   Hundreds of U.S. and European observers are in the country,
although none have been officially recognized by the government. It
allowed them in as tourists, saying no foreign supervision of the
vote was needed.
   Pinochet complained bitterly Thursday about their presence,
saying they came ``to control the pesos they gave to politicians.''
   Pinochet's right-wing administration frequently has accused the
political opposition of selling out to foreign political parties
and pro-democracy groups that donated money.
   Pinochet, meeting with reporters at the presidential palace,
said he was angered by two things: ``One, because they come to
control the pesos they gave to politicians and political parties.
Second, they come to meddle believing that there will be
irregularities, bad things, and this isn't so.''
   Among the polling stations Thursday was National Stadium in
Santiago, which became a symbol of political repression after the
1973 coup. The military penned up thousands of dissidents in the
stadium and, according to human rights groups, killed or tortured
many.
   Similar roundups occurred elsewhere in Chile.
   Although he must step down as president, Pinochet has said he
will retain command of the 60,000-man army. A provision of the
constitution written by his regime prohibits the new president from
dismissing him until 1998.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
