<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Election     12-14 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0581</SECOND>
<UNK>Personal Attacks Mark Debate, Final Week of Brazilian Presidential
Campaign</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidates Luis
Inacio da Silva and Fernando Collor de Mello traded accusations and
personal barbs Thursday in the final TV debate of a bare-knuckle
campaign before the Dec. 16 election.
   Commentators labeled the 2{-hour encounter a draw in which
neither candidate scored heavily off the other.
   The two men are virtually deadlocked in nationwide polls and the
campaign turned into a series of personal attacks over the final
week.
   Collor de Mello called his socialist rival ``intolerant'' and
``backward.'' He said da Silva's radical Workers Party would stir
national strikes, land invasions and economic chaos if da Silva is
elected.
   Da Silva called Collor de Mello ``emotionally unstable'' and
tried to depict him as a ``member of the dominant, archaic upper
class'' and the new face of the right.
   Analysts say the campaign turned ugly this week as opinion polls
indicated the race was tightening.
   An opinion poll published Thursday had Collor de Mello clinging
to a one percentage point lead over da Silva. Two weeks ago, Collor
de Mello had a 15 point lead.
   Earlier Thursday, Miriam Cordeiro, the mother of da Silva's
illegitimate 15-year-old daughter Lurian, made further intimate
accusations against him in a Collor de Mello TV campaign spot on
national TV.
   She said da Silva wanted to continue their affair after he was
married, but she refused.
   Earlier this week, Ms. Cordeiro called da Silva a racist and
said he offered pay for her to get an abortion.
   Da Silva says he had an affair with Ms. Cordeiro after his first
wife died in 1969.
   Ms. Cordeiro said her testimony was spontaneous and that she
``didn't get a cent'' for the interview. But a former aide of
Collor de Mello said his National Reconstruction Party paid her
$23,000 for her statements.
   The Supreme Electoral Court granted da Silva the right to reply
to the charges Thursday during Collor de Mello's assigned TV time.
   ``I never thought anyone could sink so low _ neither my
adversary, nor this woman,'' da Silva said. ``If I erred, I want
the people to judge me.''
   His camp attributed the attacks to desperation by Collor de
Mello.
   Collor de Mello finished first in the first-round election on
Nov. 15, with 28 percent of the votes, Da Silva was second with 16
percent. Because neither had a majority, the two went to a runoff.
   A new poll released Thursday by the DataFolha institute
indicated Collor de Mello had 46 percent of the vote and da Silva
45 percent, with a margin of error of 2 percent.
   DataFolha interviewed 5,250 people in their homes on Tuesday and
Wednesday. Da Silva, a former lathe operator and union president,
was widely considered a long-shot to reach the presidency.
   Collor de Mello, a former congressman and governor of tiny
Alagoas state, has been the front-runner since April. His promises
to clean up corrupt government and his sharp attacks on President
Jose Sarney were popular with poor Brazilians, who make up most of
the 82 million voters.
   The last free election for president was in 1960, when Janio
Quadros was elected. The armed forces took power in a 1964 coup and
ruled until 1985.
   Sarney, a civilian, was chosen by an Electoral College
controlled by the military regime.
</TEXT>
