<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     12-14 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top U.N. Official Sees Namibia Independent in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibia will probably become independent
in March after 75 years of South African rule, Martti Ahtisaari,
the senior U.N. official supervising the territory's independence
process, said Thursday.
   Ahtisaari, special representative in Namibia for
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, told reporters that
political parties in Namibia are making swift progress in drafting
a constitution for the new nation.
   ``There is the clear desire by all the parties to get this
exercise done early.''
   ``If we are very lucky, they might tie up the constitution
during January'' and then set a date for independence, he added.
   Asked how soon Namibia could gain independence, he replied:
``The general feeling is sometime in March.''
   Ahtisaari has been supervising Namibia's moves toward
independence since April. The U.N. team's mission is due to expire
at the end of March.
   The team includes 4,650 military observers and 1,500 police
supervisors.
   Ahtisaari also was asked when Namibia, also known as South-West
Africa, might join the United Nations as an independent country. He
said he hoped that would happen by September.
   A newly elected Constituent Assembly must adopt the constitution
by a two-thirds majority before setting a target date for
independence.
   Ahtisaari said he saw no stumbling blocks in drafting the
constitution.
   Ahtisaari said the process gained momentum when the leading
party, the South-West Africa People's Organization, declared in
November that it wanted to enshrine freedom of the press and
assembly as well as principles of multiparty democracy in the
constitution.
   SWAPO had conducted a 23-year guerrilla war against South
African authorities in the territory, and some Namibians feared it
would seek a one-party, socialist state.
   Ahtisaari was in New York to consult with senior U.N. officials
while the General Assembly held a Special Session on Apartheid, the
South African system of racial discrimination. He said he expected
to return to Namibia's capital, Windhoek, on Sunday.
   South Africa captured the territory from Germany in World War I.
In 1966, the General Assembly canceled a mandate from the League of
Nations, the U.N. precursor, granting South Africa the right to
administer Namibia.
   Last year, South Africa agreed to cooperate with the U.N. plan
for Namibia's transition to independence when Cuba agreed to
simultaneously withdraw its 50,000 troops from neighboring Angola.
</TEXT>
