<FIRST>u a AM-WashingtonBeltway     12-14 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Beltway,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Traffic Snarled by Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tractor-trailer carrying unknown
hazardous materials overturned Thursday on the interstate highway
circling Washington, forcing the evacuation of about 100 residents
and snarling traffic for hours during and after the evening rush
hour.
   The trailer had picked up more than two dozen chemicals in
Richmond, Va. and was bound for Harrisburg, Pa., when it lost a
tire and collided with a car at about 5 p.m, Montgomery County fire
officials said, quoting the unidentified driver.
   Seven people were injured in the chain reaction of collisions
that followed, and two of the four admitted to Suburban Hospital
were reported in serious condition.
   Traffic remained backed up for several miles at 10:30 p.m.,
officials said. Officials took the evacuated residents to a nearby
high school.
   Firefighters were unsure Thursday night exactly how the
chemicals were contained in the trailer, and had not tried to open
it or remove it from the road where Interstate 270 intersects with
the Capital Beltway, Interstate 495 at that point northwest of
Washington.
   Firefighters said it was important to know how the cargo was
packaged and positioned before they tried to enter the trailer,
which was on its side. They considered the situation so dangerous
that they retreated to more than 1,000 feet from the accident.
   Officials studied a tape made from a helicopter by a news camera
crew from WJLA-TV in an effort to determine whether the chemicals
were leaking and the best way they could be removed.
   The truck is owned by St. Johnsbury Trucking Co. of Holliston,
Mass.
