<FIRST>a w AM-NewspaperGlut Adv18   12-14 1191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper Glut, Adv 18,1221</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Dec. 18, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Recycling Programs Increase; Demand for Used Newspapers Drops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two months residents of the nation's
capital have been sorting newspapers for recycling, but most of the
papers have gone no farther than a 60-foot pit near an incinerator
_ awaiting a buyer who still hasn't come.
   It's another example of the mounting newspaper glut and the
growing awareness that a successful recycling effort means more
than persuading citizens to sort their garbage.
   Stepped-up recycling across the country has made an
unprecedented amount of old newspapers available for reuse, but
markets have been slow in developing. Old newspaper inventories
have mounted and prices for recycled papers have plummeted, with
haulers often charging to take them away.
   In many cities, the local newspaper is being viewed as a villain
for not using more recycled newsprint. ``We get telephone calls and
we get scolded,'' says Dean Myhran, assistant to the business
manager at the Star Tribune in Minneapolis.
   Myhran says the Star Tribune is studying ways to use more
recycled newsprint. All but 5 percent of the paper's newsprint now
comes from virgin wood pulp.
   Nationwide about 14 percent of the 12.3 million tons of
newsprint used last year came from recycled stock, according to the
American Newspaper Publishers Association.
   Yet there is no buyer for an estimated 500,000 tons of collected
newspapers, says Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., who co-sponsored
legislation that would require pulp mills to use a certain
percentage of recycled papers.
   Prices for old newspapers have dropped from more than $30 a ton
to $5 or less if they are in good condition and well sorted.
   ``We can't buy all the newspapers that are available to us,''
says George Elder, purchasing manager at Southeast Recycling Corp.
in Marietta, Ga., which this summer doubled its recycled newsprint
production capacity to 500,000 tons a year.
   Buyers paid up to $30 a ton for recycled newspapers in New York
about a year ago, but the city now pays $15 to $30 a ton as a
``processing'' fee, says Ivan Braun, deputy director for recycling,
   In Youngstown, Ohio, where schools not long ago competed in
paper drives, newspapers now are going to the garbage dump. ``We
were getting $20 a ton, then it dropped to $10 a ton and then to $5
and when it went to zero we stopped collecting,'' says George
Finnerty, the city's litter control coordinator.
   More than 6 million pounds of newspapers have been collected
since Oct. 1 in the District of Columbia. But to date all but 250
tons remain in a 60-foot-deep pit near a municipal incinerator.
Officials say they expect to find a buyer eventually, but will
still have to pay hauling charges.
   Representatives of the recycling and newspaper industries
acknowledge the new push for recycling is likely to change
newsprint production and buying forever.
   The newspaper recycling woes also may foreshadow pitfalls in
other recycling efforts unless markets are developed for the
recycled products.
   Lawmakers in dozens of states as well as in Congress have gotten
into the act. Connecticut newspapers will be required to use
recycled newsprint for at least 20 percent of their needs by 1993
and 90 percent by 1998; a California law calls for newspapers to
meet a 25 percent goal by 1993 and 50 percent by 2000. Florida
implemented a 10 cent-per-ton waste recovery fee on virgin
newsprint and a 10 cent-per-ton tax credit for use of recycled
newsprint.
   In Congress, legislation has been introduced that would require
paper mills, including importers, to produce 10 percent _ and
eventually 30 percent _ of their newsprint from recycled material.
``For every ton of newspapers recycled, three cubic yards of
landfill space is saved,'' says Wirth.
   The move by government to mandate newsprint recycling has not
gone unnoticed among publishers. The 1,385-member American
Newspaper Publishers Association declared in a formal policy
statement last September, ``The government should not intervene in
determinations of newsprint quality.''
   ``Regulating newsprint is regulating newspapers and it is
intolerable in a free society,'' the association said.
   First Amendment questions aside, the publishers also are worried
that government-mandated newsprint content requirements will drive
up costs of newsprint and restrict competition, says Tonda Rush,
the association's director of newspaper plans and projects.
   Environmentalists say government pressure is needed to force
increased production of recycled newsprint when mills, often owned
entirely or in part by newspapers, are expanding production from
virgin pulp. The mills are adding 2.1 million tons of virgin-fiber
capacity over the next two years, according to industry officials.
   ``As long as paper mills and publishers add capacity you're
going to have a glut. I believe that's deliberate and that's why
you need to regulate,'' says Ruth Caplan, executive director of
Environmental Action, a Washington-based environmental group.
   Many major newspaper chains and publishers are rethinking their
buying practices.
   Knight-Ridder Inc. has told its mills that it plans to increase
the share of recycled newsprint at its 29 newspapers from 11
percent to 25 percent by 1992, says Homer Taylor, the company's
vice president for supply.
   Dennis Washburn, director of purchasing at Gannett Co. Inc.,
said the company's future contracts will favor suppliers that are
increasing recycling capacity. Gannett plans to increase its use of
recycled newsprint from 40,000 tons to 100,000 tons next year at
its 83 newspapers.
   Under Environmental Protection Agency guidelines, a sheet of
newsprint is considered recycled if at least 40 percent is from
recycled paper.
   According to the National Solid Wastes Management Association, a
trade group, the amount of recycled newsprint is expected to
quadruple to more than 5.5 million tons annually by 1995. That
translates to a doubling of the 14 percent of newspaper stock that
currently is recycled product.
   The trade group predicts that percentage will exceed 40 percent
by 2000.
   Newspaper executives say most of the past concerns about the
quality of recycled newsprint have been eased with new de-inking
and recycling techniques.
   ``In the state-of-the-art mills there are no problems with
quality. Older mills where they haven't spent money to update
facilities you still have color and brightness problems,'' says
Knight-Ridder's Taylor.
   Publishers point to other problems, however, in increasing use
of recycled newsprint. Among them: a shortage of de-inking plants
and the existing contracts that newspapers signed for virgin
newsprint.
   ``It's going to be two or three years before the various
industries that use old newspapers are going to be able to gear up
and make a significant dent (in the oversupply). It worries me that
communities even knowing there is a glut out there are beginning
recycling programs. They're setting the programs up for failure,''
says Ms. Rush of the publishers' association.
   In the meantime, there is concern that people will become
discouraged with recycling.
   ``There's nothing that angers any of us more than the thought
that we've gone to an extra effort at home and find out that (the
sorted newspapers) end up getting buried or burned,'' says Allen
Moore, president of the National Solid Wastes Management
Association.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Dec. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
