<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Jones Adv20   12-14 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Jones, Adv 20,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Dec. 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bugs Bunny as Counter-Revolutionary, and Other Secrets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORONA DEL MAR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He sits at his drawing board, a
benign, grandfatherly figure whose mild manner belies his history
as creator of some of the wildest, funniest characters in film
history.
   You may not have heard of Chuck Jones, but you're certainly
familiar with the characters he helped bring to life during the
heyday of the Warner Bros. cartoon studio: Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck,
Porky Pig, Wile E. Coyote, Pepe Le Pew, Road Runner, Elmer Fudd,
and more.
   Jones, 77, lives in a spacious, ocean-view house in this Orange
County town, and he still turns out drawings in his sunlit studio.
He also has done a book, aptly titled ``Chuck Amuck'' (Farrar,
Strauss and Giroux, $24.95), which has been critically praised for
its comic brilliance.
   ``Chuck Amuck'' relates the artist's carefree California youth
as a kind of surfing Huck Finn, and his natural drift into
cartooning. For most of the book, he writes about those crazy years
at Warner Bros. when he, Tex Avery and a band of other inspired
animators created cartoons that were far more audacious and funny
than those at the Disney studio.
   Character was everything at Warner Bros., and the wilder the
character the funnier the cartoon. Jones recently talked about the
wellspring of his creations.
   ``All of the characters that I was involved with were characters
I found within myself. They were in two general categories,'' he
said. ``Most of them fell into the classic area of comedy, going
back to (Charlie) Chaplin and (Buster) Keaton and up to Woody Allen
_ when he wasn't being Ingmar Bergman _ and Richard Pryor. All of
them are losers, like the rest of us, only more so. That category
would cover figures like Daffy duck, Elmer Fudd, the Coyote, etc.
   ``Once in a while you run into another kind of character like
Bugs Bunny. He falls into a special category called `comic hero.'
It started with `It Happened One Night,' in which Clark Gable was a
comic hero and a hero at the same time. There was nobody standing
at the side and giving comic relief. Bugs falls into that category.
   ``So when you begin a picture with Bugs, because he is so strong
and can be a bully and a nuisance, you always start him in a hole
or the woods, where you would expect to find a rabbit. He would be
reading a classic tome in Sanskrit or something, a quiet-living
rabbit. Then someone comes along to do him hurt, such as take his
foot off, which is supposed to be good luck, to set him off in a
rocket or to eat him.
   ``Bugs is a natural person leading a normal life until someone
aggravates him, then he fights back. In other words, he's a sort of
counter-revolutionary.''
   Like Bugs, Daffy Duck originated in the inspired drawings of the
late Tex Avery. Jones converted both into long-lasting heroes.
   ``Tex did one of the first Daffys, `Porky's Duck Hunt,' but like
the original Bugs, the character was just nuts,'' said Jones.
``When I got acquainted with Daffy, I realized he was a person who
was very much like me. He was more courageous than I am; he rushes
in and fears to tread at the same time, which I would like to do
but don't have the guts.
   ``Daffy could be fawning and overweening and overbearing at the
same time. He can do strange things, but within all of us dwells a
Daffy Duck. Just as I later did `How the Grinch Stole Christmas'
(for television), I realized that all of us hate Christmas a little
bit. I had the opportunity to direct someone who hated Christmas
completely. That was neat.''
   Road Runner and Wile E. Coyote were born more or less by
accident, the animator recalled. He and his colleagues decided to
make a parody on chases and become the Jonathan Swifts of their
time. They needed two credible antagonists (all comedy is based on
believability), and they came up with a road runner and a coyote.
The pair so overwhelmed audiences that a series was born. So much
for parody.
   ``We arbitrarily set down rules after the first cartoon,'' Jones
recalled. ``It would always take place on the southwestern American
desert, where both characters belong. Road Runner would always stay
on the road, unless he was lured off by a detour sign.''
   Road Runner's trademark came when an artist was carrying a stack
of drawings down the hall. Unable to see ahead, he called
``beep-beep.''
   The glory days of Warner Bros. cartoons ended in 1962, because
the theatrical market for short subjects had disappeared. Since
then Jones has helped produce features (``Gay Purr-ee,'' ``The
Phantom Tollbooth''), shorts (Tom and Jerry), TV series
(``Curiosity Shop'') and specials (``The White Seal,''
``Rikki-Tikki-Tavi''). His art works have drawn big prices, and he
now serves as a consultant to Warner Bros.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wednesday AMs, Dec. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1639EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:LongGrayLine Adv21   12-14 1063</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Long Gray Line, Adv 21,1084</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Dec. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books: `Long Gray Line' Chronicles Odyssey of West Point Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS CAROLA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty graduates of the West Point Class
of 1966 died in the Vietnam War, the most of any class to see
action in Southeast Asia.
   Many are buried beneath two rows of low white stones in Section
34 of the cemetery at the U.S. Military Academy. ``Class of 1966''
is chiseled on each stone, bonding the classmates in death as it
did in life.
   Washington Post reporter Rick Atkinson has written a book about
the Class of '66, tracing its arrival at the Point as fresh-faced
plebes full of Kennedy-inspired idealism to the ideal-shattering
experience of Vietnam, from postwar career changes to a 20-year
reunion of classmates sharing a ``fierce determination to honor the
dead.''
   The young men of the Class of '66 were caught between the
rapidly changing social and moral values of the 1960s and the
staunch traditions of a hallowed military academy.
   ``They are a good way of looking at our collective social
history,'' said Atkinson, whose book, ``The Long Gray Line,'' has
made best-seller lists. ``They straddle a kind of fault line of
American history.''
   The Class of '66 arrived at West Point just a month after
President Kennedy delivered a rousing commencement address to the
Class of '62. The words of Douglas MacArthur's famous ``Duty,
Honor, Country'' speech, delivered a month earlier, still echoed
through West Point's granite halls.
   ``MacArthur told them, `If you fail, the country will be
destroyed,' and they believed that,'' said the author in a
telephone interview during a West Coast promotional tour.
   Atkinson first wrote about the Class of '66 while he was a
reporter for The Kansas City Times. His four-part series, for which
he won a Pulitzer Prize in 1982, grew from a conversation with a
friend who was a '66 West Point graduate.
   ``He was talking how they had gone charging off to war and how
they were going to win the war and come home to ticker-tape
parades,'' Atkinson said. ``They thought they had a kind of social
covenant with the country: They'd go to West Point, serve their
country and in exchange they would be held in high esteem.''
   Instead, '66ers who served in Vietnam came home to derision and
distain. Many were disillusioned about the war and the Army. Some
questioned whether four years at West Point prepared them for what
they faced in Vietnam's jungles and rice paddies.
   ``When you're 22 years old, you presume yourself to be immortal.
These guys were no different,'' Atkinson said. ``Some felt West
Point and their Army training had not prepared them for combat, for
seeing other men die.''
   The deaths of two '66 graduates in particular came to symbolize
the futility and frustrations of fighting in Vietnam. The first
died when he tried to pull a soldier out of some mud and the man's
gun accidentally fired. The second was killed along with 41 other
soldiers when an American jet bombed their hilltop position in the
midst of a fierce battle.
   A hundred '66 graduates were wounded in Southeast Asia. For some
the tragedy continued after the war. Atkinson writes of two
classmates who were murdered, one by his business partner and the
other by North Korean soldiers in a border incident over the
trimming of a poplar tree.
   The author follows the odyssey of the Class of '66 mostly
through the lives of classmates John Wheeler, Tom Carhart and
George Crocker.
   Crocker became a career Army man, leading troops in Vietnam and
Grenada. In between he helped revive a drug-ridden, demoralized
Army in West Germany and served as a West Point instructor when a
cheating scandal and the admission of women sent the academy into
turmoil in 1976. He is now chief of staff of the 82nd Airborne
Division.
   Wheeler and Carhart had both resigned their commissions by 1971,
as had a third of the 579 graduates of the Class of '66.
   Carhart and Wheeler also served in Vietnam, the former in a
combat outfit and the latter in the rear echelon. The two
classmates clashed after the war when Wheeler helped establish the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, and Carhart objected to
the memorial's design, calling it ``a black gash of sorrow and
shame.''
   The 36-year-old Atkinson, the son of a retired career Army
officer, grew up on Army bases, a fact that came in handy while
writing the book.
   ``I feel comfortable around military men,'' he said. ``I know
they are fundamentally the same as anyone else. Their hair is cut a
little shorter, if anything else. I know the lingo to a certain
degree. I don't now how far it will take you, but it will help you
get a foot in the door.''
   In 1970, Atkinson received an appointment to the West Point
Class of '74, but chose to attend college in North Carolina to
study English.
   ``I just decided it wasn't for me,'' he said. ``It was the
spring of Kent State, when the war and the Army were as unpopular
as they ever were.''
   ``The Long Gray Line'' has received mostly favorable reviews
from critics and West Pointers, both past and present. At a book
signing session this fall at West Point, a long gray line of cadets
snaked through the academy bookstore, waiting to buy copies and get
them autographed by the author.
   Atkinson said he has met or talked to about half of the Class of
'66. ``I keep running into them on the road,'' he said.
   Some told the author that admitting female cadets and other
attempts at ``humanizing'' West Point have ``devalued the place in
many ways.''
   Others told Atkinson that the intense hazing cadets suffer in
their first year is ``juvenile and contrary to what constitutes the
tenets of discipline.''
   Despite whatever differences or disillusions they may harbor,
Atkinson said West Point still commands a special place in the
lives of the Class of '66.
   ``Most of them feel this great attachment toward West Point.
It's the fountainhead of their youth, as one of them said. The
academy is, was and always will be a very big part of their lives.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Dec. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
