<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 18, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chemist Makes Clean-burning Fuel With Cooking Oil, Methanol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mixture of common cooking oil and
methanol will be tested as a fuel in a Regional District bus.
   ``Diesels run very well on it,'' said Thomas Reed, a Colorado
School of Mines chemist. ``Thirty percent added to diesel fuel will
reduce (tailpipe) smoke. Or we can use it as a substitute. We'll
try it Transportation
both ways.''
   Reed uses a process called transesterification to combine
cooking oil and methanol to produce a fuel that is 10 percent
oxygen. It is cleaner than diesel fuel and produces 95 percent of
the energy, and he has even been able to make the product using
waste drippings from such things as french-fry machines.
   ``I went down to the local fast-food restaurant and bought a
gallon of waste oil,'' he said. ``We added the methanol and cooked
it. All the nastyivision. ``We have shown
that exposure to UV light causes a marked depletion and change in
the skin's antioxidant defense mechanism, and now we are seeking to
learn how to prevent compromise of this important protective
system.''
   Work by Packer and colleagues at LBL and the University of
California, Berkeley, has been reported in recent issues of the
Journal of Investigative Dermatology, and in Photochemistry and
Photobiology.
   They tested the skin sensitivity of hairless mice to A and B
ultraviolet light, the most plentiful and damaging UV components of
sunlight. Both caused significant loss in the skin of antioxidants,
which prevent initial DNA damage and also may guard against later
stages of tumor development, Packer said.
   ``The idea is that topically applied antioxidants may confer
protection by being destroyed first _ before DNA and other
important molecules,'' he said.
   But products of UV damage can slip into deeper layers of the
skin and unexposed tissues, particularly after chronic UV exposure;
the damage products can enter the blood, affecting other parts of
the body later, he added.
   The researchers want to conduct more studies on whether
``antioxidant therapy'' through diet could be more effective than
treatment with a cream of some type, Packer said. ``Each of the
stages in the development of skin cancer may be affected by UV
exposure and may involve production of destructive oxygen species
that can be counteracted by antioxidants.
   ``Our work should therefore suggest valuable and new approaches
both to prevention of skin cancer and to protection against an
adverse outcome once cancerous changes have begun.''
</TEXT>
