<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0843</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury convicted GAF Corp. and a top
executive of manipulating the price of a company's stock, as the
government won another victory in its crackdown on Wall Street
fraud.
   After two previous mistrials, the jury in U.S. District Court
found GAF and Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin guilty Wednesday on
all eight counts of stock manipulation, securities fraud, wire
fraud and conspiracy. Two GAF subsidiaries were acquitted of all
charges.
   Sherwin's attorney, Stephen Kaufman, said he would appeal the
conviction. GAF said it also planned to appeal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of North American-made cars and light
trucks tumbled 23.7 percent in early December compared with last
year as the 1989 selling year began drawing to a
less-than-spectacular close, automakers said.
   The eight major U.S. automakers reported Wednesday that their
dealers sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 22,589
during the Dec. 1-10 period this year, compared with a rate of
29,610 a day during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. retailers' sales rebounded in November,
the government said in a report analysts saw as showing
stronger-than-expected Christmas buying and less chance of a
recession.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that sales rose 0.8
percent to a seasonally adjusted $144.6 billion in November after
plummeting 1.3 percent in October, when they were driven down by
skidding automobile sales. The October sales were revised after
originally being reported to have fallen 1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States recorded its best trade
performance in almost six years from July through September as the
deficit in the broadest measure of trade shrank 29 percent to
$22.69 billion, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the current account
deficit narrowed by $9.40 billion from a second quarter imbalance
of $32.08 billion, reflecting a big jump in the overseas earnings
of U.S. companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc. announced a
second-quarter loss of more than $1 billion due to failing
businesses and cheap asset sales in a bid to avoid bankruptcy.
   The struggling financial services firm said Wednesday the loss
exceeded a previously anticipated $600 million decline mainly
because of substantially lower-than-expected proceeds from the sale
of its core businesses.
   Integrated reported a loss of $1.04 billion, or $141.15 a share,
on revenue of $70.59 million in the April-June quarter. That
compared with earnings of $12.78 million, or 68 cents a share, in
the same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated and Allied department stores, owned
by the financially troubled Campeau Corp., may file for bankruptcy
as early as January if lenders don't agree to restructure their $7
billion debt.
   The Cincinnati-based retailers said in a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing released Wednesday that they would run out of
cash by mid-March and possibly as early as January unless creditors
ease repayment schedules.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. proposed
using a Soviet satellite network to possibly triple
telecommunications traffic between the United States and Soviet
Union.
   The plan, if approved by the Federal Communications Commission,
would route AT&amp;T's operator-assisted, direct dialed, data and video
services onto the Intersputnik satellite system for the first time.
   AT&amp;T said Wednesday telephone traffic between the two countries
increased by more than 140 percent in the past two years, ``but
demand still far exceeds existing capacity.''
