<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TimeWarner-Fees     12-14 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time Warner-Fees,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Warner Merger Creates Windfall for Banks, Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   AP Business Writer=
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The $14 billion merger of Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc. generated a multi-million dollar windfall for
the investment banks that financed it, as well as corporate
officers.
   The banks will split more than $120 million in investment
advisory fees and expenses while some of Warner Communications' top
executives will each garner nearly $20 million from the settlement
of three stock plans.
   Bert W. Wasserman, chief financial officer for Warner, will make
more than $21 million in cash under a prior agreement for
liquidating stock options and stock appreciation rights. Warner's
general counsel, Martin D. Payson, will collect a similar amount.
   Even the Securities and Exchange Commission stands to make an
estimated $4 million from the filing fees that accompany such a
large transaction. Those fees will go to the U.S. Treasury.
   The fee disclosures came in a recent prospectus, filed with the
SEC, for two new classes of convertible, preferred stock that Time
Warner Inc. wants to issue in January. Time and Warner earlier this
year agreed to the $14 billion combination, which would create the
world's largest media and entertainment concern, Time-Warner Inc.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co. were
each paid ``$16 million for acting as financial advisors'' to Time
Warner. Shearson Lehman, made an additional $32.5 million in fees
for a $1 billion ``bridge'' loan that was repaid Oct. 11.
   A bridge loan is a short-term advance, which yields high fees to
the lender, made in anticipation of longer-term financing.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. also received $32.5 million in fees for a
similar $1 billion bridge loan and collected an additional $1.5
million in financial advisor fees.
   Lazard Freres &amp; Co. collected $20 million for serving as
Warner's financial adviser and chief investment banker.
   Time Warner also paid out $350 million in fees to commercial
banks that provided additional financing.
   In all, the communications giant will have to pay an estimated
$500 million in fees and expenses.
   And sizeable chunks of cash will be going to corporate officers.
   In addition to Wasserman's $21.1 million; Payson, the general
counsel is expected to get about $19.5 million and Deane F.
Johnson, an executive in the office of the president of Warner
stands to make $20.1 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
