<DOCNO> AP891214-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Perot'sAirport     12-14 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Perot's Airport,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alliance Airport Opens, Concept Takes Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When an American Airlines jumbo jet touches down today at
spanking new Fort Worth Alliance Airport, it will signal a major
step in a unique project conceived by the son of billionaire H.
Ross Perot.
   The project is touted as the nation's first industrial airport
and an example of how to rebuild America.
   ``The whole point of what we have done and achieved is that
working with the government, you can build a lot of infrastructure
programs rather quickly,'' said H. Ross Perot Jr.
   ``This is a great example of teamwork,'' he said. Indeed the
name comes from the ``alliance'' of Perot and local, state and
federal agencies.
   ``A lot of experts say the 90s will be the decade of rebuilding
America, and this is one way, these public-private partnerships,''
he said.
   The VIP-filled plane will land ``18 months, 19 days, 23 hours
and 25 minutes'' after the airport's groundbreaking, something of a
record in cutting through a federal bureaucracy: airport
certification averages three to five years.
   Federal employees were even at work Thanksgiving Day installing
equipment, said Jack Sasser, deputy regional administrator for the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   Much work still needs to be done, including building a permanent
tower to replace temporary facilities in a trailer, although
American Airlines already has begun construction on its $400
million maintenance base _ the plum Perot landed last summer that
gave the $250 million project credibility.
   The federal Drug Enforcement Administration plans to base a
fleet of 90 planes at the airport. Sante Fe Railway has completed a
car distribution facility for Honda and is beginning work on a
similar facility for Ford.
   Although the project is ahead of schedule, ``before the whole
thing is really, no kidding ready, it'll probably be two years,''
Perot said.
   The airport, on land donated by Perot and owned by the city of
Fort Worth, was first proposed by the FAA as a relief valve for
busy Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport 15 miles away.
   The FAA approached The Perot Group with the idea in 1987 because
Perot had spent millions of his father's dollars amassing 17,000
acres to become the largest landowner in rural Tarrant and Denton
counties.
   The money came from the $2.7 billion Perot received when he sold
Electronic Data Systems Inc. to General Motors Corp. and then was
bought out of his additional stock and kicked off the board in a
bitter dispute with GM Chairman Roger Smith.
   Instead of creating an adjunct to DFW, Perot Jr. thought bigger,
dreaming up Alliance Centre. Although the FAA at first was
reluctant to increase the scale, it eventually went along,
especially after then-House Speaker Jim Wright of Fort Worth pushed
through a bill telling the agency the airport was a high priority.
   The airport, which will be managed by a Perot company, consists
of a 9,600-foot runway and two taxiways that can handle planes up
to the mammoth C-5A cargo jet and 747s. It is the largest U.S.
airport constructed since DFW opened 15 years ago.
   ``Alliance will be an airport surrounded by business and
industry,'' Perot says. ``It will allow aircraft to carry raw
materials directly to manufacturing facilities around the airport.
These materials can be quickly integrated with on-site
manufacturing processes before loading onto aircraft for transport
around the world.''
   In addition, Alliance lies on a major north-south rail line and
Perot has gotten state agreement to improve roads around the
development to better connect with nearby interstate highways.
   Perot even donated $500,000 to a local school district to allay
its fears over lost tax revenue because of concessions granted
American to lure its maintenance base.
   Perot admits success of the concept can't be measured for 20 to
25 years, but ``if it works, it will be profitable.''
   In the meantime, Perot is focusing on bringing traditional
aviation-related clients to Alliance, selling them Perot-owned land
by the runway or on the same 3,800-acre plot as the airport.
   Employees can live in a Perot-owned development nearby _ 150
houses already have been built _ and shop at a planned shopping
mall _ a development company recently purchased land to build the
complex.
   One estimate put possible revenue from land sales at $1 billion.
Estimates on the cost of the property range from $100 million to
$500 million.
   FAA officials are now suggesting similar concepts to help
relieve other congested airports, although they admit the scale
will be hard to duplicate because there are few areas with access
to a Perot-like war chest and willingness to wait for a payoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WPPGroup     12-14 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WPP Group,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sorrell Says Additional Major Acquisitions by WPP Unlikely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advertising and marketing services giant WPP
Group PLC, which has taken a place among the world's largest ad
holding companies through record-setting acquisitions over the past
few years, is through with major purchases for the next few years,
Chief Executive Martin Sorrell said.
   But Sorrell, who has guided WPP's transformation into one of the
world's largest ad conglomerates, told securities analysts
Wednesday that the Japanese and others may be interested in
pursuing major advertising deals.
   London-based WPP, whose sole business was once making wire
shopping baskets, has the distinction of making the two biggest
acquisitions in advertising history plus numerous smaller buyouts
in the past three years.
   In 1987, it acquired the parent of the J. Walter Thompson
advertising company and the Hill &amp; Knowlton public relations firm
for what was then an industry record $566 million.
   WPP shattered the ad buyout record last sumer with an $864
million purchase of Ogilvy Group, parent of the ad agency Ogilvy &amp;
Mather Worldwide.
   The acquisitions lifted WPP's billings to about $13.5 billion,
placing it in a contest with Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. PLC for the
rankings of the world's biggest advertising holding companies.
   Sorrell told analysts at the 17th annual PaineWebber media
outlook conference that new business billings have risen by another
$1.2 billion in the past year. That includes new assignments of $40
million from Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. for J. Walter Thompson and
$40 million from Olivetti for Ogilvy &amp; Mather.
   Asked if he had any plans for additional large acquisitions,
Sorrell replied it was ``unlikely we will do anything of
significant size for two or three years.''
   WPP has indicated in the past that it may be interested in
making smaller acquisitions in areas such as health care, database
management and market research.
   The company also recently indicated it is considering buying a
minority stake in a television franchise in the United Kingdom as a
way of generating a profit and gaining experience in another area
of the media business.
   Sorrell told the analysts he is intent on improving profit
margins at J. Walter Thompson, where the company already is well
ahead of the goals WPP set for it when it was acquired, and at
Ogilvy.
   In addition, Sorrell said he hoped to improve margins at Hill &amp;
Knowlton and MRB Group, the market research unit.
   He said that while WPP will be sitting the mega-deal market out
for the next few years, there still may be large-scale buyout
activity.
   Sorrell noted Japanese agencies may find it necessary to expand
overseas along with their big clients who find it ``more difficult
to achieve their objectives in the Japanese market.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
