<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in early European trading
today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was nervous in thin
year-end volume which they said was about 70 percent of normal,
causing exaggerated fluctuations.
   Market participants were also squaring positions ahead of
Friday's scheduled release of U.S. trade figures for October, they
said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.37 yen to a closing 144.07 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 144.08 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
quotes, included: 1.7330 West German marks, down from 1.7390;
1.5591 Swiss francs, down from 1.5965; 5.9360 French francs, down
from 5.9475; 1.9503 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9430; 1,294.00
Italian lire, down from 1,296.25; and 1.1605 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1585.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.5994 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5955 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $408.90 a troy ounce,
down from $411.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $409.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $408.70, down from $411.00 bid late
Wednesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong fell $6.08 to close at a bid $408.65.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.57 a troy ounce
compared with Wednesday's $5.59.
</TEXT>
