<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-14 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Once Againt Up In Tokyo, Dollar Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index, whose climb
has been almost without pause in the last three weeks, closed at
another record high today while the dollar edged up against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 118.28
points, or 0.31 percent, closing at 38,180.70. It closed above
38,000 for the first time on Wednesday, when it climbed 258.89
points to 38,062.42.
   Investors cut into the Nikkei's gains this afternoon, however,
selling shares out of concern over the speed of recent rises,
dealers said.
   It took only 16 trading days for the index to gain more than
2,000 points. It first climbed above 36,000 on Nov. 21.
   ``Market players were gradually becoming cautious and reluctant
to buy further, and the number of issues purchased has declined,''
said Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co.
   Masahiro Umemori, an analyst with Nomura Securities Co.,
attributed the index's gains to investors' expectations that
reforms in Eastern Europe will bring Japan bigger business
opportunities.
   ``Recent market movements have little to do with economic
fundamentals, but optimism over economic liberalization in Eastern
Europe,'' he said.
   An estimated 800 million shares, unchanged from the previous
day, changed hands on the first section. Among gainers were steel,
petroleum and railway issues.
   The dollar closed at 144.07 yen, up 0.37 yen from Wednesday's
143.70-yen close. It opened at 144.13 yen and ranged between 144.05
yen and 144.23 yen.
   Overnight gains on overseas markets led to the higher opening,
but the dollar moved narrowly after that as the market awaited the
announcement of several U.S. economic indicators, including October
trade figures, due Friday, traders said.
   Mitsui Bank trader Yoshitsugu Hanada said the West German mark,
which soared against other major currencies on Wednesday, slumped
today as market players sold it for profit-taking and position
adjustments.
   ``The mark weakened against the yen also as investors who had
been selling the yen to buy the mark bought back the yen,'' he said.
   The dollar-yen dealings remained inactive with only small
position adjustments, Hanada said.
   Spot trading amounted to $3.46 billion, down sharply from
Wednesday's $8.42 billion.
</TEXT>
