<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AutoSales     12-14 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Down 23.7 Percent in Early December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic automakers may be testing market
strength as they hold off boosting incentive packages although
their sales continue to fall, analysts say.
   The eight major U.S. automakers reported Wednesday their dealers
sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 22,589 during the
Dec. 1-10 period this year, down 23.7 percent from a rate of 29,610
a day during the same time last year.
   Car sales were off 27.9 percent and truck sales were down 16.6
percent.
   ``A year ago, we had some pretty aggressive incentives,'' said
analyst Doug Laughlin of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. of New York. ``No one
is going to confirm this, but I believe the industry is trying to
gauge the actual level of demand without incentives to see what
they can do without throwing out money needlessly.''
   Cash rebates and lower-than-bank-loan interest rates have become
part of car buying. But automakers pay for the incentives out of
their profits, which were severely dented in 1989.
   Chrysler Corp.'s early-December car sales fell by 33.1 percent,
Ford Motor Co.'s dropped 30.2 percent and General Motors Corp.'s
car sales during the period were off 28.4 percent.
   ``These are pretty close to what we've been getting in the last
two (selling) periods,'' Laughlin said.
   With just 2{ weeks of selling left in 1989, the industry
appeared to be heading for the seventh-best year on record, selling
somewhere around 14.8 million cars and trucks.
   Last year's sales of 15.8 million was the second-best in
history, behind the 16.3 million vehicles sold in 1986. Sales
totaled 15.5 million in 1987.
   So far this year, car and truck sales are running 3.2 percent
behind last year's pace. Car sales are down 4.3 percent and truck
sales are off 1.2 percent.
   Chrysler said its early-December truck sales were down 16.4
percent, combining with car sales for a 25.1 percent decline in
vehicle sales. Through Dec. 10 of this year, Chrysler's cars and
light trucks were selling at a pace 6.7 percent below last year.
   Ford said its 30.2 percent decline in early-December car sales
and a 16 percent drop in light truck sales combined for a vehicle
sales rate 24.4 percent lower than during the same period last year.
   So far this year, Ford's cars and trucks are selling at a rate 3
percent below last year's pace.
   GM said its combined car and truck sales in early December were
23.9 percent lower than they were during the same time last year,
as its decline in car sales combined with a 14.9 percent drop in
light truck sales.
   For the entire year, through Dec. 10, GM's vehicle sales are
down 5.8 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-GAFTrial 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Fraud Conviction Another Notch in Government's Belt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS length of Helmsley sentence in 2nd gfraf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors notched another victory in their
assault on Wall Street crime when a jury convicted GAF Corp. and a
top executive of stock manipulation in the government's third
attempt after two mistrials.
   The guilty verdict Wednesday in Manhattan federal court _ where
a judge one day earlier sentenced hotel queen Leona Helmsley to
four years in prison for tax evasion _ again demonstrated public
opposition to white-collar wrongdoing.
   Some lawyers were surprised by the verdict because of
controversial and sometimes contradictory testimony by admitted
felon Boyd L. Jefferies and evidence introduced at the trial's
close undermining central portions of the government's case.
   ``The pattern you see from a variety of these cases is that if
there is some smoke there _ circumstantial evidence _ then juries
tend to find there is some fire,'' Columbia University securities
law professor John C. Coffee Jr. said.
   ``I do think the jury particularly in Wall Street cases has a
good deal of skepticism of the motives of people,'' he said. ``This
is a case where there was some evidence, but it was a one-witness
case.''
   GAF and Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin were found guilty on all
eight counts of stock manipulation, securities fraud, wire fraud
and conspiracy. Two GAF subsidiaries were acquitted of all charges.
   Sherwin, 56, of Princeton, N.J., faces up to 40 years in prison
and $2 million in fines when sentenced March 9 by Judge Mary
Johnson Lowe. GAF, a Wayne, N.J.-based chemical and building
materials manufacturer, could be fined a total of up to $4 million.
   ``Justice is finally done,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl H.
Loewenson Jr. said.
   After the verdict, an ashen-faced Sherwin embraced his wife and
daughters. ``I'm terribly disappointed and I'm innocent of these
charges,'' he said to reporters.
   GAF and Sherwin's attorney, Stephen Kaufman, said they would
appeal the conviction. The subsidiaries found innocent were Jay &amp;
Company Inc. and GAF Chemicals Corp.
   A July 1988 grand jury indictment alleged a scheme to boost the
stock price of Union Carbide Corp. in 1986 shortly before GAF sold
a large block of Carbide shares amassed during a failed takeover.
   When the case first opened a year ago, it attracted wide
attention as the first criminal trial stemming from the insider
trading scandals of the mid-1980s.
   It lost some luster amid a series of glitzier cases, in which
the government won convictions in all but one case, where a jury
returned a split verdict.
   Among those convicted: six defendants in the Princeton-Newport
Partners racketeering trial, takeover specialist Paul A. Bilzerian
and Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. bond trading assistant Lisa Jones.
   In addition, the government has obtained guilty pleas from
figures such as former investment banker Martin A. Siegel,
arbitrager Robert Freeman and stock speculator Salim B. Lewis.
   ``It's another part of the message that the U.S. attorney's
office has been sending to the financially fortunate of our
country, that manipulation of our financial mechanisms and failure
to pay taxes are going to be severely dealt with,'' said attorney
Gerald Walpin, a former prosecutor.
   The GAF jury returned a verdict after about only eight hours of
testimony. The second mistrial, in March, was declared after 12
days and 93 hours of deliberations. The first mistrial occurred
because the government unintentionally withheld a key document.
   ``Maybe all the media concentration on fraud on Wall Street has
pressured the public that all the fraud on Wall Street was more
severe than it thought initially,'' said Alan Bromberg, a
securities law professor at Southern Methodist University.
   ``I think we're developing a pretty healthy distrust of our
financial institutions,'' he said.
   In the trial's final days, GAF lawyer Arthur Liman introduced
telephone records indicating that no calls were placed on
long-distance WATS lines from the Jefferies &amp; Co. brokerage to GAF
or Sherwin during times in October 1986 when the government alleged
the manipulation was discussed.
   ``It seemed to be a pretty significant piece of evidence but the
jury didn't think so,'' said one defense lawyer in a major case who
asked not to be named.
   Jefferies testified that Sherwin asked him to boost Union
Carbide's price to $22 a share and agreed to pay 40,000 to cover
losses in the deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
