<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-Moody's     12-14 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Moody's,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Debt Rating Knocked Down A Notch by Moody's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ratings for some Chrysler Corp. securities were
dropped one level by Moody's Investors Service because of concerns
about the automaker's future.
   Moody's, a credit rating service, said in a news release
received Wednesday in Detroit that it was lowering the ratings
because of ``concerns that Chrysler's operating performance will
remain under pressure over the intermediate term,'' or three to
four years.
   Moody's rating for Chrysler's senior debt was lowered to
``Baa2'' from ``Baa1.'' Moody's analyst Carol Verschell said that
was toward the lower end of the company's investment-grade ratings.
   Movement in security ratings indicate increasing or decreasing
faith in the creditworthiness of a company.
   Another rating service, Fitch Investors Service Inc. said it was
reviewing Chrysler's securities and Standard &amp; Poors Corp. said no
change was likely.
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Houston read a statement saying: ``We're
disappointed in the action that Moody's has taken. But we believe
that it will not have any material effect on Chrysler ... borrowing
costs.''
   Chrysler stock closed at $19.87{ Wednesday, unchanged from
Tuesday's close.
   Moody's also said Chrysler's share of the light truck market,
which includes the company's popular minivans and Jeep vehicles,
will come under increasing competitive pressure.
   Chrysler's announcement earlier this month to sell Chrysler
Technologies Corp., which includes Gulfstream Aerospace Inc., will
provide some cash, Verschell said, but the timing of the sale and
the amount of the proceeds were uncertain.
   At Fitch, auto analyst Mary Anne Sudol said her company's
ratings for a variety of Chrysler securities were either the same
or slightly higher than Moody's new ratings. All Chrysler ratings
are under review, she said.
   ``There will be some action, but I don't know when it will
come,'' Sudol said.
   Nancy Stroker of Standard &amp; Poors said her company affirmed the
``BBB'' rating of Chrysler securities, roughly the same level as
Moody's. ``We don't expect to have any kind of rating change,'' she
said.
   Verschell said Moody's wasn't reviewing the ratings of General
Motors Corp. or Ford Motor Co. securities.
   Moody's announcement of lower Chrysler's ratings came before the
company reported that sales of its North American-made cars and
trucks fell 25.1 percent in early December from the same time last
year.
   Through Dec. 10, Chrysler's vehicle sales were running 6.7
percent behind last year's pace.
</TEXT>
