<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 0943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-BayerFine     12-14 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-Bayer Fine,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Fines Bayer AG For Competition Violation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community on Thursday
fined West German chemical producer Bayer AG $590,000 for violating
competition rules in the marketing of an animal feedstuff additive.
   The fine stems from Bayer's insistence that its West German
customers buy the additive, which boosts growth in animals, only
for themselves and use it only in the factory where the product was
delivered, the Commission said in a statement.
   The West German patent for the additive expired in 1985, opening
it up to competition and lower prices, the Community said.
   Bayer's requirement that its German clients buy only for
themselves was designed to keep clients from reselling the additive
to neighboring nations ``where patent protection still existed and
where prices were higher,'' the Commission said.
   Its fine is worth 500,000 European currency units.
</TEXT>
