<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ColumbiaSavings     12-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia Savings,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Federal Restrictions on Columbia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-month, $320 million drop in
Columbia Savings &amp; Loan's huge junk bond portfolio has prompted
federal authorities to restrict the thrift's high-risk deals and
halt dividend payments.
   Columbia officials said the company would not oppose the
restrictions imposed by the federal Office of Thrift Supervision.
The company disclosed the new limits in a regulatory filing made
public Wednesday.
   The restrictions on certain types of loans and so-called
``high-risk transactions'' such as funding leveraged buyouts
parallel corporate adjustments underway at Columbia to comply with
recent legislation signed by President Bush to end the nation's
thrift crisis.
   In a Nov. 20 letter to Columbia, regulators said the thrift's
capital ``is substantially inadequate'' to cover its junk bond
holdings, the company disclosed in the regulatory filing.
   At $3.8 billion, Columbia's junk bond holdings are the largest
by far among the nation's savings and loans. They account for 40
percent of the thrift's assets.
   Junk bonds are high-yield, high-risk securities. Prices paid for
junk bonds have plunged in recent months amid fears of a recession
and concerns about bonds that have been issued by troubled
institutions.
   The value of Columbia's junk bond portfolio declined by $220
million in October and another $100 million in late November.
   Under the new federal capital-standards restrictions signed by
Bush in August, Columbia and other thrifts must divest junk bond
portfolios by July 1, 1994.
   On Monday, Columbia announced that Thomas Spiegel would resign
as chairman and chief executive to set up a separate entity
expected to hold and manage the junk bonds.
   Columbia also agreed to seek permission from regulators before
paying any new dividends to shareholders. The thrift last paid a
dividend on Nov. 28, at 7 cents a share.
   Columbia also needs to seek federal approval before funding any
non-real estate commercial loans and risky transactions including
leveraged buyouts, in which a company is bought and the debt paid
off through cash from the sale of assets or operations.
   The restrictions will remain in effect until regulators approve
a new plan to be submitted by Columbia on how it will meet the new
federal capital guidelines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Allied-Federated 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Allied-Federated, 1st Ld-Writethru,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federated and Allied Department Stores Threaten To Seek Bankruptcy
Refuge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Eds: subs lead and 8th graf to clarify that the chains might
seek bankruptcy-court protection.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federated and Allied chains, owners of
Bloomingdale's and other big retailers, could seek bankruptcy-court
refuge early next year if lenders won't reschedule their $7 billion
debt, their parent company said.
   ``In the next 30 to 60 days, there's going to be a restructuring
one way or the other. One way is a voluntary restructuring. The
other would be under bankruptcy protection,'' an official at
Campeau Corp.'s headquarters in Toronto said Wednesday on the
condition on anonymity.
   Federated and Allied, both based in Cincinnati, said in filings
with the Securities and Exchange Commission that the companies
expect to run out of cash by March, possibly as early as next
month, unless creditors ease repayment terms.
   Federated must pay creditors $1.15 billion by the end of April.
Allied says it faces debts of $633.7 million due by the end of
March.
   Federated and Allied took on $8 billion in debt, much of it in
high interest ``junk bonds,'' as part of their takeover by Canadian
real estate magnate Robert Campeau. Campeau bought Federated in May
1988 and Allied in December 1986.
   Olympia and York Developments Ltd. of Canada, the huge real
estate company that owns a chunk of Campeau Corp., promised Campeau
in September to try to secure an $800 million bridge loan to keep
the retailers solvent.
   The Campeau official said that if Olympia and York can't arrange
the loan and the companies can't sell off assets fast enough to
stay solvent, ``Bankruptcy is spelled out as a possibility given
certain circumstances,'' possibly as early as January.
   What effect bankruptcy protection would have on shoppers is
unclear.
   In Cincinnati, Campeau spokeswoman Carol Sanger said that if
Federated and Allied sought Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy
protection, their stores would remain open. Chapter 11 allows
companies to continue operating while trying to repay creditors.
   Ms. Sanger said the debt burden is becoming increasingly
difficult for the companies to manage.
   Difficulty in meeting earlier debt payments prompted the
September restructuring that ousted Robert Campeau as board
chairman when Olympia and York bailed out the company.
   Campeau put Bloomingdale's, its leading retailer, up for sale
after announcing the restructuring. Federated is negotiating with
six bidders to sell Bloomingdale's to repay a $1.05 billion
short-term loan by April 30.
   Among Federated's other holdings is Lazarus department stores,
based in Cincinnati; Abraham &amp; Straus in New York; Burdines in
Miami, and Rich's and the Goldsmith stores in Atlanta and Memphis,
Tenn.
   Allied Stores' operations include Boston-based Jordan Marsh,
Maas Brothers-Jordan Marsh in Florida, Bon Marche in Seattle and
Stern's in New Jersey.
   Campeau stock tumbled 1 point to close at 4 in over-the-counter
trading Wednesday largely on rumors of a possible bankruptcy
filing, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891214-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-JetInspections     12-14 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jet Inspections,0286</SECOND>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan American World Airlines and USAir Group Inc.
said they are beginning inspection and modification programs for
older jets because of potential problems caused by aging.
   Pan Am said Wednesday it signed a $52.5 million contract with
Boeing Military Airplanes in Wichita, Kan., for structural
modifications on 13 of Pan Am's older 747s.
   In addition to the 13 planes, Boeing will continue modifications
to Pan Am 747s under the Civil Reserve Air Fleet program which
prepares aircraft for Air Force use in case of national emergency.
   The modifications, begun on 18 747s in 1985, cost about $11
million per plane. Boeing also has conducted other updates to the
planes, costing about $6 million each during the program.
   Pan Am said 10 more of its 747s will be upgraded at its
maintenance center at Kennedy Airport in New York, with all 747
upgrading completed by 1993, said Robert Gould, senior vice
president of operations.
   USAir has also begun inspecting and repairing 50 of its oldest
DC-9s. The airline, based in Washington, D.C., has 75 McDonnell
Douglas DC-9s, delivered from 1967 to 1982.
   Older Boeing planes have been subjected to inspections and
modifications ordered by the Federal Aviation Administration as a
result of findings and recommendations of an industry task force.
   Larry Pickett, USAir spokesman in Los Angeles, said one DC-9 has
been examined and another is about halfway through the month-long
process. The work is being done in Pittsburgh.
   The industry effort to inspect older planes followed the 1988
Aloha Airlines incident in which the top of the fuselage of a 737
tore off in flight, killing a flight attendant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
