<FIRST>r f BC-Swissair-SingaporeAirlines     12-14 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Swissair-Singapore Airlines,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swissair, Singapore Airlines Sign Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swissair and Singapore Airlines
announced Thursday they have signed a new cooperation agreement and
plan to finalize details of a 5 percent share-swap accord by the
end of 1990.
   The agreement established the third link in a global alliance
between the two airlines and Delta Air Lines of the United States,
according to a statement issued after the signing ceremony in
Zurich.
   Swissair, Switzerland's national flag carrier, and Singapore
Airlines both signed bilateral agreements with Atlanta-based Delta
earlier in the year.
   The new accord provides for coordination of flight schedules
between Switzerland and Singapore and for cooperation in marketing,
the statement said.
   ``Together with Delta, we are the world's first truly global
travel system,'' said Singapore Airlines Chairman Cheong Choong
Kong.
   Swissair has 55 aircraft serving 110 destinations in 68
countries. It carried a total of 8.1 million passengers and 267,000
metric tons of cargo in 1988.
   Singapore Airlines operates 39 jets to 57 cities in 37
countries. It transported 6.2 million passengers and 240,000 metric
tons of cargo last year.
</TEXT>
