<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-14 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Open Higher On Weather Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were slightly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
advancing Wednesday's gains amid concern about the market impact of
the cold weather.
   Some traders say frigid temperatures in the Eastern United
States will boost domestic demand for feed grains and soybean meal
as livestock producers increase feedings.
   But others see the freezing of waterways as slowing grain
shipments, a bearish factor.
   ``The ultimate disaster would be if it slows shipping to the
point where exports are canceled,'' said William Biedermann,
director of research with the futures brokerage Allendale Inc.
   Forecasts for continued hot, dry weather in southern Brazil, the
world's No. 2 soybean producer, supported the soybean market.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent to 1\ cents higher
with December at $4.15} a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 1{
cents higher with December at $2.34} a bushel; oats were \ cent
lower to \ cent higher with December at $1.43} a bushel; soybeans
were 1} cents to 3\ cents higher with January at $5.82\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading, led by
pork prices, reflecting the belief that the bitter cold
temperatures in the Midwest are slowing the movement of hogs to
market.
   Live cattle futures were .22 cent to .52 cent higher with
December at 77.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .50
cent higher with January at 83.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .25
cent to .85 cent higher with December at 52.55 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .83 cent to 1.10 cents higher with
February at 53 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
