<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Mesa-Pickens 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mesa-Pickens, 1st Ld-Writethru,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mesa LP Eliminates Distribution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT that prices are quoted in thousand
cubic feet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mesa Limited Partnership, the energy company run
by takeover strategist T. Boone Pickens, announced today it would
stop paying unitholders a cash distribution next year because of
low prices for natural gas, which account for 80 percent of its
holdings.
   Mesa said it would pay its 37.5 cents distribution for the
fourth quarter, but ``discontinue cash distribution to the common
units until industry conditions and cash flow improve.''
   The news sent Mesa units tumbling in active trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, where prices fell $1.12{ to $7.87{.
   ``The drop in natural gas prices has clearly been a problem for
Mesa, as it has been for the entire industry,'' Pickens said in a
letter to unitholders.
   He said in 1985, the partnership's average gas price was $2.68
per thousand cubic feet and has declined each year to an average of
about $1.65 per thousand cubic feet in 1989. If prices had held at
$2.68, he said, the partnership's cash flow would have been $400
million greater.
   Pickens said the distribution policy will be reviewed quarterly.
The cut does not affect preference unitholders, who will continue
to receive 37.5 cents for six additional quarters.
   The announcement is the second time this year Mesa has cut its
distribution. In March, the partnership cut its payout from 50
cents per unit. To maintain that high distribution, Mesa had used
stock profits and asset sales to cover any gaps.
   In an effort to reduce debt, Mesa also announced today the
creation of a Hugoton Royalty Trust made up of Mesa's holdings in
the Hugoton field in Kansas, the nation's largest natural gas
field. Mesa said the interest will be sold in a public offering
next year and is expected to bring in $300 million.
   ``I remain a believer in natural gas,'' wrote Pickens, who said
90 percent of his net worth is tied up in Mesa. ``Never has more
been written and spoken about the environmental superiority of gas
and the competitive advantages of gas over oil.
   ``About 80 percent of Mesa's reserves are natural gas _ we have
placed our bet,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
