<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BurgerKing-Kids Bjt   12-14 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burger King-Kids, Bjt,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burger King Courts Children With New Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles eat only pizza, but
Burger King Corp. is hoping the swashbuckling terrapins and other
pre-adolescent idols will come to the rescue of the nation's No. 2
fast-food chain.
   With sales sluggish and market share dipping, Miami-based Burger
King will court youngsters with an ambitious advertising and
promotional campaign scheduled to begin next month.
   The Kids Club _ with toy give-aways and a gang of contemporary
cartoon characters _ aims directly at the grade-school market long
dominated by rival McDonald's Corp. and its orange-haired
ambassador Ronald, analysts say.
   ``The kids are a link to our future business and they heavily
influence where a family might go to eat,'' says Burger King
spokeswoman Cori Zywotow.
   The first sign of Kids Club will appear at Burger King's 5,400
U.S. restaurants on Jan. 1 with special meals that include toy cars
shaped like french fries and other fast-food mainstays. Future
prizes include Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtle badges and figures from
the Beetlejuice cartoon series.
   Applications also will be available for Kids Club membership,
which includes stickers, other goodies and a subscription to a
newsletter published five times a year.
   But the centerpiece of the 18-month-old project is the seven
Kids Club characters, a sort-of ultra-hip ``Our Gang'' with an
absent-minded computer genius; a voracious food expert, and
Spanky's leading role taken over by Kid Zid, who moves between the
``real'' world and a high-technology realm of video and electronics.
   Other characters include a girl obsessed with photography; a
cheerful lad in a turbo-charged wheelchair and a tom-boy who speaks
in sports cliches. Their mascot: a stray dog.
   ``Most kids will be able to identify with at least one of the
Kids Club members,'' said Ms. Zywotow. ``Kids today are
sophisticated beyond our imagines ... you need to speak their
language.''
   Right now, Burger King executives are speaking about wide-spread
changes following a 3 percent rise in sales since London-based
Grand Metropolitan PLC acquired the company and its parent
Pillsbury Co. in January.
   Plans include revamping and expanding Burger King's menu and
upgrading service and conditions at franchise-owned outlets, which
comprise about 85 percent of the 5,900 Burger Kings worldwide.
   Problems in food quality and restaurant atmosphere have been
cited as contributing to Burger King's slide from 17.5 percent of
the $61 billion fast- food market in 1987 to 16.8 percent last year.
   Burger King's $5.4 billion in sales last year compares with more
than $17 billion at Oak Brook, Ill.-based McDonald's, which
operates about 10,500 restaurants. No. 3 Hardee's posted sales of
about $3 billion in 1988.
   Burger King has average store sales of about $1 million.
McDonald's outlets average about $1.6 million and Hardee's
restaurants sell about $920,000 apiece annually.
   The Kids Club will debut just 12 weeks after Burger King
unveiled a nationwide advertising campaign focusing on adults and
teens. The Kids Club commercials mostly will air Saturday morning,
where the line between entertainment and advertising often is hazy.
   ``Children control an incredible amount of money by influencing
where adults shop and eat _ and this is particularly true with
fast-food restaurants,'' said Peggy Charren, president of Action
for Children's Television in Cambridge, Mass.
   ``For Burger King to move back to this type of approach sends
the message that influencing children through advertising must work
quite well,'' said Ms. Charren, sponsor of a Senate bill to limit
commercial time on Saturday morning children's programs.
   But it's uncertain how successful Burger King will be against
McDonald's, which has ruled the children's fast-food market through
Saturday morning commercials and tie-ins between its Happy Meals
and such popular movies as Walt Disney Co.'s ``The Little Mermaid.''
   ``McDonald's has been very successful at the children's
market,'' said Laurie Lively, an analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co Inc.
in New York. ``They've been doing it well for a long time.''
   Daniel Lee, an analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert in New York,
said some studies indicate Ronald McDonald is the second most
recognizable figure for pre-school children behind Santa Claus.
   ``Try putting a couple of kids in a car and driving past a
McDonald's,'' said Lee. ``It's hard. That's something McDonald's
has been working on for years and years and years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
