<DOCNO> AP891214-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northrop     12-14 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northrop,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say B-2 Maker Puts HQ Building Up for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled defense contractor Northrop Corp.,
maker of the B-2 Stealth bomber, plans to sell its tony
headquarters complex in Century City to raise cash, company
officials say.
   ``In order to reduce our debt, we're actively looking at the
sale of our non-operating assets,'' spokesman Tony Cantafio was
quoted as telling Copley Los Angeles Newspapers in a story
published today.
   Northrop is not the first aerospace company to try to cash in on
real estate recently as prospects for defense work have dimmed.
Last month, F-14 maker Grumman Corp. said it would redevelop nearly
half its 500-acre Long Island headquarters with a hotel, shopping
center and offices.
   Northrop sent information packages to 10 prospective buyers on
its two Century Park East buildings about a month ago, asking
$247.5 million for them, said Mike DeSantis, a vice president of
the Cushman &amp; Wakefield real estate brokerage.
   De Santis said that price represents the same cost per square
foot that was paid last year for the nearby Fox Plaza, where former
President Ronald Reagan, billionaire investor Marvin Davis, and
20th Century Fox have their offices.
   Potential buyers were not disclosed.
   Northrop's stock has traded as high as $35.75 during the past
year, but closed Wednesday at less than half that level, $17.50 per
share.
   It was up $1 in early trading today on a Los Angeles Times
report that Defense Secretary Dick Cheney had decided to build all
132 of the B-2 stealth bombers, a program that accounts for half
Northrop's sales.
   At $18.50 per share, Northrop's 47 million shares of common
stock would be worth about $870 million _ far less than the
company's $1.2 billion debt.
   The $870 million is also less than than the value of the
company's real estate holdings, according to aerospace analyst
Lawrence Harris at the Bateman Eichler, Hill Richards brokerage in
Los Angeles.
   Northrop Chairman Thomas Jones told shareholders at the annual
meeting in May the company might sell properties no longer ``useful
in our plans.''
   Northrop owns manufacturing plants in Southern California,
Illinois, Massachusetts and Oklahoma, but those properties are not
for sale.
</TEXT>
