<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mesa-Pickens Bjt   12-14 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mesa-Pickens, Bjt,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eliminates Cash Distribution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Low natural gas prices have forced Mesa Limited
Partnership to scrap cash distributions and sell assets to reduce
debt, the energy company run by takeover strategist T. Boone
Pickens announced Thursday.
   Pickens said stopping the cash distribution, akin to a dividend
payment to shareholders in a corporation, was necessary to maintain
Mesa's ``financial integrity while gas prices remain low.''
   Besides cutting out its 37.5-cent per unit quarterly
distribution, Mesa said it will package its holdings in the Hugoton
natural gas field into a separate royalty trust and sell shares to
raise $300 million to pay down its $1.5 billion in long-term debt,
much of it left over from last year's $715 million purchase of
natural gas properties from Tenneco Inc.
   The news sent Mesa units tumbling in active trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, where prices had fallen $1.37{ to $7.62{ by
mid-afternoon.
   Until earlier this year, Mesa had paid out $2 a year to each
unitholder, even though revenue from its holdings fell far short of
justifying the payout. The difference had been made up from
Pickens' stock plays involving such companies as Gulf Oil Corp.,
Phillips Petroleum Co and Unocal.
   Pickens defended the practice Thursday, calling it a way of
``prepaying'' unitholders profits from high gas prices in the
future.
   Mesa still has about $400 million worth of cash and marketable
securities, said Bill Ballew, a Mesa financial official.
   In March, Mesa announced a cut in third and fourth quarter
payments to 37.5 cents, and analysts had been expecting a further
reduction although some were surprised the distribution was
eliminated.
   Charles Strain, an analyst with Lovett, Underwood, Newhouse and
Webb Inc. in Houston, said Mesa could only justify a payout of 30
cents a year based on current gas prices, ``so this makes sense.''
   ``The drop in natural gas prices has clearly been a problem for
Mesa, as it has been for the entire industry,'' Pickens said in a
letter to unitholders.
   ``In 1985, our average gas price was $2.68 per thousand cubic
feet; it has declined each year to an average of about $1.65
thousand cubic feet in 1989. If prices had held at $2.68 per
thousand cubic feet during the four years 1986-1089, our cash flow
would have been $400 million greater.''
   The current December price is about $1.85; it is expected to
rise above $2 in January.
   The price should rise to about $2.50 per thousand cubic feet if
oil remains in the $20-a-barrel range, Strain said.
   At that level, he said, Mesa would be profitable.
   ``We didn't make any money this year, but there is a good
possibility that we're going to make money in the mid- to late
90s,'' Ballew said.
   Most observers expect the price of natural gas to continue
rising as demand catches up to supply. The fuel frequently is
touted as a domestically available, safe, clean replacement for
gasoline.
   Mesa said the 37.5 cent distribution would be paid for the
fourth quarter, giving unitholders $1.75 per unit this year, but it
will ``discontinue cash distribution to the common units until
industry conditions and cash flow improve.''
   Pickens, who owns 4.3 million common units, said the
distribution policy will be reviewed quarterly. The cut does not
affect preference unitholders, who will continue to receive 37.5
cents for six additional quarters.
   To immediately raise money, Mesa said it would create the
Hugoton Royalty Trust from its holdings in the Hugoton field in
Kansas, the nation's largest natural gas field. Mesa said shares in
the trust will be sold in a public offering next year and are
expected to bring in $300 million.
   Twice in the past, Mesa has packaged holdings into trusts,
shares of which were distributed to unitholders. This time,
however, ``we needed the money,'' Ballew said.
   Pickens said the company would remain a limited partnership
because under that structure it doesn't pay pay federal income
taxes.
   ``I remain a believer in natural gas,'' wrote Pickens. ``About
80 percent of Mesa's reserves are natural gas _ we have placed our
bet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
