<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-14 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Gain On New-Crop Supply Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, paced by modest
gains in the soybean market amid concerns about new-crop supplies.
   The new-crop soybean contracts _ those for delivery next fall _
gained the most, as they have for most of this week.
   Traders are speculating that U.S. farmers will plant fewer
soybeans in 1990 than this year and devote more acreage to corn,
wheat and cotton to take advantage of government-guaranteed prices
for those crops in the last year of the current Farm Bill, said Ann
Frick, senior soybean analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   New crop soybeans also were supported by increasing fears of a
drought in the prime soybean-growing region of Brazil.
   Buying of corn, wheat and old-crop soybean futures was linked in
part to ideas that bitter cold in the Eastern United States would
lead to increased domestic livestock feeding.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent to 2\ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.16\ a bushel; corn
futures were } cent lower to 1} cents higher with December at $2.35
a bushel; oats were unchanged to \ cent higher with December at
$1.43} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 4\ cents higher with
January at $5.82{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
