<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1618EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Canada-Trade     12-14 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Trade,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Registers First Trade Deficit In 13 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's merchandise trade during October
registered a deficit for the first time in 13 years, the government
reported Thursday, fueling concern about a recession.
   Canada imported $421 million more goods than it sold abroad in
October, compared with a revised surplus of $134 million in
September, Statistics Canada reported.
   The October trade figures were much worse than analysts were
projecting. A surplus of about $200 million had been expected.
   ``The likelihood of a recession is rising every day,'' said
Ernie Stokes, an economist at WEFA Group, an economic research firm
based in Toronto.
   The federal agency said the worst monthly trade performance
since March 1976 was the result of imports growing much faster than
exports as the high-flying Canadian dollar makes Canadian goods
more expensive on foreign markets.
   In recent weeks, the Canadian dollar has risen to nine-year
highs of more than 86 U.S. cents as the Bank of Canada keeps
interest rates higher than rates in the United States to fight
inflation.
   John Crow, governor of the Bank of Canada, is expected to stick
with his policy of using high interest rates to slow the economy
and keep a lid on consumer prices and wage demands.
</TEXT>
