<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-14 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed Thursday in dull
trading on world currency markets.
   Gold prices slipped overseas but appeared to stabilize in U.S.
dealings after Wednesday's steep plunge.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $408.30 a troy ounce, up 20 cents from late
Wednesday. Republic National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for
gold at $408.30 an ounce, up 30 cents.
   Traders said the market was extremely quiet. ``Everybody is on
the sidelines,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Dealers and investors are awaiting Friday's release of key U.S.
economic data. The government is scheduled to report merchandise
trade figures for October and producer prices and industrial
production data for November.
   The figures will offer ``a lot to react to,'' said Marc
Chandler, an analyst with Chicago-based Money Market Services
International. But he noted that ``we don't have full liquidity in
the market _ it's sort of the holiday thinness.''
   Dealers have been expecting October's trade deficit to register
somewhere between $9 billion and $10 billion. But the Canadian
government's report Thursday showing the nation's first monthly
trade deficit in 13 years was cause for some speculation that the
U.S. deficit may have benefitted.
   Canada imported 421 million Canadian dollars more goods than it
sold abroad in October, compared with a revised surplus of 134
million in September, Statistics Canada reported.
   ``A lot of people track the two against each other since Canada
is our largest trading partner,'' Flanagan said.
   But others suggested Canada's weak showing may reflect a
slowdown in the U.S. economy. Chandler said that since Canada's
major exports to the United States are autos and auto parts, a
decline in U.S. auto buying may have contributed to Canada's
shortfall.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to close at 144.07 Japanese yen, from
143.70 yen on Wednesday. But later in London, it fell to 144.00
yen. In New York, the dollar finished at 144.15 yen, up from 144.05
yen late Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5970 from $1.5955 late
Wednesday. In New York it cost $1.6010 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Wednesday's $1.6000.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.7344 West German marks, up from 1.7280;
1.5630 Swiss francs, down from 1.5645; 5.9285 French francs, up
from 5.9070; 1.1598 Canadian dollars, unchanged; and 1,292.25
Italian lire, up from 1,289.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.7375 West German marks, down from 1.7390; 1.5630 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5965; 5.9420 French francs, down from 5.9475;
1.9565 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9430; 1,295.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,296.25; and 1.1585 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $407.50 a troy ounce
from $411.25 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, Switzerland, the metal
fell to a closing bid of $408.50 from $411.00 bid late Wednesday.
Gold in Hong Kong fell $6.08 to close at a bid $408.65.
   Silver prices were mixed. In London silver bullion fell to a
late bid price of $5.58 a troy ounce from $5.59 bid late Wednesday.
But on New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
finished at $5.557 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's $5.544.
</TEXT>
