<FIRST>r f AM-RacingForm     12-14 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racing Form,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racing Form Publisher To Retire; Regional GM Promoted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael P. Sandler, publisher of the Daily
Racing Form for nearly 16 years, will retire at yearend and remain
an advisor to the publication, it was announced Thursday.
   Martin Singerman, president of Racing Form's parent News America
Publishing Inc., said he would become president of the publication
and William H. Williams, general manager of the Racing Form's
eastern edition, would be promoted to national general manager.
   No one will assume the title of publisher.
   Sandler has been publisher of Daily Racing Form since February
1974. Between 1944 and 1972, he served as circulation manager,
assistant general manager and general manager of the Los Angeles
edition of the publication, which prints articles and extensive
statistical information on U.S. thoroughbred horse racing.
   News America, a unit Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. media empire,
acquired Daily Racing Form, TV Guide, Seventeen magazine and a
number of other publications when it bought Triangle Publications
Inc. for $3 billion in August 1988.
   ``Michael Sandler is the person most responsible for bringing
the Daily Racing Form to its present level of success,'' Singerman
said in a news release. ``We at News America are greatly indebted
to Mike for his guidance and dedication during the transition
period from Triangle to News America.''
   Williams, a former editor and general manager of the Colorado
Springs (Colo.) Free Press, joined Triangle in 1970 as director of
labor relations for the Racing Form. He has been general manager of
the Eastern edition, which is based in Highstown, N.J., since 1972.
</TEXT>
