<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-89 1802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-14 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hog Futures Surge On Cold-Weather Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for near-term deliveries of hogs surged more than a penny
per pound Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as frigid
weather in the Midwest slowed marketings and reduced slaughter
rates.
   The cold spell, which is expected to continue through the
weekend, also contributed to gains in the cattle and grain futures
markets.
   On other commodity markets, oil futures retreated and precious
metals were mostly higher.
   Hog futures settled .08 cents to 1.05 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December up 1.05 cents at 52.75 cents a
pound.
   Live cattle futures were .15 cent to .60 cent higher with
December at 77.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .43
cent higher with January at 83.72 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.10 cents to 1.60 cent lower with February at 50.32
cents a pound.
   The gains in hog futures extended a three-month advance from
prices near 40 cents a pound in mid-September.
   Cold weather typically supports the hog market for two reasons:
animals tend to burn energy rapidly in cold weather, causing weight
loss when they are moved around; and farmers, like everyone else,
tend to stay indoors in cold weather.
   ``People don't want to go out and sort their pens. It's too cold
to go out, period,'' said Dale Durchholz, a livestock analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc., a market advisory service in Bloomington,
Ill.
   Before the cold snap set in this week, hog prices were boosted
by a seasonal surge in wholesale demand for hams. Pork bellies
provided support before that amid speculation that Eastern Europe
would become a major market for U.S. pork bellies.
   ``A series of short-term factors continue to come along and push
it,'' Durchholz said. ``But if we see the weather moderate on us,
we'll probably see a pretty sharp break in the hog market.''
   Pork bellies fell sharply on profit-taking, giving up nearly all
of Wednesday's gains.
   Most grain and soybean futures rose on the Chicago Board of
Trade, paced by modest gains in the soybean market amid concerns
about new-crop supplies.
   Buying of corn, wheat and old-crop soybean futures was linked in
part to ideas that bitter cold in the Eastern United States would
lead to increased domestic livestock feeding.
   The new-crop soybean contracts _ those for delivery next fall _
posted the strongest gains, as they have for most of this week.
   Traders are speculating that U.S. farmers will plant fewer
soybeans in 1990 than this year and devote more acreage to corn,
wheat and cotton to take advantage of government-guaranteed prices
for those crops.
   Wheat futures settled 1 cent to 2\ cents higher with December at
$4.16\ a bushel; corn futures were { cent lower to 2 cents higher
with December at $2.35\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to \ cent
higher with December at $1.43} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to
3} cents higher with January at $5.82\ a bushel.
   Heating oil futures fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
ending an 11-day upswing.
   The selloff largely reflected profit-taking and analysts said
the bullish factors _ cold weather and shipping problems in Europe
_ remained in place.
   ``I think any setbacks are temporary,'' said William Hinton, a
broker with Stotler &amp; Co. in New York.
   Heating oil futures settled .45 cent to .84 cent lower with
January at 67.28 cents a gallon; West Texas Intermediate crude oil
was 5 cents to 12 cents lower with January at $20.65 a barrel;
unleaded gasoline was .11 cent to .35 cent lower with January at
51.61 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures were little changed while silver advanced slightly
on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 10 cents lower to 20 cents higher with December at
$408.30 a troy ounce; silver was 0.4 cent to 1.3 cents higher with
December at $5.557 a troy ounce.
   Platinum settled $6.40 to $6.60 higher on the New York Merc with
January at $511.30 a troy ounce. Analysts attributed the rally to
technical market factors.
</TEXT>
