<FIRST>u f AM-Argentina-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   12-14 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Bank Declares Bank Holiday Friday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 1-10 new with government order of bank holiday; picks
up 7th graf pvs, Argentines who</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Bank on Thursday
ordered banks and foreign exchange houses closed Friday in an
emergency holiday, evidently aimed at slowing an alarming loss of
confidence in the austral currency.
   The Central Bank gave no reason for the second bank holiday this
week, except to say it was ordered by the Economy Ministry. The
move was disclosed in a two-paragraph story on the state news
agency Telam late Thursday night.
   But the holiday follows the plunge of the austral against the
U.S. dollar since a 34.5 percent devaluation last Sunday as part of
an austerity program that included massive hikes in public service
rates, export taxes and the suspension of repayment of some
government debts. Banks and foreign exchange houses were ordered
closed thispast Monday because of the devaluation.
   Monthly interest rates soared Thursday to 43 percent for large
depositors, up from about 30 percent the day before and 17 percent
last week.
   ``I know I have lost some credibility, but I will remain in the
Economy Ministry until the president decides otherwise,'' said
embattled Economy Minister Nestor Rapanelli.
   Earlier in the day, President Carlos Menem acknowledged there
may be a political price to pay for the economic disorder and the
unpopular austerity measures he implemented this week.
   ``There is flinching and protests when you put in the scalpel to
draw out puss from a wound and it hurts,'' Menem said in an
interview with Radio Argentina. ``There is no other way out of this
situation without some political cost.''
   A recent survey by Radio de Plata indicated Menem's popularity
has waned since he took office last July. Unions are threatening to
strike for wage hikes, and businesses have ignored government pleas
to hold down prices.
   Newspapers in the capital have speculated for days that
Rapanelli will be forced out. Menem, however, insisted that his
economics minister enjoys his ``absolute confidence.''
   Menem also said the controversial program of privatizations and
deregulation will proceed, and the 34.5 percent devaluation and 60
percent and higher hikes in public service rates were unavoidable.
   Argentines who wanted to buy dollars paid 1,560 australs apiece
at the close of the business day, or 14.7 percent more than on
Wednesday and 56 percent more than the official rate, set last
Sunday, of 1,000-1.
   ``There is a lack of confidence in the economic plan,'' said
Ramiro Taboada, a manager at the Bank of Buen Ayre.
   Also, banks and other large investors were buying dollars and
forcing down the austral as a ``a kind of vengeance'' against the
government for suspending for two years the repayment of principal
on dollar-denominated, internal bonds, Toboada said.
   Alfredo Piano, head of the large foreign exchange company that
bears his name, said small investors were simply trying to protect
their money against inflation. ``People are fleeing the austral and
taking refuge in something they consider more solid,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
