<HEAD>Energy Futures Weaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures weakened Thursday with prices of
wholesale home heating oil taking the biggest tumble.
   The contract for January delivery of No.2 heating oil dropped
0.68 cent to 67.28 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, wiping out the 0.66-cent gain registered Wednesday.
Contracts for delivery during February through April fell by
amounts ranging from 0.70 cent to 0.84 cent.
   The slide in the January heating oil contract ended an 11-day
string of consecutive increases. Analysts said the downturn was
caused by a slump in prices in London for gasoil, the equivalent of
U.S. heating oil.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 12 cents to $20.65 per 42-gallon
barrel. The February through April contracts ended 9 cents to 11
cents lower.
   Among other refined oil products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which fell 0.10
cent on Wednesday, lost another 0.32 cent and closed at 51.61 cents
a gallon. Other contracts also closed lower.
