<FIRST>u f AM-PinnacleWest-PacifiCorp     12-14 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pinnacle West-PacifiCorp,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinnacle West Rejects PacifiCorp Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGER SANDAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pinnacle West Capital Corp. ended weeks of
speculation Thursday by announcing it had turned down an
``opportunistic attempt'' by an Oregon-based holding company to buy
Arizona's largest corporation.
   PacifiCorp on Dec. 1 proposed swapping stock to acquire Pinnacle
West in a deal valued at about $1.87 billion. The bid, which was
conditioned upon Pinnacle West's disposing of ailing subsidiary
MeraBank, was an expansion of a Nov. 8 bid by PacifiCorp to buy
Arizona Public Service Co. for $1.7 billion. APS is a wholly-owned
subsidiary of Pinnacle West and is Arizona's largest utility.
   ``The board unanimously determined that PacifiCorp's proposal is
inadequate and not in the best interests of Pinnacle West and its
shareholders,'' Pinnacle West Chairman Keith Turley said in a
letter to PacifiCorp President A.M. Gleason.
   Turley's letter continued, ``In reaching these conclusions the
board has carefully considered the business, financial condition
and future prospects of Pinnacle West and its subsidiaries
including Arizona Public Service Co. and MeraBank.''
   Mike Nelson, director of financial planning and investor
services for PacifiCorp, said in Portland, Ore., that PacifiCorp
executives were disappointed by the rejection.
   ``I think they're just reacting to the increase in their stock
price this week and last week and at this point, they're not
willing to sit down and talk to us,'' he said of Pinnacle West.
   Pinnacle West's stock nearly doubled Dec. 7, jumping 4~ to 10\,
after the company announced a settlement with federal thrift
regulators concerning MeraBank. The settlement required Pinnacle
West to infuse MeraBank with $450 million.
   Nelson said Turley's letter was the first reaction PacifiCorp
had received to either of its offers.
   In contrast to the silence with which he'd met the much
publicized offer, Turley commented Thursday on the Portland-based
holding company's bid, calling it ``an opportunistic attempt by
PacifiCorp to enhance value for its shareholders at the expense of
our shareholders.''
   He said Pinnacle West's board of directors ``firmly believes
that the best course for Pinnacle West and its shareholders is to
continue our program to resolve the MeraBank issues and build value
for shareholders as an independent company.''
   The Pinnacle West board acted on the opinion of advisers First
Boston Corp. and Salomon Brothers Inc. that the proposal was
``inadequate from a financial point of view,'' Turley said.
Pinnacle West had hired the two investment banking companies to
study the bid.
   Turley concluded the letter by informing Gleason that ``no
purpose would be served'' by future talks between the two companies.
   PacifiCorp's Nelson declined to speculate whether Pinnacle West
was implying PacifiCorp should sweeten its proposal.
   ``I don't know if there's anything between the lines in his
letter in terms of other messages,'' he said.
   As for PacifiCorp's next move, he said: ``We're evaluating that
right now. We don't have any comments on what our plans are as of
yet.
   The rejection was ``not unexpected because at this point the
offer isn't good enough'' given Pinnacle West's stock price, said
Marcia Weeks, a member of the Arizona Corporation Commission, which
regulates APS.
   The commission has scheduled a Monday hearing on the APS
dividend matter.
   A high priority at that hearing will be Pinnacle West's deal
with federal thrift regulators to infuse MeraBank with $300 million
in cash within four months. Pinnacle West also has promised a note
for $150 million spread out over the next 12 years. Pinnacle West
borrowed the cash from four New York firms, using APS stock as
collateral.
</TEXT>
