<SECOND>BC-Hunt Bankruptcy,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creditors Group Reaches Settlement in Hunt Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major group of creditors who lost money in the
1979-80 silver market crash has reached a settlement in the Hunt
brothers' bankruptcy case, officials said.
   The settlement is subject to bankruptcy court approval, but
paves the way for confirmation of the bankruptcy cases of William
Herbert Hunt and Nelson Bunker Hunt. Confirmation hearings begin
Friday.
   A group of more than 500 creditors with smaller claims against
the Hunts had threatened to challenge an alliance of the two
bankruptcy cases' largest creditors.
   Under the proposed settlement, some 500 smaller creditors who
suffered trading losses when the Hunts allegedly tried to corner
the world's supply of silver would receive about $9 million of the
$220 million they originally lost when the market crashed.
   ``I'd be optimistic that the cases will be confirmed since all
the significant creditor groups now support the plan,'' Robert
Brousseau, attorney for the silver claimants, told The Dallas
Morning News.
   The brothers' estates have been under Chapter 11 federal
bankruptcy protection since September 1988.
</TEXT>
